<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-89 0614EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>d e BC-Dance     04-21 0292</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Dance,0304</SECOND>
<HEAD>Paul Taylor Dance Co. Has Delightful Premiere</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: No PMs Planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After three stimulating dances, the Paul Taylor
Dance Company concluded its Thursday night program at the City
Center with the premiere of the delightful, light-hearted, funny
``Minikin Fair.''
   The music sounded like a circus and the dancers, in baggy
leotards with scanty coverups added, became amateur circus
performers. They somersaulted in twos, the men groaning when
attempting to lift the women. A virtuoso in a bathing cap tumbled;
he made it look like diving.
   A ``faerie king and queen,'' Christopher Gillis and Mary Cochran
replacing the injured Kate Johnson, had a dance which appeared to
be based on ballet's bluebird pas de deux. But she slipped out of
his grasp. There is nothing funnier to a dance audience than
parodies of ballet.
   One dancer was in a collapsible green pipe, forcing him to crawl
like an insect. Three women in petal dresses got chains of flowers
caught in the petals as they danced. A couple inside the same
garment seemed to be skating. A woman juggled three scarves.
   ``Minikin Fair'' followed a brief, funny dance, ``3 Epitaphs,''
from 1956. That one, to a recording of ragged early New Orleans
jazz, has five people apparently covered in mud. They come out of
the ooze, shake their flippers or scratch like monkeys, then slouch
offstage, presumably back into the ooze, deciding against evolution
after all.
   The evening began with ``Syzygy,'' which presents perpetual
motion and in which Linda Kent was fabulous, and ``Dust,'' which
has a leader of the blind going blind, in one section.
   Paul Taylor choreographed everything. The company will be at the
City Center through May 7.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
