<FIRST>r i PM-EcologistMovie     04-21 0806</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ecologist Movie,0829</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wife Dispute Threatens Movie About Slain Brazilian Ecologist</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TODD LEWAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A legal struggle to decide who is
the wife of the slain hero-ecologist Francisco ``Chico'' Mendes
could thwart efforts of international filmmakers to make a movie of
his life.
   Eunice Feitosa de Menezes, who claims to be Mendes' first and
only legal wife, has asked a court in Acre, his home state, to
confirm her marital status so she can contest any film rights
allotted the recognized widow, Ilzamar Mendes.
   Mendes, 44, a rubber tappers union leader who fought to save the
Amazon from deforestation, was killed by the son of a cattle
rancher Dec. 22 outside his modest wooden house in Xapuri, 2,666
miles northwest of Rio de Janeiro.
   Mendes had won a United Nations award for his struggle against
Amazon ranchers wanting to clear the rain forests for grazing.
   Hollywood producers, seeing dramatic value in a story about a
confrontation between powerful Amazon landowners and humble rubber
tree tappers, have been turning up in Brazil to see about shooting
a movie about Mendes, regarded by many as the world's first
environmental martyr.
   Gilson Pescador, a member of the Chico Mendes Foundation, said
offers have come from Robert Redford, representing 20th Century
Fox, from United Artists, Paramount Pictures, Warner Bros. Inc.,
Ted Turner from Atlanta, and a number of British and Brazilian film
companies.
   For the moment, the decision on who will get the authorized film
rights, along with cooperation from Mendes' Brazilian colleagues,
lies with a four-member panel from the foundation, an organization
made up of ecologists, rubber tappers and Mendes' family members.
   But panel members are concerned that a court battle pitting
Eunice Menezes against Ilzamar Mendes could discourage film
producers and scuttle the project, said Pescador.
   He and other foundation members say Menezes and her lawyer are
backed by the right-wing Rural Democratic Union, a powerful group
of landowners that rubber tappers and local Roman Catholic leaders
allege took part in the Mendes shooting.
   ``This is an underhanded attempt by the Rural Union to descredit
Chico and demoralize our movement to save the forest,'' Pescador
said in an interview. ``The Rural Union fears the movie will make
Chico an even greater hero than he is now.''
   The Rural Union denies the accusations.
   Also at stake is the money the project would bring to the rubber
tappers, estimated at more than $300,000, Pescador said.
   ``We need economic resources to continue our work,'' he added.
``The movement is in a delicate stage after Chico's death, and our
opponents know it.''
   The Rural Union, which spent millions of dollars in a successful
lobby effort to water down land reform clauses in Brazil's new
constitution, says it doesn't oppos a Chico Mendes movie.
   ``If the film shows what really happened with dignity and is
backed up with official evidence presented in court, we would
welcome such a production,'' Roosevelt dos Santos, president of the
Rural Union, said by telephone from Brasilia, the capital.
   But Mary Helena Alegretti, a member of the Mendes Foundation
panel, charged that the landowners' group had sought out Menezes
and her daughter with other motives.
   ``The Rural Union is trying to show the world that Chico wasn't
such a good, innocent boy after all,'' she said.
   ``All I know is that I was married to Chico,'' Ilzamar Mendes
told The Associated Press, maintaining that she married him in Acre
in 1983.
   But Menezes' lawyer, Norival Valadao, who has defended Rural
Union cattle ranchers in numerous cases against squatters,
ecologists and the rubber tappers, said Mendes never divorced
Menezes, thus invalidating his marriage to Ilzamar.
   Valadao said he had the certificate from Mendes' church wedding
to Menezes, the baptism certificate of his first child by Menezes,
and the index of a town hall register documenting the marriage.
   ``The page listing Mendes' wedding was torn out,'' he said.
``But I still have enough evidence to serve justice and annul his
second marriage.''
   Pescador said, ``There is not one document proving that this
woman was married to Chico.'' But he conceded that Menezes was the
mother of Mendes' 20-year-old daughter, Angela Maria.
   Alegretti said Angela Maria would be considered a Mendes family
member when it came time to divide the family's share of film
rights.
   Ilzamar Mendes, her two children and Mendes' brother and sisters
would receive 15 percent of the royalties. Another 15 percent would
be donated to the rubber tappers union and other such organizations
in Acre. The remainder would go to education and health projects
for Indians and rubber tappers throughout the Amazon, Alegretti
said.
   ``No one here is trying to get rich on these projects,'' she
said. ``We're doing it to get Chico's message out. That's what he
would have wanted.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
