<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-89 0148EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-FallSurvivor     04-21 0343</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fall Survivor,0355</SECOND>
<HEAD>Survivor Says Fall Won't Make Him Scared Of Heights</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY COATES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alvin Glaze fell off the top of a
180-foot tower and lived to tell about it _ if he could just
remember.
   ``I don't remember a thing about the fall,'' said Glaze, head of
a tower maintenance crew for the state Office of Forestry. ``The
doctors say it might be psychological. It's just as good I don't
remember.''
   The 47-year-old Glaze suffered no broken bones, no internal
injuries.
   ``I got a bunch of deep cuts and bruises and the meat's tore
from my hands from grabbing those wires,'' he said Thursday from
his hospital bed.
   Glaze was dismantling a microwave tower from the old forestry
headquarters Tuesday when he fell from the top. Other workers said
the fall was cushioned because Glaze grabbed two different guy
wires which turned the fall into a wild slide.
   ``All I know is the chances of me thinking about grabbing any
wires are too great,'' Glaze said. ``I try to live by the Lord, and
I believe he did it for me.''
   Dale Singleton, who was 40 feet below Glaze, said Glaze dropped
10 feet to the first guy wire and slid along it for about 40 feet.
   At that point, Singleton said, Glaze reached out and grabbed a
second wire, hooked his leg over, and rode the wire to the ground.
   He said he couldn't believe his boss was alive on the ground.
   ``He sat up, looked at his hands and said, `I'm all right,'''
said Singleton.
   The triangular tower is supported by three sets of wires and
Glaze used the bottom two to break the fall.
   Glaze said as soon as he gets back to his Leesville home, ``I'm
going to hug my family and make some of my own coffee. I don't like
this instant coffee at the hospital.''
   And he'll climb again?
   ``I've got a strong will, and I'm the kind of person who'll
master it again,'' he said.
</TEXT>
