<FIRST>u i AM-Philippines-Shooting 8thLd-Writethru   04-21 0642</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Philippines-Shooting, 8th Ld-Writethru,a0407,0660</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gunmen Kill U.S. War Hero Who Escaped From Viet Cong</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 12 grafs to UPDATE with officials suspect rebels
responsible for slaying, victim shot in head, details. Picks up graf 10
pvs, `Toto Austria ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN GUERRERO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hooded gunmen killed an American
military officer and Vietnam War hero Friday as he was driving to
work at the Joint U.S. Military Advisory Group headquarters, U.S.
and Filipino officials said.
   U.S. Embassy spokesman Jerry Huchel said Army Col. James N.
Rowe, 51, of McAllen, Texas, was pronounced dead on arrival at a
Philippine military hospital, and his body was flown to Clark Air
Base, 50 miles north of Manila.
   While no group claimed responsibility, a senior Filipino officer
said investigators believed the killers were Communist rebels.
   Rowe, who was shot in the head, was held prisoner by the Viet
Cong from 1963 until he escaped in 1968. He wrote a book about the
ordeal entitled ``Five Years to Freedom.''
   Friends of Rowe's in the U.S. diplomatic community said he was
to have addressed the U.S. Embassy's women's club on Wednesday
about his experiences in Vietnam. He is survived by a wife and two
young children, the friends said on condition of anonymity.
   Col. Victor Tiangco of the Philippine military's Capital Region
Command said Rowe was chief of the army division at the Joint U.S.
Military Advisory Group, which provides training and logistical
support for the Filipino army.
   He said Rowe's Filipino chauffeur, Joaquin Vinuya, was wounded
in the shooting but was reported out of danger.
   Tiangco said assailants wearing hoods opened fire with M-16
rifles as Rowe's car approached the group compound in suburban
Quezon City about 7:10 a.m. Tiangco said 21 bullets struck the car.
   Police said at least three people were in the assailants' car,
at least two of whom were gunmen and one a driver. One gunman had
an M-16 and another had a .45 caliber pistol, they said.
   Tiangco said the assailants sped away. Witnesses said Rowe's car
was able to reach the compound, about two blocks from the shooting.
   Col. Manuel Oxales, deputy chief of the National Capital Region
Defense Command, said Communist rebels were suspected because of
the weapons and style of the attack. Oxales said Rowe was struck in
the head.
   Oxales said the preliminary investigation indicated three cars
may have been used in the attack, although most witnesses said they
saw gunmen firing from only one.
   Toto Austria, a cashier at a gasoline station, said he heard
shots and turned to see a white car pull alongside Rowe's
silver-gray vehicle with tinted windows.
   As the cars turned right along a traffic circle, Austria said he
saw one M-16 rifle extending from the window and firing at the
other vehicle. He said Rowe's car turned toward the military
compound and the assailants followed, continuing to fire.
   The assailants' car then made a U-turn and sped away.
   There was no indication as to who staged the attack or why.
   In October 1987, communist rebels killed three Americans and a
Filipino of U.S. descent in simultaneous attacks near Clark Air
Base.
   The rebels have threatened more attacks against Americans
because of U.S. support for President Corazon Aquino's
counterinsurgency campaign. U.S. officials, speaking on condition
of anonymity, said any future attacks would probably be directed
against soldiers assigned to the advisory group.
   On April 9, rebels blasted a U.S. military communications in
Benguet province. No one was injured, but U.S. officials asked that
security around American installations be tightened.
   Rowe's book, published in 1971, details the disease and
psychological and physical torment he endured as a Viet Cong
prisoner.
   After his release, he was chief of the Army's Survival, Evasion,
Resistance and Escape Training, which also included training in
anti-terrorism techniques, based in North Carolina.
</TEXT>
