<DOCNO> AP890421-0018 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-89 0207EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Fidel'sAgent Bjt   04-21 0748</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fidel's Agent, Bjt,730</SECOND>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON TODAY: Castro's Man in Washington Going Home After 12
Years</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   He is perhaps the longest serving chief of
diplomatic mission in Washington but his name has been
conspicuously absent from State Department invitation lists for
years.
   He came here in the summer of 1977 with high hopes for a more
congenial relationship between his government and the United States
but is going home in a few days with the atmosphere worse now than
when he arrived.
   For Ramon Sanchez Parodi, being Fidel Castro's agent in
Washington has not been an easy task.
   Much of his tenure has overlapped with the era of conservative
Republican dominance in Washington, a time when kind words for
Castro have been as rare as frost in Havana in July.
   But Sanchez Parodi has acquired a reputation here as a no
apologies defender of his country's leader and its revolution.
   For starters, don't try to convince him about the merits of
``Western values.'' He told a gathering at a local university the
other day that to Cuba, ``Western values'' means centuries of
Spanish colonial rule, decades of American neo-colonial rule and a
capitalist system that left millions of Cubans in misery.
   ``We don't want to have anything to do with these values,'' he
said, his mastery of English reflecting his long stay here.
   He believes the strain in relations with the United States has
damaged American interests. Cuba could help the United States curb
drug trafficking and environmental pollution but Washington has
been unwilling to enlist Cuba's cooperation, he said.
   The absence of a more normal relationship, he said, is the
result of Washington's refusal to accept Cuba ``as a sovereign and
independent nation.''
   Sanchez Parodi assumed his duties here on Sept. 1, 1977, ending
a 16-year period in which diplomatic contact between the United
States and Cuba was a rarity.
   When he arrived to open a small Cuban diplomatic mission here,
there were champagne toasts. The Carter administration was young
and was giving high priority to promoting a more normal
relationship with Cuba.
   Sanchez Parodi thought that full diplomatic relations could be
restored in two or three years.
   But one setback followed another. President Carter's national
security adviser, Zbigniew Brzezinski, was never enthusiastic about
detente with Castro, and he worked behind the scenes to head off
that possibility, according to officials familiar with that period.
   There were myriad other irritants during the Carter years: the
dispatch of Cuban troops to Ethiopia, a flap over a Soviet military
brigade in Cuba, and the arrival in Florida of more than 125,000
Cubans _ including many who were criminals or mentally ill _ aboard
the Mariel boat lift in 1980.
   With the advent of the Reagan administration, Sanchez Parodi
acquired almost pariah status, a reflection of the view of
then-Secretary of State Alexander M. Haig Jr. that Cuba was
responsible for leftist turmoil in Central America.
   There was a time at the end of 1981 that Sanchez Parodi feared
an American invasion of Cuba. That concern didn't materialize but
the administration in other ways tried to make life for Castro as
difficult as possible.
   It tightened the U.S. embargo against Cuba, forbade American
tourists from going there and encouraged allied countries _ with
some success _ to limit their dealings with Cuba.
   There was the U.S.-led invasion of Grenada, Cuba's main
supporter in the Caribbean, and the introduction of Radio Marti,
the VOA broadcast operation tailored for Cuban listeners.
   There were U.S. spy flights over Cuba and an intensive U.S.
campaign to call United Nations attention to alleged human rights
violations in Cuba. For a time, the U.S. representative in Cuba was
as much a social outcast in Havana as Sanchez Parodi was in
Washington.
   Even the arrival of a moderately less ideological administration
in Washington three months ago has not produced a breather in
relations.
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III saw to that by sending
diplomatic posts a memo last month asserting that an improvement in
relations with Cuba is not possible until Cuba ends its
``unacceptable behavior.''
   Now Sanchez Parodi is returning to Havana, having been promoted
to the post of vice foreign minister. Once installed there, he may
have a hand in shaping Cuba's response to Washington's latest
proposed innovation for the island _ a television version of Radio
Marti.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   George Gedda has covered foreign affairs for The
Associated Press since 1968.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
