<FIRST>u i AM-Namibia 2ndLd-Writethru   04-21 0424</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Namibia, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0804,0434</SECOND>
<HEAD>Battle Breaks Out, Three Guerrillas Reported Dead</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with three grafs to UPDATE with three guerrillas reported
dead, details. Picks up graf 4 pvs, `Col. Richard ...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WINDHOEK, Namibia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three black nationalist guerrillas were
killed in a battle with South African-controlled forces in northern
Namibia in the first fighting reported this week, a territorial
official said Friday.
   Gerhard Roux, chief aide to Namibia Administrator-General Louis
Pienaar, gave the death toll for the Thursday afternoon battle
before flying north Friday on what he said was a routine trip.
   He said he had no more information about the clash.
   Col. Richard Warren, commander of Australian U.N. military
forces in northern Namibia, said the battle was reported to be
serious. He said it took place three to five miles from Okankolo,
which lies about 30 miles southeast of Ondangwa airbase, where Roux
was headed.
   Martti Ahtisaari, the special U.N. representative for Namibia,
was informed of the fighting, sources said.
   The United Nations forces in Namibia have set up assembly points
in the north for the guerrillas to report to and be transported
back across the border to Angola.
   But according to police and military reports, most of the
guerrillas who have left crossed the border on their own rather
than report to the assembly points or to church premises, which
also have been declared safe havens.
   The incursion by several hundred guerrillas from the South-West
African People's Organization, or SWAPO, across the border from
Angola on April 1 interrupted the implementation of a U.N. peace
plan intended to lead to independence elections in November.
   South Africa, which has ruled the territory for 74 years, had
agreed to the plan, which called for the orderly, unarmed return of
the guerrillas in mid-May from their bases in Angola and Tanzania.
   SWAPO guerrillas have been fighting since 1966 to end South
African control of the territory, which is also called South-West
Africa.
   In another development, a U.N. official said Thursday the United
Nations has completed an investigation into allegations of police
intimidation at a mission station in northern Namibia and has asked
the South African-appointed administrator of the territory to take
action.
   U.N. official Cedric Thornberry said the report by the U.N.
police commissioner, Steven Fanning, would not be made public.
   Residents of the area around Oshikuku, where some SWAPO
guerrillas had assembled for transport to Angola, had told church
officials and reporters that police threatened and harassed them in
an attempt to make them give information about guerrillas in the
area.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
