<FIRST>r a PM-MustardWar Bjt   04-21 0631</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mustard War, Bjt,0646</SECOND>
<HEAD>Baseball Fans Balk At Stadium Mustard Switch</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CD2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DWIGHT WOODWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Through good years and bad years, Cleveland
Indians' baseball fans have always had one thing they could count
on _ Cleveland Stadium's Famous Bertman Ball Park Mustard _ until
now.
   The Indians cut the mustard from the menu this spring, prompting
dismay from fans who have been defying chilly breezes off Lake Erie
to see the home team.
   ``I've been away from this town for 15 years and lived all over
the U.S., and I've told everybody that the best mustard in the U.S.
is in Cleveland,'' said Lee Snyder, 43, of Columbus. ``And now,
they tell me it's not the same mustard. It's like taking the brats
(bratwurst) out of Milwaukee.''
   But stomach grumbles apparently outweigh discontent.
   Laverne Schmotzer, general manager for Service America, the
concessionaire at the stadium, say fans this year have been eating
about 1{ hot dogs apiece per game, the same as usual.
   Attending an Indians game or Cleveland Browns football contest
and munching a hot dog topped with the tangy Bertman mustard has
been a tradition since Joe Bertman introduced the brown mustard at
ballgames in 1950.
   But when bids came in this February, Bertman's price was $2 more
per case than its Cleveland competitor, Authentic Stadium Mustard,
Ms. Schmotzer said. She said she decided to switch to Authentic
Stadium Mustard after tasters from the Indians' and Browns' staffs
said they couldn't tell the difference between the two mustards.
   ``There has been a feud between the two companies and every
year, they both say they have the best mustard,'' Ms. Schmotzer
said. ``The taste was so similar, we decided to go with a better
price.''
   But at least some of the fans attending Wednesday's game with
the Boston Red Sox think tradition is more important than money.
   Others said you have to pay for good taste.
   ``It's a little different but the taste is basically the same,''
Mike McGonega, 40, of suburban Bay Village said while eating a hot
dog. ``What makes everybody mad is that it was based on price. They
broke a tradition without asking anybody. Normally, I'm not an
opinionated guy, but on this, you've got to dig your heels in.''
   Larry Hammond, 33, of Jackson, Mich., said: ``I used to buy this
stuff by the jar. I don't know if I will after tasting this. It
tastes diluted. It's not as tangy.''
   Pat Bertman Mazoh, Joe Bertman's daughter, took over the mustard
and food distribution business after her father died. She says the
recent mustard switch at the stadium is just another skirmish in
``mustard wars'' with David Dwoskin, president of the Davis Food
Co. which distributes Authentic Stadium Mustard.
   In 1968, Dwoskin and Joe Bertman agreed that Dwoskin would sell
Bertman's Mustard to retailers and the mustard became available in
jars to shoppers.
   ``Bertman and I had a deal where he would continue selling the
mustard at the stadium. We were both buying the same mustard from a
Chicago plant,'' Dwoskin said.
   ``Up until 1982, we were Stadium Mustard,'' Mrs. Mazoh said.
``Then my father dreamed up `Ball Park' mustard.''
   Stadium Mustard is made in Chicago, while Bertman's is made in
southern Ohio, the mustard distributors said.
   Margaret Engel, co-author of ``Food Finds: America's Best Local
Foods and The People Who Produce Them,'' said Bertman's mustard was
included in their 1984 book, but a new edition of the book may
include both brands.
   ``No matter which company was selected, Cleveland is to be
commended for having two great mustards,'' Ms. Engel said from her
Bethesda, Md., home. ``Cleveland has always had mustard 10 levels
above other stadiums. Most ballparks have that horrible,
institutional, bright yellow tasteless glop.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
