<FIRST>r w PM-Honoraria     04-21 0509</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Honoraria,560</SECOND>
<HEAD>Interest Groups Target Fees to Lawmakers with Right Influence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The financial industry was the leader of 19
categories of special interest groups that paid honoraria to
senators from 1984 to 1987, a new study says.
   And eight of the top 10 Senate recipients of the money held
positions on committees that voted on issues affecting that
industry, according to report released Thursday by Public Citizen.
   The financial interests spent $1.3 million in honoraria during
1984-87, followed by the food and beverage industry, which spent
$1.1 million. The next group, educational institutions, paid more
than $663,000.
   Recipients of honoraria served on committees able to help the
giver. All the top 10 recipients of honoraria from the food
industry were on committees that voted on food issues.
   All together, senators received $9.5 million during the years
studied and kept $7.3 million, the difference going to charity so
members could comply with the Senate limits on honoraria.
   Republican senators received an average of $27,881 each year
compared with $22,005 for Democrats, the study said.
   Other contributors of honoraria were the health,
telecommunications, and transportation industries; builders and
developers; the energy and insurance industries; business advocacy
groups; the defense industry; ideological groups; law firms;
religious organizations; advertising firms; the computer and
chemical industries; utility companies; and publications that
bought articles.
   Public Citizen, which describes itself as a national consumer
and environmental advocacy organization founded by Ralph Nader,
entitled its honoraria report ``Who Pays The Piper.''
   Honoraria consist of payments for speeches, appearances and
articles. Senate rules allow senators to keep up to 40 percent of
their $89,500 salary _ or $35,800 in honoraria a year _ with the
rest given to charity.
   House members can keep honoraria totaling 30 percent of their
salary, or $26,850 annually. Payments to lawmakers in both houses
cannot exceed $2,000 for an individual speech or appearance.
   Lawmakers appeared willing earlier this year to do away with
honoraria in return for a pay raise that would at least offset the
loss. This supplemental income was left untouched, however, when
the pay raise collapsed under intense public pressure.
   The system is now under review by a special committee headed by
Reps. Vic Fazio, D-Calif. and Lynn Martin, R-Ill., and no action is
expected anytime soon.
   In unveiling new ethics proposals April 12, President Bush made
no recommendation on congressional honoraria, saying he wanted to
take it up at a future time in connection with a congressional pay
raise.''
   The report said Sen. Ernest Hollings, D-S.C., received the most
honoraria during the four-year period, totaling $308,934. Following
were Sens. Richard Lugar, R-Ind., with $266,685; Orrin G. Hatch
with $259,440; Minority Leader Bob Dole, R-Kan. with $254,849; and
Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y. with $235,894.
   Eleven senators in office during the four-year period did not
accept honoraria: Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas; Lawton Chiles, D-Fla.;
Dennis DeConcini, D-Ariz.; John Glenn, D-Ohio; Bob Graham, D-Fla.;
Frank Lautenberg, D-N.J.; Carl Levin, D-Mich.; Russell Long, D-La.;
Harry Reid, D-Nev.; Terry Sanford, D-N.C.; and John Stennis, D-Miss.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
