<FIRST>r w PM-FarmScene     04-21 0885</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Farm Scene,880</SECOND>
<HEAD>Farmland Values Head Upward Again</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Improved prospects for the nation's
agriculture have helped boost the value of farmland, but
Agriculture Department economists say the heady price levels of the
early 1980s are as yet but a dream.
   The department's Economic Research Service said Thursday that as
of Feb. 1 the average value of U.S. farmland, including buildings,
was $597 per acre, up 6 percent from about $564 on Feb. 1, 1988.
   It was the second consecutive annual increase. Farmland prices
sank to a 19-year low of $548 per acre on Feb. 1, 1987, before
gaining 3 percent last year.
   ``However, the 1989 value was still 27 percent below the record
$823 in 1982,'' the report said.
   Several factors were cited for the gain in farmland prices. Net
cash income of farmers in 1988 nearly matched the 1987 record, and
that buoyed confidence among prospective buyers that the
agricultural sector was working its way out of the crunch that
weighed on many farmers.
   Although producers hit by the 1988 drought experienced lower
crop yields, many grain producers, particularly those with
irrigation and those holding grain stocks from previous harvests,
benefited from sharply higher market prices, the report said.
   Federal drought aid also boosted farm receipts in 1988 and
helped blunt the short-term impact. Higher cattle prices ``helped
expand cash receipts from livestock to record levels'' last year,
the report said.
   ``Values rose in all farm production regions except the Southern
Plains,'' the report said. ``Substantial gains in Pennsylvania,
Delaware and New Jersey led the 13 percent average (increase) in
the Northeast.''
   Although state average farmland prices were not immediately
available, the report said substantial gains also occurred in the
Corn Belt, up 10 percent, and the Northern Plains, 9 percent.
Further ``significantly higher'' values were reported in Iowa and
Nebraska.
   Land value increases in the Lake States, up 5 percent, and the
Southeast, up 7 percent, were said to be ``comparable to last
year,'' while a 6 percent increase in Appalachia was sharply higher
than the year before. A 3 percent increase in the value of farmland
in the Delta States was the first since 1981.
   ``Higher values in the Pacific region, 5 percent, and the
Mountain region, 1 percent, represented the first increases since
1984,'' the report said. ``The 5 percent drop in Texas more than
offset the 9 percent gain in Oklahoma, leading to an overall 2
percent decline for the Southern Plains.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Agriculture Department says it is making
progress in writing new federal regulations on making old-fashioned
country hams, a rule-making procedure that began more than six
years ago.
   But a final decision could take until the end of this year and
maybe longer, if the USDA's long history of delays is taken into
account.
   The country ham issue began in March 1983 when the department
initially proposed new safety rules for commercial processors. But
industry challenges, USDA tinkering and other hurdles kept pushing
back the rule-making deadline, which is currently Dec. 31, 1989.
   Country hams are most commonly found in cloth bags in
supermarkets and country stores, preserved by salt, smoke and air
for months and even years. They must be scraped, soaked and cooked
before being eaten.
   Most hams in supermarket meat counters are wet-cured quickly in
brine solutions and cooked before sale to consumers.
   In its latest move announced Thursday, the USDA proposes ``to
allow certain amounts of potassium chloride as an alternative to
salt'' in the curing of country hams to kill trichinae, microscopic
parasitic worms. If improperly cooked and eaten, infested meat can
cause a disease called trichinosis in humans.
   Lester M. Crawford, administrator of the department's Food
Safety and Inspection Service, said federal regulations currently
allow three curing methods for destroying trinchinae in ham. The
proposal modifies two of the methods and provides and additional
method.
   Crawford said the proposed new method would allow processors to
substitute potassium chloride for some of the sodium chloride _
salt _ in the curing mixture. Current rules call for a 4 percent
salt content to ensure safety of the ham.
   But research by North Carolina State University shows that some
substitution of potassium chloride can be allowed without
compromising safety, he said. A minimum salt content in the cure
mixture would be required, but up to half the weight could consist
of potassium chloride.
   The proposal also would eliminate the current ``method No. 2''
for destroying trichinae, which involves injecting a salt water
solution into the ham. Crawford said his agency believes this
method is no longer being used commercially.
   Public comments on the country ham proposal can be sent through
June 19 to: Policy Office, Attn: Linda Carey, FSIS Hearing Clerk,
Room 3171-S, FSIS, USDA, Washington, D.C. 20250.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two senior officials have been sworn in at the
Agriculture Department by their new boss, Agriculture Secretary
Clayton Yeutter.
   Oaths of office, following earlier Senate confirmation, were
administered Thursday to Jack C. Parnell, deputy secretary, which
is the No. 2 post at the department, and Richard T. Crowder, as
undersecretary for international affairs and commodity programs.
   Parnell had been director of the California state department of
food and agriculture, and Crowder was an executive with the
Pillsbury Company.
</TEXT>
