<FIRST>r w PM-DefenseCuts     04-21 0439</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Defense Cuts,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cheney Has List of Expected Cuts from Defense Budget</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Secretary Dick Cheney wants to cut the
Midgetman missile, attack submarines, new fighter jets, troop
transport planes and some funding for Star Wars from the 1990
budget, congressional sources say.
   Warren Nelson, an aide to the House Armed Services Committee,
said Thursday the cuts are in a draft report Cheney sent to the
military branches, but he warned the recommendations could change
in the final report.
   Cheney is making adjustments to the 1990 budget submitted by
former President Reagan in order to meet the goals of a budget
compromise worked out a week ago between the White House and
Congress. The agreement calls for spending $299.2 billion on
defense, which requires trimming $10 billion from the budget Reagan
submitted.
   Cheney is expected to present a package of cuts to Congress next
week.
   Nelson said Cheney's draft report called for the elimination of
funding for new F-14D Tomcat fighter jets, the V-22 Osprey troop
transport aircraft and the Midgetman missile as well as the last of
two submarines in the Los Angeles class.
   In addition, the preliminary report recommended slicing in half
funding for F-18 fighters, stretching out the purchasing plan for
the B-2 bomber, cutting funds for the Strategic Defense Initiative,
reducing various helicopter programs and decommissioning an
aircraft carrier.
   Rep. George Hochbrueckner, D-N.Y., said Cheney has ``kicked
upstairs'' to the White House decisions on what he described as the
most controversial cutback recommendations _ the F-14, the Los
Angeles class subs, Midgetman and the SDI reductions.
   ``Right now, the ball is in the White House court,''
Hochbrueckner said. He declined to reveal the source of his
information.
   The planned elimination of the two attack submarines already
spurred lobbying by lawmakers from the Eastern Seaboard. The subs
are made at the Electric Boat shipyard in Connecticut.
   Sen. John H. Chafee, R-R.I., a former Navy secretary, on
Thursday wrote a letter to Cheney that criticized any move to
eliminate the sub funding as ``short sighted in terms of our
national security requirements.''
   Chafee pointed to a recent independent report ordered by the
House Armed Services Committee that detailed major advances in
Soviet submarine technology.
   ``I hope you will agree that it would be a serious mistake for
the United States to curtail the SSN-688 program at this time,'' he
said.
   Congressional aides said the submarines were vulnerable to the
budget ax because they were scheduled to be the last two of the Los
Angeles class series. The Los Angeles series will be replaced by
the SSN-21 Seawolfs.
</TEXT>
