<FIRST>r w PM-MedicareSurcharge     04-21 0475</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Medicare Surcharge,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Advocates for Elderly Cheered by Surtax Projection</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENISE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Organizations representing the elderly say
they're encouraged about the prospects for a reduction in the
surtax paid for coverage of catastrophic illness under the Medicare
program.
   Sen. Lloyd Bentsen said Thursday that revised revenue estimates
from the Congressional Budget Office and the Joint Committee on
Taxation show that the government may be collecting more money than
it needs for the program. He said the new projections indicate a
$4.9 billion surplus for the period 1989-1993.
   Bentsen, who heads the Senate Finance Committee, said he sent a
letter to Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady asking whether the Bush
administration concurs with the revised revenue estimates.
   ``The Congressional Budget Office concludes that the surplus in
the catastrophic care funds is twice as large as originally
estimated; two times bigger than needed to provide adequate reserve
and contingency margins,'' Bentsen said.
   He suggested that the surtax could be cut ``at least 16
percent'' if the projections are accurate.
   The supplemental premium or surtax enacted in the Medicare
Catastrophic Coverage Act of 1988 is paid by Medicare recipients
whose federal income tax is at least $150 annually. The tax
increases according to income up to a ceiling of $800.
   Bentsen's letter said ``the cap on the supplemental premium
could be reduced to $500'' if the projections by CBO and the tax
panel are correct.
   Horace Deets, executive director of the American Association for
Retired Persons, said the organization was ``delighted to hear that
beneficiaries may pay less for the expanded Medicare coverage.''
   ``The biggest estimating difficulty we had is identifying how
the elderly are spread across the income levels,'' said Ronald
Pearlman, staff director for the tax panel, in explaining the new
figures.
   Bentsen and Pearlman emphasized that the figures were
preliminary. Pearlman added that the new estimates were not based
on current revenue collection or a change in the economy but
instead were based on the tax panel's use of different economic
models from those used during congressional debate before the
bill's passage last year.
   Since the beginning of the year when the law went into effect,
members of Congress have been flooded with mail from older
Americans objecting to the tax which the lawmakers and former
President Reagan agreed should be paid solely by beneficiaries of
the program.
   ``But it was never our intention that the beneficiaries pay more
than needed to operate this program in a prudent, responsible
fashion,'' said Bentsen.
   ``There are two reasons for us to interpret this as
encouraging,'' said Eric Shulman, legislative director for the
National Council of Senior Citizens.
   ``One is that hopefully this new revenue will yield tangible and
significant reduction in premiums. The other is that it may open
the door to some reconsideration of the financing mechanism,'' said
Shulman.
</TEXT>
