<FIRST>r w PM-Shoreham-NRC     04-21 0621</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Shoreham-NRC,630</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shoreham Wins License, Cuomo Vows Appeal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KIM I. MILLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Department of Energy is calling the
approval of a full-power operating license for the Shoreham nuclear
power plant perhaps the most important development for the nuclear
industry in a decade, but New York Gov. Mario Cuomo has vowed to
appeal the decision.
   The bitterly divided response came as the Nuclear Regulatory
Commission voted 4-0 on Thursday to award a full-power license to
the Long Island plant.
   ``The NRC's full-power license for Shoreham is an emblem of
hypocrisy,'' Cuomo said in a statement from Albany, N.Y. ``We will,
of course, appeal.''
   DOE, on the other hand, saw the development as a milestone,
because it marked the first time a plant has been licensed on the
basis of a utility-drawn evacuation plan, sidestepping the
opposition of local communities.
   ``The NRC's decision reaffirms its confidence not only in the
safety and viability of Shoreham, but in the entire U.S. nuclear
industry as well,'' Energy Secretary James D. Watkins said. ``If
put into operation, Shoreham could spur the recovery of the
industry from the erosion of public confidence that followed the
accident at Three Mile Island in 1979.''
   His department called the Shoreham license ``perhaps the most
important development for the nuclear industry in the United States
in the past decade.''
   But the license may prove to be only a symbol, since the Long
Island Lighting Co., which owns the 809-megawatt reactor, has
agreed not to turn up the power pending a vote by shareholders to
scrap the $5.5 billion plant.
   After the vote Thursday, NRC Chairman Lando Zech said the
commission had fulfilled its duties without regard to whether
Shoreham ever operates.
   ``Our responsibility as the Nuclear Regulatory Commission is to
review the application for a license and to determine whether that
application meets our requirements,'' Zech told reporters. ``We
have made such a determination.''
   Zech said the refusal of the state and local governments to
participate in emergency planning ``has been a challenge to this
commission.''
   Asked if he thought it was a waste that Shoreham might never
operate, Zech said, ``As the chairman of the regulatory commission,
that's not my responsibility. As an American citizen, I would call
it a waste.''
   The vote by LILCO shareholders, which must take place by June
15, will make or break a deal under which LILCO would sell Shoreham
to New York state for $1 in exchange for a decade of annual rate
increases. The state would then oversee the decommissioning and
dismantling of the plant that was once touted as the solution to
Long Island's energy shortages.
   Shoreham becomes the first U.S. nuclear plant to be licensed on
the basis of a utility-formulated emergency plan, rather than one
created by the state and local governments.
   LILCO was forced to draw up its own plan after the governments
of New York state, Suffolk County and the Town of Southampton
withdrew support for the plant, contending the zone around Shoreham
could not be safely evacuated. They cited Long Island's large
population and the dearth of roads leading away from the plant as
impediments.
   Rep. George Hochbrueckner, a Democrat whose district includes
Shoreham, called the license ``an insult to the people of Long
Island.''
   ``The people of Long Island are sick and tired of being bullied
by a pro-nuclear NRC,'' he said.
   But LILCO Vice President Joseph McDonnell hailed the license as
a ``prerequisite for establishing a national nuclear policy.''
   ``It's been a long and difficult road but I maintain the
full-power license decision says clearly and definitively that
Shoreham is a safe plant and that the politicians who opposed this
plant have been flat wrong,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
