<FIRST>r a PM-Wright-Wife     04-21 0385</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wright-Wife,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Speaker's Wife Speaks Out on Accusations</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Wright Probe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   House Speaker Jim Wright's wife kept no records of her work for
an investment company formed by the Wrights and another Texas
couple because it was a ``piddling little mom-and-pop operation,''
she said in interviews published today.
   ``We were all friends,'' Betty Wright told The Washington Post
in an interview published in today's editions. ``There was no
reason to document anything. I had some notes, but I don't know
where they are and they are probably thrown away by now.''
   In remarks published in today's New York Times, she said:
``There was no time clock and we were not keeping records. It was
just the four of us. We all trusted each other.''
   The speaker faces 69 allegations of House rules violations
brought by the ethics committee. Among the accusations is that Mrs.
Wright was paid for work she did not do for the investment firm,
Mallightco Inc.
   The 64-year-old Mrs. Wright, along with her husband, formed the
company with friends from Fort Worth, George and Marlene Mallick.
   She said it was just part of the business arrangement if Mallick
gave her the use of a condominium in Fort Worth or if he gave her a
Cadillac.
   ``I think it is unfair to criticize it because that is the way
George Mallick did business,'' she told the Times. ``That is the
way he operated. Other employees had condos and cars, he had a
fleet of cars. I certainly don't think he was funneling anything to
me. It was just part of the employment,'' she said.
   She said she has been unfairly portrayed as a domineering,
scheming wife who liked to spend money on expensive things and
coaxed her husband into politically risky financial ventures.
   ``Oh, well, they are making me a Nancy Reagan,'' she said. ``I
felt sorry for her when they did it to her. I don't know why they
ever started on me.''
   ``Neither Jim nor I ever intended to evade the law in any way,
shape or form,'' she told the Post. ``My God, he's been there for
30 years. Why all of a sudden would he do a shady thing like that?
He wouldn't jeopardize his career over a piddling little
mom-and-pop operation. ''
</TEXT>
