<FIRST>r w PM-HepatitisTest     04-21 0526</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hepatitis Test,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>California Company Develops Test For Blood-Borne Hepatitis</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   California scientists have developed a test
that they say can detect a virus thought to cause 90 percent of all
hepatitis disease spread by blood transfusions.
   ``The advent of the specific, sensitive test ... should improve
the safety of the world's blood supply as well as provide an
important clinical diagnostic tool,'' said a report in this week's
edition of the journal Science, released today.
   Scientists at the Chiron Corp. in Emeryville, Calif., report in
one article on experiments that have characterized the antibodies
to the virus causing a type of hepatitis called non-A, non-B. It is
thought to infect up to 10 percent of all blood transfusions.
   Type non-A, non-B is so named because it was of an unknown
origin. The Chiron researchers have now labeled it hepatitis C or
HCV.
   The scientists report in a second article in the same journal
that they developed a screening test that was able to successfully
detect antibodies to the disease, thus providing a method of
testing blood transfusions for the presence of the virus.
   Hepatitis is an infectious disease that attacks the liver.
Though most patients with hepatitis recover with few lingering
effects, the disease can cause serious and sometimes fatal
complications. It can lead to cirrhosis, a hardening and gradual
failure of the liver that can cause death. The disease also has
been associated with liver cancer.
   To verify the HCV screening test, the researchers analyzed coded
blood samples from 16 patients. The patients included nine who were
proven by other tests to have hepatitis C, five normal blood
donors, a patient with alcoholic hepatitis, and a patient with
biliary cirrhosis, a liver disease.
   The Chiron assay detected hepatitis C antibodies in all but two
of those infected with the disease.
   Next, the researchers tested the 138 blood donations that had
been given to 10 patients who later developed chronic hepatitis C.
With only one exception, the tests found hepatitis C infection in
at least one blood donor for each of the blood transfusion
recipients. This showed the test could successfully screen donated
blood and identify those samples that were infected. Hepatitis C
antibodies were not detected in a control group of blood samples
tested at the same time.
   A further test was conducted on samples obtained from patients
in Italy and in Japan. The antibodies were detected in 84 percent
of the Italian patients who had been diagnosed with the hepatitis
infection. For the Japanese patients, 78 percent were found to be
positive for chronic infection, and 15 percent with acute
infection, a less serious condition that is healing.
   Chiron Corp. researchers, led by Qui-Lim Choo and G. Kuo, were
the lead scientists in the study, but the Science articles also
credit researchers at the Centers for Disease Control, the UCLA
School of Medicine, the University of Southern California, the
National Institutes of Health, Massachusetts General Hospital in
Boston, the New York Blood Center, the Community Blood Center of
Kansas City, and two groups of researchers from Italy.
   Science is the journal of the American Association for the
Advancement of Science.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
