<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-89 0412EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-OklahomaCentennial     04-21 0534</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Oklahoma Centennial,0549</SECOND>
<HEAD>Observance Of Land Run Centennial Climaxes In Guthrie</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GIL BROYLES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GUTHRIE, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A century after this sleepy railway stop
emerged from the prairie as a teeming tent city, crowds again are
converging on this historic territorial capital.
   On April 22, 1889, more than 40,000 anxious settlers toed the
borders of 2 million acres of unassigned lands to claim 160-acre
farms or town lots.
   They came by train, on horseback and on foot, in wagons and on
bicycles, pushing carts and driving oxen to one of the nation's
last frontiers.
   This weekend, organizers of centennial observances in Guthrie
say they are preparing for traffic jams when up to 100,000 people
show up for parades, re-enactments, rodeos and other events in the
central Oklahoma community of 10,300.
   The ``Run of '89,'' the first of five land runs used to settle
land in the former Indian Territory, marked the first white
settlement in what would become the 46th state in 1907.
   Although some Indian groups are participating, others object to
the festivities.
   ``We're in the ghetto while the people who stole our land are
enjoying prosperity,'' said Francis Wise, a member of an
organization of groups calling itself the Tribal Voices coalition.
   ``In all the festivities where Indians are included throughout
this land run celebration, we're being asked to put on feathers and
dance and sing and help the white community celebrate the land
run,'' she said. ``They're asking us to dance on the graves of our
people.''
   Historians say there is little argument that the government
cheated Indians out of their land in Oklahoma. Organizers of
centennial observances say they have tried to be sensitive to
Indian concerns.
   After the Civil War, cowboys drove cattle from Texas to Kansas
over the Chisholm Trail through Oklahoma until a railroad connected
Gainesville, Texas, and Arkansas City, Kan., in 1887.
   Guthrie and the future Oklahoma City became minor rail stops on
that line.
   The focus of the yearlong series of celebrations and tourism
promotion efforts is the historic district of Guthrie, where 40
blocks of Victorian buildings recall the years Guthrie served as
territorial and state capital.
   Both Guthrie, on Cottonwood Creek, and Oklahoma City to the
south along the Santa Fe Railroad tracks were born full-grown on
that single day in 1889 _ each with an estimated overnight
population of more than 10,000.
   Guthrie became the territorial capital, graced with fine
architecture of the period and a bustling downtown. It served as
the state capital until 1910, when the state seal moved to Oklahoma
City in what Guthrie residents still consider a case of theft.
   Oklahoma City continued to grow into a city of more than
400,000, while Guthrie stayed much as it was. But such lack of
growth has turned into an asset.
   ``By the town almost being forgotten for a number of years, it
preserved the history and the heritage,'' said Carol Ringrose, a
spokeswoman for the local centennial observance.
   In 1975, 1,400 acres of Guthrie was placed in the National
Register of Historic Places. Nearly half of the 4,700 homes in the
town are certified Victorian. Restorations aim at making the city a
living museum.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890421-0037 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-89 0250EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-WinerySlayings-Confession Bjt   04-21 0659</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Winery Slayings-Confession, Bjt,0682</SECOND>
<HEAD>Salcido: I Woke Up And Decided To Kill My Wife And Children</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANITA SNOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A California winery worker has told Mexican
officials he decided to kill his family the day after he came home
to find his children alone and his wife out late on what he thought
was a tryst.
   Following that confession, Ramon Salcido asked the officials to
return him to the United States to be tried for seven murders.
   ``He was very passive. Like he was talking about the most normal
thing in the world,'' Fernando Arias, spokesman for the Federal
Attorney General's Office, said Thursday.
   Later Thursday, Salcido was flown back to California.
   As he was being deported, Salcido told a U.S. television field
producer that he had no regrets for his murderous rampage.
   Arias gave this account of Salcido's confession to Mexican
authorities on Wednesday:
   Salcido said his anger began to build about 4 p.m. on April 13
when he returned home from his job at a winery in Sonoma County,
Calif., to find his three little girls alone.
   Depressed and wondering about his wife, Angela Richards, the
28-year-old forklift operator said he left his children and went to
local bar for a few beers. When he returned home, Ms. Richards
still was not there, he said.
   Salcido said his wife arrived late that evening and he accused
her of having an affair with fellow winery worker Tracy Toovey.
   He had long suspected the two of being romantically involved,
and said he and his wife had had marital problems ever since they
wed in December 1984.
   When Salcido awoke early on the morning of April 14, the killing
began.
   First, he said, he killed his wife, shooting her three times
while his daughters slept. Then he drove to the Grand Cru winery
and shot Toovey to death, Salcido said.
   Next, he went to the home of his mother-in-law, Marian Louise
Richards, 47. He said he thought she knew and approved of the
alleged affair.
   Salcio said he killed her and her two young daughters, Ruth, 12,
and Marie, 8.
   Then he went home, he said, and slashed the throats of his
daughters. He killed Sofia, 4, and Teresa, 1, but only wounded
2-year-old Carmina.
   Salcido said he headed immediately for the Mexican border. He
left his car behind and entered Mexico without identification and
with little cash. He said he took a bus to a small town east of his
hometown of Los Mochis in northwestern Mexico and spent three days
with his grandmother.
   He said he told her of the killings and the two cried together.
   He called his mother to tell her he might never see her again.
   Early Wednesday morning, federal agents picked up Salcido
outside Los Mochis. The attorney general's office said he was
riding a bus when he was arrested at a roadblock set up by drug
agents outside the village of Guasave.
   Authorities flew Salcido to the Pacific Coast resort of
Mazatlan, where he confessed to federal agents and in an interview
broadcast on national Mexican television.
   ``I'm guilty,'' he said in the interview. ``I did the killings
in the United States and I expect to be judged there.''
   He was flown to Mexico City on Thursday and deported to the
United States aboard a private jet provided to Sonoma County
authorities by ``Peanuts'' cartoonist Charles Schulz.
   Salcido was shackled to another man at the rear of the Mexicana
airlines plane that brought him to Mexico City, said George
Ramirez, a field producer with KRON-TV in San Francisco.
   ``He was very tense. He was always moving his head around,
looking,'' said Ramirez, who was on the flight. Ramirez said he had
a brief conversation in English with Salcido.
   When asked if he had any regrets, Salcido replied, ``No.''
   When asked if he had anything to say to his daughter who
survived, Salcido also replied, ``No.''
</TEXT>
