<HEAD>Slaying Fugitive Sought Refuge in Mexican Home</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Winery Slayings-Confession, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Jesus is cq, 4th graf</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS MOCHIS, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ramon Salcido left Mexico as a
teen-ager in search of a better life in the United States. When his
dream turned into a bloody nightmare, he sneaked home a fugitive.
   The California winery worker's desperate flight following the
April 14 slayings of his wife, two of his daughters and four other
people ended with his arrest on the hot coastal plains of
northwestern Mexico.
   Mexican authorities say Salcido was captured early Wednesday
when drug agents stopped the bus he was riding in at a roadblock
outside Guasave, a village 50 miles east of Los Mochis, his
hometown.
   He told authorities he visited his 74-year-old grandmother,
Jesus Armendariz, and wept with her.
   A neighbor, Gildaro Gutierrez, said soldiers raided the
grandmother's modest home Wednesday in a farming hamlet near
Guasave.
   He said four pickup trucks and an automobile loaded with
soldiers and plainclothes agents pulled up at 1 a.m. and took away
Salcido's uncle. The convoy returned again a half-hour later, but
quickly left, Gutierrez said.
   He said he didn't know Salcido and had seen no strangers or
anything suspicious at Ms. Armendariz's house before the raid.
   Local reporters found a cot inside a shed adjoining the house
and several pieces of clothing, including a pair of U.S.-made boots.
   Ms. Armendariz's house is only three miles from a train station
on the rail line from the border city of Mexicali, where Salcido
also has relatives.
   A few days before his capture, Salcido, 28, telephoned his
mother, Valentina Bojorquez Armendariz.
   Neither Salcido's mother nor his grandmother were at home
Thursday and neighbors did not know where they had gone.
   Mrs. Bojorquez earlier told the local newspaper El Debate that
her son telephoned her the day of the killings.
   ``Mother, I have problems. I am going to kill myself. I am
calling you because it is the last time you will hear my voice,''
Mrs. Bojorquez said her son told her.
   She said Ramon, the eldest of her six children, left Los Mochis
when he was 16 to seek work in the United States.
   Mrs. Bojorquez, 49, said she could not believe her son had
killed his wife and two daughters, even though he had confessed. A
third daughter is recovering from a slashed throat.
   Mrs. Bojorquez said her son brought the family to visit her at
Christmas in 1987. It was the last time she saw him.
   ``Everything seemed normal. It seemed they lived happily,'' she
said.
</TEXT>
