<FIRST>r w PM-EPA-Rosenberg 1stLd-Writethru a0457 04-21 0250</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-EPA-Rosenberg, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0457,230</SECOND>
<HEAD>EPA Nomination Hits Snag in Senate</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS lede to recast; picks up 2nd graf pvs, Simpson, R-Wyo.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Alan Simpson is stalling President Bush's
choice to run the EPA's clean air and nuclear programs because
Simpson contends the nominee shows no understanding of the problem
of airborne radioactive dust from mining uranium and other minerals.
   Simpson, R-Wyo., on Thursday put a hold on the confirmation of
William Rosenberg, a real estate executive from Ann Arbor, Mich.,
using a parliamentary device.
   ``His interest is in resolving the problems,'' said Mary Kay
Hill, an aide to Simpson. ``He is certainly not trying to torpedo
an individual.''
   Simpson had asked Rosenberg to comment on the question of
airborne radioactive material and fugitive dust produced from
mining for uranium and other minerals.
   The nominee ``didn't indicate that he understood the issue at
all,'' Hill said.
   Environmental regulations set limits on the amount of such
particles that can be released into the air. Simpson maintains that
the EPA should make allowances for particles placed in the air by
natural causes, such as the brisk Wyoming wind, Hill said.
   The Senate Environment Committee approved Rosenberg's nomination
on Tuesday, 15-1. Simpson was the lone dissenter.
   Rosenberg was chairman of the Michigan Public Service
Commission, which regulates utilities, from 1973 to 1975, and moved
from that job to a position as assistant administrator for energy
resource development with the Federal Energy Administration. He
left that position in 1977.
</TEXT>
