<FIRST>u a AM-WinerySlayings 5thLd-Writethru a0427 04-21 0777</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Winery Slayings, 5th Ld-Writethru, a0427,0796</SECOND>
<HEAD>Precede SAN DIEGO</HEAD>
<HEAD>Mexico Deports Salcido To California</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with Salcido arrival in Santa Rosa.
Picks up 5th graf pvs, `In his...'. SUBS grafs 10-11, `In San...', with
one graf to conform.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA ROSA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A California winery worker who
admitted killing seven people, including his wife and two of his
daughters, was returned to the United States on Thursday.
   Ramon Salcido, who had been sought since the slayings last week
in California, was arrested early Wednesday near his hometown of
Los Mochis, in the western state of Sinaloa.
   He was brought to Mexico City Thursday afternoon, was deported
and quickly put onto a jet for a flight to California, the
officials said.
   He arrived amid tight security at Sonoma County Airport just
outside Santa Rosa in northern California late Thursday night.
   Salcido, smiling faintly at the crowd of Sonoma County Sheriff's
deputies and reporters, was quickly led to a sheriff's van and
taken to the county jail.
   ``In his statements (to Mexican federal authorities), Salcido
himself said he was an American citizen and asked to be sent to the
United States of America to be judged for the homicides he has
committed,'' the Mexican attorney general's office said in a
statement.
   ``As a result, after a brief stopover in Mexico City, Mr. Ramon
Salcido was turned over today to immigration authorities and
expelled from this country within the framework of existing laws,''
it said.
   Earlier, NBC News quoted Salcido as saying upon his arrival in
Mexico City, ``I want to be tried in an American court and face an
American jury.''
   The government did not immediately disclose how Salcido was
flown out. But airport logs showed that a jet provided to Sonoma
County authorities by ``Peanuts'' cartoonist Charles Schulz left
the airport later Thursday afternoon.
   The plane had arrived in Mexico City on Wednesday carrying
officials from Sonoma County, Calif., where the crimes were
committed and where Schulz lives. Airport logs indicated the jet
was to make a refueling stop in Hermosillo, in northern Mexico.
   In San Francisco, U.S. Attorney Joseph Russoniello said the
federal government would seek to dismiss an unlawful flight charge
against Salcido in Sonoma County Municipal Court on Friday.
   He said he was aware of no assurances that had been given to
Salcido that he would not face the death penalty.
   Salcido, wearing a dark T-shirt, was hustled aboard the plane,
airport attendants said. They refused to be identified because they
are not authorized to speak to the press.
   Salcido claimed to be an American citizen, according to Mexican
authorities, even though U.S. authorities said they had no record
he had been naturalized. If Salcido had been treated as a Mexican
citizen, lengthy extradition proceedings might have been necessary.
   ``The assistance of the Mexican government, and in particular of
the attorney general's office, is greatly appreciated,'' said the
U.S. Embassy in a statement.
   George Ramirez, a field producer with KRON-TV in San Francisco,
traveled to Mexico City on the same plane as Salcido and said he
had a brief conversation in English with him.
   When asked if he had anything to say to his surviving 2-year-old
daughter, who he tried to kill, Salcido said ``No,'' Ramirez said.
When asked if he had any regrets, Salcido also said ``No.''
   When asked about his motive, Salcido replied: ``I'll do all my
explaining to U.S. authorities.''
   Salcido, a 28-year-old forklift operator at a Sonoma county
winery north of San Francisco, admitted to the slayings Wednesday
night in a TV interview and said he made his way back to Mexico to
see his parents for the last time. He refused to discuss his
motives.
   Federal officials said he had told agents he killed his
American-born wife, Angela Richards, and a winery co-worker, Tracy
Toovey, and five other people in a jealous rage when he came to
believe Toovey and his wife were romantically involved.
   The only survivor of the rampage, his 2-year-old daughter
Carmina, is recovering from a slashed throat.
   Spokesman Hector Aguilar said Salcido ``has been living in the
United States for nine years, and according to his statement (when
interrogated), he said he acquired American citizenship and was
married to an American.''
   Salcido told police interrogators he drove to Mexico through the
border crossing at Calexico, Calif., hid in a village along the way
for three days, and then headed for Los Mochis.
   Last week, Salcido had been served with Fresno County, Calif.,
court papers ordering him to pay $511 a month support for a
4{-year-old daughter from another marriage, plus nearly $6,000 to
the county for back payments.
</TEXT>
