<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0238</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Off Against Yen, Shares Also Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar closed lower Friday against the
Japanese yen, while share prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange also
finished the week lower.
   The dollar closed at 131.45 yen, down 0.83 yen from Thursday's
close of 132.28 yen. The currency started at 131.35 yen and traded
from 131.30 yen to 131.75 yen.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average, which shed 178.68 points
Thursday, lost another 155.34 points, or 0.47 percent, to close at
33,029.81.
   Traders said the dollar's opening lower followed its slide on
overseas markets after a round of interest rate hikes by several
European countries.
   West Germany's central bank raised interest rates, including its
official discount rate by half a percentage point to 4.5 percent,
effective Friday, to stem inflation, while similar moves were taken
by other central banks in the Netherlands, Austria and Denmark.
   A dealer with the Bank of Japan described the trading as mixed.
   ``There are a group of investors showing concern over a possible
move by the Bank of Japan to raise interest rates in the future,
while others are concerned over a (possible) similar move by U.S.
monetary authorities,'' said the dealer, who would not be quoted by
name.
   Japan's discount rate, which the central bank charges on its
loans to commercial banks, is 2.5 percent, the lowest among major
industraialized countries.
</TEXT>
