<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     04-21 0322</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0333</SECOND>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Minnesota House tried an interesting
angle when a debate over changing the date of the walleye fishing
opener hit a snag over a conflict with Mother's Day observances.
   Opponents said the change would mean the opener _ a cherished
rite of spring in the state _ would fall on Mother's Day weekend 18
times in the next 22 years, compared with only nine times under
current law.
   The law currently has the walleye, sauger, northern pike and
bass season openers beginning on the Saturday closest to May 15.
   A compromise amendment reached Thursday says mothers can fish
for free on the opening weekend of the season.
   Rep. Dee Long asked how conservation officers would be able to
tell whether a woman is a mother and thus entitled to fish without
a license.
   The author of the Mother's Day compromise amendment, Rep. Dave
Gruenes, retorted, ``I think what you do is ask; moms don't lie.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Florida Supreme Court has made it
legal. Legal documents can't be put on legal-sized sheets of paper
anymore.
   The high court, in an order issued Thursday, said filings of
pleadings, motions and other documents in all state courts
beginning Jan. 1 must be on 8{-by-11-inch paper.
   Chief Justice Raymond Ehrlich, who issued the ruling on
legal-size paper, said federal appellate courts require the
letter-size paper. There is no rule now specifying the size of
paper to be used in Florida courts, but legal-sized sheets _ 8{ by
14 inches _ are common.
   Clerks at the Palm Beach County Courthouse were bewildered by
the Supreme Court's interest in paper size. Most shook their heads,
raised their eyebrows and wondered if the high court didn't have
enough work to do.
   ``It will probably save a few trees,'' admitted Mary Ann
Susdorf, supervisor of the felony division. ``Isn't that the whole
idea?''
</TEXT>
