<NOTE>Kemp Says Parental Role To be Considered</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Housing Secretary Jack Kemp says authorities
will have to consider the role parents played in drug activity by
their children before evicting entire families from public housing.
   Kemp, who has encouraged efforts to rid public housing of drug
users and sellers, said Thursday that in some cases parents may be
unable to control older, physically strong children who are engaged
in drug activity. In those cases, he said, ``I don't think Mom and
Dad should be punished'' by eviction.
   But he said there are cases where mothers or other heads of
families are participants in drug enterprises, sometimes with their
children.
   ``Let the tenants and the (public housing agencies) throw them
out,'' the secretary of Housing and Urban Development said. ``On
the first, first _ one, one _ time you're caught doing, dealing,
engaging in drug traffic, I would say, out.''
