<DOCNO> AP890421-0048 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-89 0500EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Soviet-Election     04-21 0571</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Election,0590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sakharov, Slate Of Reformers Win Academy Election</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Human rights activist Andrei D. Sakharov,
initially eliminated from the ballot, won a seat in the Soviet
Union's new parliament in a repeat election by the Academy of
Sciences, the Tass news agency reported today.
   Tass announced preliminary results of Thursday's balloting for
12 parliamentary seats to be filled by the prestigious academy.
   Also elected to the Congress of People's Deputies were space
scientist Roald Z. Sagdeev, economist Nikolai Shmelev and Georgy A.
Arbatov, director of the U.S.A. and Canada Institute.
   Tass said Shmelev, who has proposed radical solutions to the
Soviet Union's economic problems, won the most votes, 869 of 1,101.
Sakharov received 806 and Sagdeev received 739, it said.
   Sakharov, Sagdeev and Shmelev were among a slate of reformers on
the list of 28 candidates. Other reformers who won election were
Vitaly Ginzburg and Yuri Karyakin, Tass said.
   The 2,250-member congress will meet for the first time on May 25
to choose from among its members the country's president and a
Supreme Soviet, which will make policy for the nation.
   Sakharov's election ``will be a great success for perestroika,''
said one of his backers, Alexander Sobianen, using the word for
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's reform program.
   Sakharov originally was nominated for the congress in January,
but the academy's screening committee eliminated him and other
reformers when it cut the list of candidates on the final ballot
from more than 100 to 23.
   However, Sakharov's supporters, including Sobianen, charged that
the nominees were old-style academic bureaucrats, and organized a
campaign to reject them. In the first election last month, only
eight of the 23 received more than 50 percent of the vote.
   This time, 28 candidates were nominated for the 12 seats still
open, and Sakharov, Sagdeev, Shmelev and other reformers were
nominated once again.
   Sakharov, a physicist, voted Thursday morning at a polling
station at Moscow State University. He made no comment to reporters.
   Sakharov, winner of the 1975 Nobel Peace Prize for his rights
activities, was exiled to the closed city of Gorky in January 1980
for criticizing the Soviet intervention in Afghanistan. In 1986,
Gorbachev allowed him to return to Moscow.
   Sakharov has since resumed his scientific work and continues to
speak out on social issues. He supports Gorbachev's reforms but
criticizes what he sees as efforts to slow or reverse them.
   In a speech to the academy Wednesday night, Sakharov again
criticized two laws that allow authorities to use special troops to
quell demonstrations.
   Sakharov blamed the April 9 clash in Tbilisi, the capital of
Soviet Georgia, on such laws and on forces opposed to reforms.
   At least 20 people died when soldiers moved into a crowd of
demonstrators on Tbilisi's main street. A commission is
investigating charges that soldiers used poison gas, shovels and
clubs.
   Hundreds of academy members voted to support a resolution of its
branch in Georgia that called the incident an ``unprecedented
massive beating of innocent people.''
   The Communist Party, trade unions and social and professional
groups such as the academy will elect 750 congressional members.
The 1,500 others are elected from geographical districts.
   In balloting for the geographical districts on March 26, voters
rejected dozens of top party and government officials, many of whom
were running unopposed.
   Repeat elections will be held May 14 for almost 200 seats that
remain unfilled.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
