<DOCNO> AP890421-0049 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-89 0555EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Voyager-Neptune     04-21 0422</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Voyager-Neptune,0434</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trajectory Change Puts Voyager 2 On Course For Neptune Encounter</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PASADENA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Zipping through space 2.67 billion miles
from Earth, the Voyager 2 spacecraft changed course in a maneuver
that targeted it for its Aug. 24 picture-taking encounter with
Neptune.
   Thursday's trajectory change took place 183 million miles from
Neptune as the hardy space probe cruised at a speed of 42,279 mph,
said Mary Beth Murrill, spokeswoman for NASA's Jet Propulsion
Laboratory.
   Radio commands sent by mission controllers traveled at the speed
of light _ nearly 670 million mph _ but still took four hours to
reach the distant Voyager 2, which started its journey in 1977 and
explored Jupiter in 1979, Saturn in 1981 and Uranus in 1986.
   The commands made Voyager 2 fire some of its thrusters and
adjust onboard gyroscopes to execute the course correction, Murrill
said. She added that it as one of the last major maneuvers needed
to propel the probe toward the solar system's eighth planet.
   ``This puts the spacecraft on target for Neptune,'' she said at
the laboratory, which operates America's unmanned space exploration
program for the National Aeronautics and Space Administration.
   Voyager 2 is scheduled to take numerous television pictures as
it swoops within 3,013 miles of Neptune's cloud tops Aug. 24.
   The spacecraft is controlled with radio commands sent through
NASA's Deep Space Network, which includes large dish-shaped
antennas in Goldstone, Calif., Spain and Australia.
   The latest maneuver ``was performed during a week of simulations
in which the Voyager team is rehearsing what they will be doing
during the Neptune encounter,'' Murrill said.
   Scientists believe Neptune probably has a watery atmosphere that
slowly blends into an underlying ocean, with no clear boundary
between sky and sea. They believe Triton, one of Neptune's two
known moons which the spacecraft also will fly by, has methane and
water ices on its surface, and possibly lakes or an ocean of liquid
nitrogen.
   After encountering Neptune, Voyager 2 will head out of the solar
system and conduct studies of interstellar space.
   It's twin, Voyager 1, also was launched in 1977, but explored
only Jupiter and Saturn before heading toward the edge of the solar
system.
   NASA officials have said the Voyager flights _ which scientists
have called humanity's most productive space exploration effort _
will cost $920 million by 1995, less than half what the Pentagon
spends during a single work day.
   The Voyagers discovered at least 17 previously unknown moons
orbiting Jupiter, Saturn and Uranus.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
