<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     04-21 0373</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0386</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Falls Against Yen, Prices Lower Too</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar fell today against the Japanese
yen, while prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange dropped after
announcements of interest rate hikes in Europe.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average, which lost 178.68 points
Thursday, shed another 155.34 points, or 0.47 percent, to finish
trading at 33,029.81.
   The dollar ended the week at 131.45 yen, down 0.83 yen from its
132.28-yen closing on Thursday. The U.S. currency opened lower at
131.35 yen and ranged from 131.30 to 131.75 yen during the day.
   The dollar's lower opening was because of announcements of
interest rate hikes in West Germany and other European nations,
said Ichiro Ikeda of Chemical Bank in Tokyo.
   West Germany's central bank raised its official discount rate by
half a percentage point to 4.5 percent, effective today, while
similar moves were taken by central banks in the Netherlands,
Austria and Denmark.
   ``Investors began speculating over a possible interest rate hike
by Japanese monetary authorities in the near future and bought the
yen,'' he said.
   ``But investors then slowed down their yen-buying following
comments by (Japanese) Finance Minister (Tatsuo) Murayama this
morning,'' Ikeda added.
   Murayama said early today that he saw no need at the moment to
raise the country's official discount rate.
   ``I don't see any need for a change in credit conditions,''
Murayama told a news conference following a regular Cabinet meeting.
   On the stock exchange, prices were lower throughout the day
because of the European interest rate hikes and higher oil prices,
said Kenji Ishizuka of Daiwa Securities.
   Oil prices surpassed $22 per barrel following an explosion on a
North Sea oil rig two days ago.
   The Nikkei index plunged in early trading but then made up some
of its losses toward the end of the morning session following
Murayama's comments.
   Despite a massive purchase by Salomon Brothers Ltd. of 15,000
shares of each of the 225 key Nikkei issues to take advantage of
cheaper prices, a majority of participants were reluctant to buy
ahead of the weekend, Daiwa's Ishizuka said.
   Trading was moderate, with volume on the market's first section
estimated at 900 million shares, unchanged from Thursday. Among the
winners were construction and food issues.
</TEXT>
