<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-89 0548EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-SovietIntrusion     04-21 0409</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Soviet Intrusion,0421</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japanese Jets Scramble After Soviet Aircraft</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Japanese defense force airplanes scrambled
after what was believed to be a Soviet aircraft that twice today
crossed into Japan's northern airspace, a Defense Agency official
said.
   The aircraft intruded into Japanese airspace at 2:36 a.m.,
crossing from north to south over Rebun, a small island off Japan's
main island of Hokkaido, 500 miles northwest of Tokyo, the official
said.
   At 3:51 a.m. near the same area, what local radar monitoring
officials called a ``large-sized aircraft'' flew from the east
toward the south, said the official, who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   The intruding aircraft was in Japanese airspace for 3{ minutes,
the official said.
   Japan's airspace begins 12 nautical miles from shore.
   ``Judging from the flying course the aircraft took, we believed
it might be a Soviet electronics reconnaissance plane,'' the
defense official said.
   In both cases, two F-15 jet fighters were rushed from Chitose
Air Base on Hokkaido but could not identify the aircraft because it
had already left Japanese airspace, the official said. He said a
Japanese air force radar site on Hokkaido warned the aircraft twice
in Russian but received no reply.
   Japan's Foreign Ministry today lodged a strong protest with the
Soviet Union over the alleged Soviet intrusion, a Foreign Ministry
official said.
   Kazuhiko Togo, chief of the ministry's Soviet Division, summoned
Georgy Komarovsky, councillor at the Soviet Embassy in Tokyo, to
the ministry and told him the incident was ``extremely
regrettable,'' the official said. Togo asked the Soviet Union to
take steps to prevent the recurrence of a similar incident.
   The official quoted Komarovsky as telling Togo that he had
``heard nothing about the occurrence of a violation (of airspace).''
   But Komarovsky was quoted as telling Togo he would convey the
Japanese protest and request to his government.
   It was the first violation by a foreign aircraft of Japan's
airspace since a Soviet Tu-16 Badger bomber violated Japanese
airspace over Okinawa in December 1987.
   In that incident, two Japanese jet fighters scrambled from an
Okinawa base and one fired live ammunition as warning shots at the
Soviet plane. It was the first time for a Japanese fighter to fire
warning shots at a Soviet aircraft since the Defense Agency assumed
air defense responsibility in 1958.
   Today's incident brought the number of violations of Japan's
airspace since then to 21, most of which by Soviet aircraft, the
defense official said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
