<DOCNO> AP890421-0054 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-89 0608EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-AbortionTelevision     04-21 0657</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Abortion Television,0673</SECOND>
<HEAD>NBC Abortion Movie Highlights Increased Threat of Advocacy Groups</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NBC was so afraid of hostile advocacy groups
and unnerving advertisers that it shot its dramatization of the
landmark court case that legalized abortion under two phony script
titles.
   The network also insisted on numerous script rewrites, invited
an anti-abortion activist to view ``Roe vs. Wade'' before its May
15 broadcast and tried to prevent the film's author, director and
producer from giving interviews.
   ``They're just terrified of everything at this point,'' said
screenwriter Alison Cross.
   Said the film's star, Holly Hunter: ``I know what they're
worried about. They're afraid we'll say something we're not
supposed to say. ... But the script has a point of view, and so
does history.''
   NBC's fear of an assault from the anti-abortion lobby _ and the
possibility of advertiser defections _ runs so deep that the
network's depiction of the legal pursuit of abortion rights nearly
ended with the suggestion that the court decision be overturned.
   ``It was our fear that in the effort to make this piece balanced
we were going to bend over so far backwards that it was going to
end up pro-life,'' said Cross, referring to herself and ``Roe vs.
Wade'' executive producer Michael Mannheim.
   ``And there were a couple of drafts ... where I felt that ... I
had made all these little changes and I didn't realize how
cumulative they were. Until finally, at the end, you look at the
script and you say, `Boy, this is a hell of a propaganda piece for
the other side,''' said Cross, who was reached independently after
NBC refused to make her available for interviews.
   But why is NBC so afraid to take even the slightest position on
an issue that is, after all, the law, and that a majority of
Americans support?
   The answer speaks loudly to both the fervor of the abortion
debate and the growing clout that advocacy groups wield over the
entertainment industry, evidenced by the religious right's outrage
over ``The Last Temptation of Christ,'' which led some theater
chains to refuse to exhibit the movie.
   Next Wednesday, the Supreme Court is to hear arguments in a key
abortion rights case from Missouri that could eventually mean Roe
vs. Wade will be overturned or substantially limited.
   Anthony Masucci, senior vice president of NBC's movies for
television and miniseries, said he thought the story ``made for
what I thought was dramatic, compelling television, without
necessarily getting on a soapbox and preaching about anything.''
   But as soon as Cross sat down to write the screenplay, though,
it became clear that the network's interpretation of ``preaching''
ran far and wide.
   Cross had trouble getting the phrase ``women are dying'' into
the script, and couldn't use the issue of coat hangers in reference
to illegal abortions because, she said, the network considered them
inflammatory and excessive.
   ``There were more than 17 drafts. Finally, we couldn't even
number them anymore,'' Cross said. ``We just put dates on them. I
have a whole shelf full of them.''
   Rosalyn Weinman, NBC's vice president of program standards and
community relations, said it is ``absolutely inaccurate'' to say
NBC tried to soften the movie's inherent pro-choice stance. ``There
was no pressure to make this more pro-choice or more pro-life,''
Weinman said.
   But while the parties involved say they believe the final script
is fair to both sides, the number of rewrites illustrates
Hollywood's anxiety over protests.
   Under pressure recently from viewers and special interest
groups, advertisers have pulled out of NBC's ``Saturday Night
Live,'' the Fox Broadcasting Corp.'s ``Married with Children'' and
ABC's canceled ``Heartbeat.''
   ``I think if this movie were on a year and a half ago, we'd
probably be less cautious then we are,'' said Masucci. ``There are
some fringe elements out there ... and we don't want to raise their
hackles in any way, shape or form.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890421-0055 </DOCNO>
