<HEAD>University Football Players Suspended For Killing Swan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KALAMAZOO, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two college football players have been
suspended until next January for allegedly ripping a swan's head
off.
   Bradley Willis, 19, and Paul Johnson, 20, were arrested
Wednesday and arraigned in 9th District Court on one count each of
killing a protected wild fowl. They pleaded innocent and were
released on $500 bond.
   Matthews said the two admitted to Western Michigan University
police that they were drinking Tuesday before they allegedly killed
the white male swan, which lived with its mate at the Goldsworth
Valley pond on campus. The female and her eggs later were removed.
   The university ordered Willis and Johnson to serve one year's
probation upon their return to school. They were also ordered to
undergo alcohol counseling, make restitution and provide 100 hours
each of community service to Michigan State University's Kellogg
Bird Sanctuary, which owned the bird, university spokesman Michael
Matthews said.
   Johnson, of Rockford, Ill., was a defensive tackle and Willis,
from Rossville, Ill., a linebacker.
