<FIRST>u i PM-Hitler-Clashes     04-21 0348</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hitler-Clashes,0360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Leftists-Rightists Clash, 13 Policemen Injured, 100 Arrested</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Clashes between leftists and neo-Nazis on the
100th anniversary of Adolf Hitler's birth left 13 policemen
injured, West Berlin police said today. Authorities said 100 people
were arrested.
   Scattered fighting broke out late Thursday on Hitler's birthday
and went on throughout the city until early today, police said.
   A police statement said about 500 people, mostly young leftists
and foreigners armed with clubs, gas pistols and chains, roamed the
streets looking for neo-Nazi ``skinheads.''
   The ``skinheads,'' recognizable by their shaven heads and black
combat boots, had threatened to harass foreigners and leftists on
Hitler's birthday.
   Thirteen young Germans and Turks clashed with five neo-Nazis
near the city's Congress Hall, police said. Both sides were armed
with clubs and gas pistols. Police arrested all 18 and confiscated
their weapons.
   In another incident, an off-duty policeman sustained facial
injuries when he attempted to arrest two neo-Nazis who were
spray-painting swastika emblems on a building. The officer was able
to arrest one of the men, but the other got away, police spokesman
Jorg Mueller said.
   Police said 12 other officers were slightly injured but provided
no details.
   Mueller said a 16-year-old ``skinhead'' was injured when he was
beaten up by 10 people who attacked him while he was riding in a
subway train.
   Several hundred people in West Berlin's Kreuzburg district,
which has a large foreign population, patroled the area's streets,
Mueller said. Construction trailers parked in the area were
overturned and several windows smashed.
   The skirmishes continued through 4 a.m., when a group of eight
people thought to be from a rightist group attacked a group of four
Germans and four Turks with baseball bats in the Hasenheide area,
Mueller said.
   Police arrested three of the attackers, he said.
   He said a total of 100 people were arrested overnight, and
dozens of weapons, including baseball bats, knives, gas pistols,
and chains, were confiscated.
   Mueller said most of the arrested were freed after
identification checks. ``The majority of those temporarily detained
were from the leftist scene,'' he said.
</TEXT>
