<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--RussianRoulette     04-21 0185</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Russian Roulette,0188</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Says Russian Roulette Victim Shouldn't Get Benefits</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The family of a police officer who shot and
killed himself during a game of Russian roulette doesn't deserve
$161 a week in workers' compensation benefits, a state appeals
court ruled.
   The Appellate Division of the state Supreme Court on Thursday
overturned a decision by the state Workers' Compensation Board
awarding the family of Timothy Gibbs benefits because he wasn't
fully trained in how to use his gun.
   ``One does not need intensive experience in weapons firing to
become familiar with the deadly risks of playing Russian
roulette,'' Justice Howard Levine said.
   Gibbs was hired as an Orange County deputy sheriff to provide
extra security at a 1983 trial. He was standing lookout on the roof
of a jail.
   When another officer arrived to relieve Gibbs, the pair emptied
ammunition from their guns, and Gibbs said to his companion,
``Let's play Russian roulette,'' Levine said.
   Gibbs put a shell into his .357-caliber Magnum, spun it and put
the gun to his head. He pulled the trigger and was killed.
