<FIRST>u i PM-Soviet-Solzhenitsyn 1stLd-Writethru a0490 04-21 0440</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Solzhenitsyn, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0490,0449</SECOND>
<HEAD>Solzhenitsyn's Gulag Archipelago To Be Published In His Homeland</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs to CORRECT that magazine earlier published
a short Solzhenitsyn novel. Pickup 7th graf pvs, ``The Gulag...''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Selections from Alexander Solzhenitsyn's banned
chronicle of Stalin's labor camps, ``The Gulag Archipelago,'' will
be published this year by a literary journal, a secretary at the
magazine said today.
   Some chapters from the lengthy book will appear before year's
end in the monthly magazine Novy Mir, Valentina Ivanovna said in a
telephone interview.
   The secretary refused to say who in the Soviet leadership had
approved publication of the gripping tale of repression under
Stalin. Kremlin officials have said such works still are off limits.
   ``I am against the publication of a number works by
Solzhenitsyn, and in the first place such works as `Lenin in
Zurich' and `The Gulag Archipelago,''' Communist Party ideology
chief Vadim A. Medvedev told a news conference in November.
Exposing Soviets to such books would undermine society, he said.
   But The Washington Post in today's editions quoted Novy Mir's
chief editor, Sergei P. Zalygin, as saying in an interview that
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev supported publication of
Solzhenitsyn's works. Ms. Ivanovna said Zalygin would not be in his
office and was immediately unreachable.
   It was Novy Mir that published Solzhenitsyn's short novel, ``One
Day in the Life of Ivan Denisovich'' in November 1962.
   The Gulag is a triology that maintains widescale political
repression began in the Soviet Union under founder Vladimir I.
Lenin.
   Zalygin had said last year he was negotiating for the rights to
print Solzhenitsyn's novel ``Cancer Ward.'' Ms. Ivanovna said no
decision had been made about publishing works of Solzhenitsyn other
than the Gulag.
   Several writers, artists and activists have clamored for
publication of Solzhenitsyn's works, citing Gorbachev's policy of
glasnost, which among other things allows re-examination of sore
points in Soviet history like Stalin's reign of terror.
   In February, a journal of the Soviet Peace Committee titled
Twentieth Century and Peace printed an appeal to reject officially
sanctioned lies that Solzhenitsyn wrote just before being exiled in
1974. The journal also carried a commentary crediting Solzhenitsyn
for helping pave the way for Gorbachev's reforms.
   The reforms have led to publication of Soviet authors that had
been long banned. Others that have come into the open include the
novel ``Doctor Zhivago'' by Boris Pasternak and the political
satire ``Heart of a Dog'' by Mikhail Bulgakov.
   Solzhenitsyn was arrested, branded a traitor and expelled for
his writings.
   Solzhenitsyn, 70, gained U.S. citizenship in 1974. A Nobel
laureate, he is living in rural isolation in Vermont.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
