<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-89 0843EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-RiverboatGambling     04-21 0445</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Riverboat Gambling,0458</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iowa House Approves Riverboat Gambling, Sends Bill To Governor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE GLOVER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bill legalizing floating casinos on
rivers and lakes in Iowa is on its way to Gov. Terry Branstad, who
has pledged to sign it into law as a way of bolstering the state's
economy.
   The House voted 51-47 Thursday to approve the measure, without a
vote to spare in reaching the required majority of the 100-member
body.
   Rep. Phil Tyrrell, a Republican, was among opponents who
predicted dire consequences, saying gambling would not be confined
long to rivers and lakes.
   ``Like a sickness and a disease, it spreads across the state of
Iowa,'' said Tyrrell. ``We'll see all of the problems that follow,
the drugs and the prostitution, as if Iowa didn't have enough
problems.''
   Critics complained bitterly about intense lobbying pressure to
reverse last week's rejection of the same bill by three votes.
   Rep. Greg Spenner, a Republican who voted against the bill last
week, said before the vote that he would switch sides because his
phone had not stopped ringing.
   ``The people in my district are in apparent disagreement with my
earlier stance,'' said Spenner.
   Backers said eastern Iowa badly needs multimillion-dollar
developments that have been proposed for the Iowa side of the
Mississippi River in association with casino boats. Besides, they
said, the state already has pari-mutuel betting, bingo and a
lottery, so gambling is nothing new.
   ``It's hypocritical for us to deny another part of the state
their form of gambling,'' said Rep. Mark Haverland, a Democrat who
is a United Methodist minister.
   ``I do not think gambling is a sin. I think gambling is dumb and
self-destructive,'' he said. ``But I don't think gambling is the
only thing that's legal, dumb and self-destructive.''
   ``We continue to delude ourselves into thinking that somehow we
will find a magic button that will solve our financial problems,''
said Rep. Tom Miller, a Republican.
   Backers painted a picture of 19th century riverboats plying the
river and theme amusement parks providing wholesome family
entertainment.
   Developer Franklin Fried of San Diego issued a statement
immediately after the vote saying, ``Iowa has laid the foundation
for bringing a unique first-class national tourist attraction to
the Midwest.'' He promised to move ahead with plans for a $10
million Iowa Queen riverboat.
   Under the bill, the state's Racing Commission would issue
gambling licenses for boats on rivers and lakes, with the
commission setting the location and number.
   The bill legalizes small stakes gambling, with a $5 limit per
bet and a $200 nightly loss limit. The first boatload of gamblers
could sail in 1991.
</TEXT>
