<FIRST>u i PM-Lebanon 1stLd-Writethru   04-21 0701</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0509,0721</SECOND>
<HEAD>Syrians Shell Christians As Civilians Flee Moslem Sector</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 13 grafs to UPDATE with reports of peace efforts.
Pickup 15th, `About 150,000...' ADDS 2 grafs at end with U.N. chief's call
for aid.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syrian forces today bombarded the
Christian enclave with rockets, concentrating their attacks on the
port of Jounieh in an apparent effort to block the Christians' only
route out of Lebanon.
   Police had no immediate reports of casualties.
   Syrian gunners in Moslem west Beirut fired truck-mounted BM-21
rocket launchers that shot 40 122mm rockets carrying 105-pound
warheads.
   A police spokesman said the Syrians fired every four hours on
Jounieh and the coastal highway running north from Beirut in the
Christians' crescent-shaped, 310-square-mile enclave.
   Christian forces did not return the fire, police said, but
Moslems in west Beirut continued to flee the city.
   Kuwait's Al-Qabas daily newspaper said several Arab states were
seeking to persuade Syria, the main power broker in Lebanon, to
accept a peacekeeping force. It said the Arab force could number
``several hundred officers and troops from six or seven Arab
states.'' It did not name them.
   The rocketing flared after a short lull Wednesday in the battle
between Gen. Michel Aoun's mainly Christian army units and an
alliance of Syrians and Moslem Druse militiamen.
   A police spokesman, who cannot be named under standing
regulations, described the missile barrage as ``a message'' that a
ferry service linking Jounieh with Larnaca, Cyprus, ``should not
resume.''
   The Cypriot companies that run two ferries into Jounieh
suspended service two days ago after their vessels came under
Moslem rocket fire. They have carried about 12,000 Christians and
foreigners to Cyprus in recent weeks.
   However, Cypriot officials in Larnaca said one of the ferries
sailed for Jounieh today. Because of the shelling, the ferries have
anchored 10 miles offshore and fleeing Christians are shuttled out
to the ships in small boats.
   Maj. Gen. Sami Khatib, commander of Moslem units of Lebanon's
divided army, said Jounieh and Beirut ports would ``remain under
blockade'' as long as Aoun maintains his siege of illegal ports
south of Beirut run by Moslem militias.
   Aoun's blockade, in a move aimed at restoring government control
long eroded by the powerful militias, led to the latest round of
fighting in Lebanon's 14-year civil war.
   Since March 8, at least 270 people, mainly civilians, have been
killed and nearly 1,000 wounded.
   About 150,000 Moslems have fled Beirut, many out of fear of
renewed fighting. Others have left because of shortages of flour
and fuel, power blackouts and the breakdown of the water system.
   But many Moslem men have stayed to look after homes and
businesses.
   ``I'm prepared to live in an underground shelter for the rest of
my life, but I won't leave my shop or apartment to be looted,''
said Izzat Salam, a Sunni Moslem spare parts dealer who has sent
his family to Damascus, the Syrian capital.
   Police reported numerous complaints about robberies in
bomb-damaged apartments, shops and warehouses.
   Meanwhile, about 400 Christians demonstrated in the Jdaideh
suburb of east Beirut to support Aoun's ``war of liberation'' to
force Syria to withdraw its 40,000 troops in Lebanon.
   A spokesman for the demonstrators, who refused to be identified,
said they planned to stage a sit-in near the U.S. Embassy in east
Beirut to ``demand U.S. action to save Lebanon and rid it of the
Syrian occupation.''
   Lebanese guards outside the embassy fired in the air on Thursday
to stop demonstrators jumping over a barbed wire fence to get into
the U.S. compound, police said.
   The spokesman said six demonstrators ``fell on the barbed wire
fence and suffered injuries.''
   Aoun accused Washington of failing to mobilize Western pressure
on Syria to stop the fighting. U.S. officials have said Washington
has little influence with the Syrians.
   In Geneva, U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar today
called on all countries to provide humanitarian asssistance to
Lebanon and said immediate needs totaled $92 million.
   ``The needs of humanitarian assistance for the most disfavored
population groups _ the wounded, the disabled, the displaced, and
the very poor _ are greater than ever,'' he said in a statement.
</TEXT>
