<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-89 0913EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Sudan     04-21 0420</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sudan,0431</SECOND>
<HEAD>Air And Road Convoys Leave Uganda For Southern Sudan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KAMPALA, Uganda (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United Nations began trucking and
airlifting food to the southern Sudanese town of Torit today, three
days after an ambush halted the relief effort's first convoy to the
beleaguered town.
   The airlift and convoy are part of the United Nations' Operation
Lifelife Sudan, meant to stock more than 110,000 tons of food and
supplies in war-torn southern Sudan before heavy seasonal rains
begin in mid-May.
   The $132 million operation aims to prevent a repeat of 1988's
tragedy when between 250,000 and 500,000 people died because of a
famine caused by drought, floods and the 6-year-old insurgency by
the Sudan People's Liberation Army.
   A giant C-130 Hercules cargo plane carrying 155 tons of maize
landed in Torit after leaving Uganda's Entebbe airport before dawn,
said Paul Mitchell, a spokesman for Operation Lifeline Sudan.
   The plane, leased from and operated by the Miami-based Southern
Air Transport Co., is to make three flights daily to Torit until it
has delivered 1,100 tons, he said.
   Mitchell said today's delivery was the first large shipment of
relief food to the town. The Norwegian People's Aid and World
Vision relief agencies have delivered 100 tons of food to Torit
since April 1, he said.
   Gote Hertz, a U.N. spokesman in Kampala, said a 47-truck convoy
carrying 1,100 tons of food also started off today. He said the
convoy first will deliver food to the Sudanese border town of
Nimule, then travel 60 miles northeast to Torit if the convoy
leaders believe conditions are safe.
   In recent weeks, Torit's civilian population has swelled from
3,000 to 25,000 as displaced southerners seeking food and shelter
pour in from the surrounding bush. U.N. officials expect the
population to climb to 50,000 in the coming weeks.
   On Tuesday, the first U.N. convoy in rebel-held southern Sudan
was ambushed as it traveled west to Torit from the Sudan People's
Liberation base of Kapoeta. Eight rebel escorts were killed, and
the convoy's lead truck was destroyed. U.N. officials have not
assessed blame for the attack.
   Operation Lifeline began April 1 after the United Nations
received assurances from Sudan's government in Khartoum and the
rebels that the relief effort would be allowed to move unhampered.
   U.N. officials say they probably will not meet their goal of
delivering 115,000 tons of food to southern Sudan before the onset
of the rainy season.
   The rebels seek greater autonomy and economic development for
the predominantly Christian and animist south.
</TEXT>
