<FIRST>u i PM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru   04-21 0601</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0496,0614</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Beef Up Forces In Jerusalem For Moslem Prayer Day</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with Israeli comment on restrictions,
Jewish settlers allowed into city while Arabs turned back, Moslem prayers
ending without incident. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police deployed extra officers today near the
Al Aqsa Mosque in Arab east Jerusalem, and soldiers turned back
Palestinians trying to enter the city for prayer services at the
holy site.
   Moslem officials had called on Palestinians from the occupied
West Bank and Gaza Strip to attend the services despite Israeli
efforts to restrict the number of worshipers as a way to prevent
violence.
   Also today, the army announced that a 17-year-old Palestinian
from the Gaza Strip was killed Thursday when he was struck by
plastic bullets during a clash with army troops.
   The death brought to 440 the number of Palestinians killed since
the December 1987 start of the uprising against Israeli occupation
of the West Bank and Gaza. Eighteen Israelis also have died in the
unrest.
   Since capturing the Old City from Jordan in the 1967 Middle East
war, Israel has taken pride in guaranteeing free access to all
religious sites. Authorities, however, occasionally have blocked
traffic from the occupied areas during the 16-month Palestinian
uprising to prevent riots at Moslem prayers.
   ``When it comes to violence, there's a need to restrict
movement,'' said a senior military official, speaking on condition
of anonymity.
   Police and army roadblocks were set up today along the roads
linking Jerusalem with the West Bank. Troops stopped and searched
Arab-owned cars and pulled passengers off Arab buses. Young men
were ordered to go back while elderly people were allowed to
continue on their way to Jerusalem.
   On the road from the biblical West Bank towns of Hebron and
Bethlehem, 10 Arab men were turned back just as a group of 50 armed
Jewish settlers, accompanied by police and army cars, marched by,
singing religious songs.
   ``This is ... to show that Jews can walk throughout the land of
Israel without fear, that this is our country,'' said 36-year-old
Mark Zell from Alon Shvut settlement, a lawyer who immigrated to
Israel from Washington.
   But Jamal, a 35-year-old Palestinian who watched the settlers
pass, noted: ``They want to show us this is their land, but they
have to carry all these guns. It shows that they are afraid of
us.'' He declined to give his full name.
   In Jerusalem, hundreds of security personnel were deployed
around Al Aqsa's hilltop site, compared to the usual 90.
   Police were searching grocery bags and checking identity cards
of all Arabs asking to enter the compound, turning back all
residents of the occupied West Bank. Those allowed to enter turned
over their identity cards to police.
   Below the mosque, about 300 Jewish worshipers were seen praying
at the Western Wall, the holiest site in Judaism which Jews believe
is the last remnant of their ancient temple.
   Jerusalem police commander Yosef Yehudai told reporters Moslem
prayers were attended by 14,000 worshipers. Israel army radio
estimated the number at 5,500.
   Moslem worshipers dispersed without incident, and Yehudai said
it was ``because of all the measures police and border police
made.''
   Security was tightened after Palestinians stoned police in the
mosque compound following prayers on April 7, the first Friday of
the Moslem holy month of Ramadan. The violence spread to the
adjacent Western Wall.
   On April 14, police turned away most West Bank and Gaza
Palestinians headed for the mosque, the third-holiest site of Islam
after Mecca and Medina in Saudi Arabia.
</TEXT>
