<FIRST>r i PM-SouthAfrica     04-21 0487</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-South Africa,0497</SECOND>
<HEAD>Last South African Hunger Striker Resumes Eating</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The last participant in a
hunger strike has resumed eating, ending a protest that helped win
freedom for hundreds of black inmates who were held without charge,
a human rights group said today.
   The Human Rights Commission said the last known hunger striker,
Zelile Zwane, began eating Thursday after being taken to court and
charged with various offenses, including illegal weapons possession
and attempted murder.
   Like the other hunger strikers, many of them anti-apartheid
activists held since 1986, he had demanded the government either
release him or charge him.
   The government said this week that less than 100 people remained
in custody under emergency regulations allowing indefinite
detention without trial. About 1,000 were held in late January,
when hundreds of detainees began fasting in prisons across the
country.
   ``We see what happened as a great victory for detainees,'' said
Audrey Coleman, a member of the Human Rights Commission. ``Through
their united action, they were able to expose the whole system of
detention without trial.''
   However, the commission and civil rights lawyers issued angry
protests today because of reports that former hunger strikers had
been shackled to their beds while recuperating at Johannesburg
Hospital.
   The National Medical and Dental Association, an organization of
anti-apartheid health care professionals, said Thursday that at
least two detainees had been shackled to prevent escapes. Since
September, there have been at least four escapes from hospitals by
detainees receiving treatment.
   Police headquarters declined comment on the use of shackles at
the hospital but said departmental policy allowed such measures.
   The Human Rights Commission says a majority of detainees freed
in recent weeks have been issued with restriction orders. Many of
them are barred from certain political activities, confined to
their homes at night and required to report to a police station
twice daily.
   One former detainee, Chris Ntuli, was killed by unidentified
assailants last week after making his required appearance at a
police station in a black shantytown outside Durban. Civil rights
groups suggested the killers were right-wing vigilantes who were
able to predict Ntuli's movements because of the restrictions.
   Black activists in the Durban area today called for residents to
stay away from work and school in conjunction with a memorial
service for Ntuli. There were unconfirmed reports that two buses
were fire-bombed and that a milk truck was set on fire, killing the
driver.
   The Weekly Mail, a leading anti-apartheid newspaper, reported
today that the decision to free most detainees was made by the
Cabinet against the wishes of the State Security Council, which
includes senior military and intelligence officials as well as a
few Cabinet ministers.
   The Weekly Mail quoted Mark Swilling, a Johannesburg-based
political scientist, as saying it was the first time the security
council was overruled in the 11 years since President P.W. Botha
took power.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890421-0076 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-89 1041EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-USLabor     04-21 0383</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-US Labor,0393</SECOND>
<HEAD>American Labor Chiefs Say Soviets Ruled Out Independent Unions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two American labor leaders said today that Soviet
officials admitted their trade unions have not adequately protected
workers but ruled out formation of independent trade organizations.
   However, the leaders, AFL-CIO vice presidents Jack Sheinkman and
William Winpisinger, told a news conference they believe such
independent unions, like Poland's Solidarity, might surface.
   ``If steps are not taken to adequately reflect representation
and problems that the workers are putting to their leadership, that
kind of pressure might ultimately explode,'' Sheinkman said. He is
president of the New York-based Amalgamated Clothing and Textile
Workers Union.
   One of the tenets of communism is that workers' rights are a top
priority of the government, but trade unions have come under
increasing criticism for not aggressively prodding bureaucrats to
improve housing, salaries and working conditions.
   At least two strikes by Soviet miners have been reported this
year over low salaries and poor working conditions.
   Sheinkman said he asked Stepan A. Shalayev, president of the
All-Union Central Council of Trade Unions, on Monday whether
independent trade unions would be created in the Soviet Union.
   ``This was not what they felt was necessary. ... Pluralism as
defined by him in our conversations meant pluralism within the
existing system and framework and not in terms of an independent
union such as exists in Poland,'' the American labor chief said.
   But he said President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's reforms could lead
to such unions because the government will not ``be able to put the
necessary checks on everything.''
   Earlier this month, Poland's government ended seven years of
suppression and legalized the trade union Solidarity.
   Winpisinger, president of the International Association of
Machinists and Aerospace Workers, said he believes Gorbachev, whom
he met Wednesday, is aware of the faults of Soviet trade unions.
   Gennady Yanayev, a secretary of the Soviet trade unioncouncil,
told the news conference that officially backed trade unions have
not paid enough attention to the social and economic needs of
workers but that improvements are under way.
   ``We are confident the unions will be made an even more dynamic
and efficient force, and given that I think there will be no
question of the need for alternative groups,'' Yanayev said.
   ``But,'' he added, ``life will show.''
</TEXT>
