<FIRST>r a PM-ChurchClosings     04-21 0276</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Church Closings,0283</SECOND>
<HEAD>Detroit Catholic Churches Fight Closings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seventeen Roman Catholic churches that have been
ordered closed filed grievances with the Archdiocese of Detroit,
charging that church officials' decision to shut down 30 inner-city
churches was racist.
   The grievances, filed Thursday, call for an independent church
review of the closings announced by Cardinal Edmund Szoka in
January after five years' study. The churches were ordered to close
by June 30 because of dwindling membership and the expense of
maintaining obsolete buildings.
   Three churches that aren't scheduled to close also filed
grievances in sympathy for the others.
   The grievances charge that Szoka, Bishop Patrick Cooney and
members of two committees that recommended the closings showed a
lack of love for the city's black Catholics.
   They ``willingly accept the premise that white suburban
Catholics would not involve themselves in the church in the city
for reasons of racism, fear of crime and overall lack of love for
their urban brothers and sisters,'' the documents state.
   The Rev. Norman Nawrocki, the archdiocese's grievance clerk, has
20 days to decide whether the grievances fit the archdiocese's
guidelines for disputes. If they do, they will be heard by a
grievance committee that can make a recommendation to the cardinal,
said Jay Berman, a spokesman for the archdiocese.
   Berman, who called the charges in the grievances ``harsh and
very unfair,'' said however that only the cardinal can overturn his
own decisions about the churches.
   Berman also said there could be an appeal directly to the
Vatican, but most of the parishes filed that appeal earlier, before
filing this one, and to his knowledge there has been no response.
</TEXT>
