<FIRST>u i PM-China 2ndLd-Writethru   04-21 0703</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China, 2nd Ld - Writethru,a0526,0722</SECOND>
<HEAD>Protests Swell To 100,000</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs to UPDATE with crowd growing to 100,000,
students marching across town to join rally. Pickup 5th pvs, ``Hu, who...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tens of thousands of people crowded into a square
today and cheered as student demonstrators waved banners demanding
greater political freedoms and carried wreaths honoring a dead
leader who favored reform.
   The crowd of up to 100,000 swept from one side of the 100-acre
Tiananmen Square the other every time a new group of
wreath-carriers arrived.
   At one point about 1,000 people crossed a low chain barrier and
trotted halfway up the steps of the adjacent Great Hall of the
People, the national seat of government. They did not try to enter
the hall.
   Today's gathering was the largest of five straight days of
demonstrations on the square following the April 15 death of former
Communist Party chief Hu Yaobang, which touched off long-simmering
anti-government sentiments.
   Meanwhile, another 20,000 students from Beijing University and
at least nine other schools gathered in northwest Beijing and began
a nine-mile walk to the square to join the demonstrations.
   The students chanted ``long live democracy'' and ``down with
corruption'' as they marched along a road, tying up traffic. People
in buses stranded by the march looked out the windows and cheered
the demonstrators.
   Hu, who died of a heart attack at age 73, was admired by
students for protecting the rights of scientists and intellectuals.
   Students from more than 20 universities have placed wreaths to
Hu's memory on a monument to revolutionary heroes on the square,
and hoisted banners calling for democracy and freedom of speech and
press.
   A well-known writer, Lao Gui, put up a banner written in his own
blood eulogizing Hu and urging students not to stop praising him.
   Numerous small groups made their way through the crowd to the
monument today, including one group from Nankai University in
Tianjin and representatives from the Science and Technology Daily.
   ``China's political life is even more pitiful than our economic
life,'' a government official from the Committee for Restructuring
the Economy told The Associated Press. The official said, ``Our
consciousness is higher than it was before but still the government
won't permit us to express our views.''
   Police vehicles drove along the outside of the square
broadcasting through loudspeakers: ``Keep moving, don't interfere
with people's work.'' Police did not try to break up the rallies.
   About 100 students from the China School of Journalism carried
banners reading ``press freedom'' and ``we need facts'' as they
marched on the square and then around the Great Hall of the People.
   China's official press again warned that further anti-government
acts by students would not be tolerated.
   ``Anyone who attempts to undermine unity under any excuse will
be punished by law,'' said the People's Daily, official paper of
the Communist Party.
   ``Until now the government has acted with restraint toward these
illegal activities. If anyone takes this attitude as one of
weakness ... they will eat their own bitter fruit.''
   The editorial referred to attempts by thousands of students
Tuesday and Wednesday to force their way into the Communist Party
headquarters.
   The students were pushed back by police at the gate of the
red-walled compound near the square and later dispersed by large
contingents of police.
   On Thursday, only about 1,500 students braved a daylong downpour
to march to the square.
   Universities and the official press have told students that they
may participate in officially sanctioned mourning activities, but
have warned students not to use the occasions for anti-government
activities.
   The Communist Party will hold a memorial service for Hu at the
Great Hall on Saturday morning.
   Students in Nanjing and Shanghai also have used Hu's death to
demonstrate for political reforms. There have been unconfirmed
reports of student rallies in Tianjin, Wuhan and Hefei.
   The rallies have been the largest since pro-democracy
demonstrations in the winter of 1986-87. Those demonstrations were
followed by a conservative backlash against Western liberal ideas
that included the ouster of Hu as party general secretary.
   Hu was blamed for failing to stop the students and the trend
toward ``bourgeois liberalization.''
</TEXT>
