<FIRST>r i PM-Walesa     04-21 0476</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Walesa,0490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Solidarity Leader Calls for Investments</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY BETH SHERIDAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lech Walesa, leader of Solidarity and champion of
Poland's new political course, told Italian political leaders today
that his country needs investment, rather than aid.
   ``Poland has all the figures to be part of of Europe, but it
needs investments, more than aid _ investments to create companies
and a market,'' the Polish labor leader told Premier Ciriaco De
Mita.
   Walesa traveled to Italy just days after Poland's communist
government restored the legality of the Solidarity labor movement
and agreed to free elections for a new house of Parliament.
   The labor leader, who played a key role in negotiations leading
to the reforms, met with Pope John Paul II on Thursday to receive
his blessing for Poland's new reforms.
   Walesa drummed home his plea for investments in talks today with
President Francesco Cossiga, Foreign Minister Giulio Andreotti,
Socialist Party leader Bettino Craxi and Rome Mayor Pietro Giubilo.
   In a 35-minute meeting with the premier, Walesa said Solidarity
intended to fight economic centralism and work for political,
economic and social pluralism. Foreign investment would play a key
role in helping Poles reach those goals, he said.
   ``There is everything to be done in our country and therefore
cooperation can also be good business,'' said the labor leader,
winner of the 1983 Nobel Peace Prize.
   Walesa also emphasized that Poland wants to be integrated into
Europe and not shut out when European Community countries form an
internal market without borders in 1992.
   ``We Poles count on you heavily in constructing the new
Poland,'' he told Andreotti, according to a translation from the
Foreign Ministry. ``I think that we can together build a single
Europe, and you can be our teachers.''
   De Mita and Andreotti assured Walesa that Italy would encourage
investment in Poland and support economic and political change in
the country.
   ``The European Community, in its entirety, must look at the
East, starting from the primary locomotive of its economic force,
which ought to move toward the East consolidating the dialogue of
peace in the economic-commercial area,'' said Craxi, who was
Italy's prime minister from 1983-87.
   ``A Europe that closes up within itself and doesn't know how to
look to the south and to the east is a myopic and egoistic
Europe,'' he added.
   The situation in Poland is of keen interest in Italy, which has
a strong union tradition and is overwhelmingly Roman Catholic.
   Poland's government imposed martial law in December 1981 to
crush Solidarity, the Soviet bloc's first independent trade union.
With the legalization of Solidarity, the communist government is
hoping to win the union movement's support in reviving the economy
and encourage new aid from the West.
   The Catholic Church, extremely influential in Poland, took part
in the negotiations with the government that produced the reforms.
</TEXT>
