<FIRST>r a PM-MinoritySet-Asides     04-21 0299</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Minority Set-Asides,0306</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Issues Injunction Against Minority Set-Asides</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A program that earmarks 10 percent of
city and school board contracts for minorities and women has been
halted pending trial by a federal judge.
   The preliminary injunction issued Thursday by U.S. District
Judge John H. Moore II takes the place of a temporary restraining
order that shut down the programs April 6. The future of the
set-aside program, challenged as unconstitutional by non-minority
contractors, will be decided at a trial in December.
   About $14 million is earmarked each year by the city and school
board for companies owned and operated by minorities and women.
   ``The court finds that the public interest is served by ensuring
that the legislative bodies' programs conform to the provisions of
the United States Constitution,'' Moore said in his ruling.
   Moore cited a U.S. Supreme Court ruling in January that declared
minority set-aside programs unconstitutional unless they are based
on a detailed study showing the minorities have faced governmental
discriminination in the past.
   Neither the city nor the school board has conducted a study on
the 10 percent set-aside programs started in 1984. A study is
scheduled to be conducted soon, officials said.
   Officials with the Northeast Florida chapter of Associated
General Contractors and Barcorp., which filed the suit challenging
the set-asides, said their rights were being violated because they
could not bid on some of the city and school board projects.
   Blacks in this city of 550,000 claim the ruling means they will
be shut out of contracts.
   ``It's going to put us back in the same predicament as five
years ago,'' said Ernest McDuffie III, a contractor who has
received work under the program. ``A lot of people will go out of
business and people won't have work.''
</TEXT>
