<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-89 1114EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-FusionPaper     04-21 0372</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fusion Paper,0381</SECOND>
<HEAD>Authors Withdraw Paper on Fusion From Scientific Journal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The authors of a highly publicized report on
room-temperature nuclear fusion have decided not to publish it in a
prestigious British scientific journal, the editors announced
Thursday.
   B. Stanley Pons of the University of Utah and Martin Fleischmann
of Britain's University of Southampton had said publicly that they
submitted the paper to Nature magazine, an editorial in Thursday's
issue noted.
   Following standard practice, editors referred the paper to other
scientists for review. These referees raised several questions that
would require Pons and Fleischmann to do more work on the paper,
Nature said.
   But ``Fleischmann and Pons have taken the view that they could
not at the same time satisfy the referees and get on with other
urgent work,'' Nature said.
   So their paper will not be published, but a second cold fusion
paper, from a team including Brigham Young University scientist
Steven Jones, will appear in next Thursday's issue, Nature said.
Jones and colleagues did make changes requested by referees, Nature
said.
   Pam Fogle, a University of Utah spokeswoman, said Nature
``specifically asked for more data and to flesh out the article by
some 1,000 to 2,000 words. Some of the data they were asking for
was coming out of experiments that are currently operating. They
didn't have the data to supply to the reviewers for the second
go-round.''
   Fleischmann and Pons already have reported their work in the
Journal of Electroanalytical Chemistry, Nature noted.
   Nature said that the absence of their article should not be
taken to imply that their research is inherently less believable
than the work by Jones and colleagues.
   Nor does the appearance of Jones' paper mean that ``all those
who have seen it are persuaded to its chief conclusion,'' the
editorial said. It just means that ``the authors have produced an
article which answers questions that would otherwise spring to
readers' minds,'' it said.
   Both teams of researchers say they have produced nuclear fusion
at room temperature, in contrast to the extreme heat used in
standard fusion experients.
   Fusion powers the sun and stars, and scientists say it may
provide an environmentally benign source of energy if it can be
harnessed.
</TEXT>
