<FIRST>u w PM-Hinckley 1stLd-Writethru a0444 04-21 1002</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hinckley, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0444,940</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hinckley Testifies for First Time, Wants New Lawyer</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: TOPS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with Lane interview, picking up
at pvs 5th graf, bgng ``Hinckley, who;'' SUBS 17th graf pvs bgng, `In his,'
to CORRECT date and title of book; DELETES outdated 21st graf pvs bgng,
`Lane did;' St. Elizabeths without apostrophe is cq</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Maverick attorney Mark Lane today confirmed he
is interested in representing presidential assailant John W.
Hinckley Jr., but denied suggestions he wants to write a book about
the man who shot President Reagan.
   Lane, who made a national reputation for his writings on
assassination conspiracy theories, insisted that Hinckley's
interest in retaining him was based solely on a desire for
effective legal counsel rather than to collaborate on a book.
   He said ``it appears that Mr. Hinckley seems more settled, more
concerned about constitutional rights and more accurate and less
emotionally disturbed than are his keepers'' at a local mental
institution where Hinckley has been held since his 1982 acquittal
by reason of insanity in the 1981 shooting of Reagan and three
others.
   Lane, who said he has spoken with Hinckley several times by
telephone since Hinckley called him in early March, also dismissed
suggestions that he would seek payment of his legal fees in
revenues from a book on the case.
   ``I have never made any agreement with any client in which my
fee was paid by the publication of a book,'' Lane said in a
telephone interview from Daytona Beach, Fla., where he is
representing a man on death row. ``I never have because I believe
that generally constitutes a conflict of interest.''
   Lane commented in response to testimony Thursday in federal
court in which Hinckley said he wanted to hire Lane because ``he
has done very well'' defending famous criminals.
   ``He has taken some cases of national .... reknown,'' Hinckley
said in his first testimony, choosing the last word after a long,
careful pause.
   ``He has represented some people who are famous to the general
public,'' Hinckley told prosecutor Robert R. Chapman. These clients
gained notoriety ``as criminals, in the criminal world.''
   Hinckley won permission at Thursday's hearing to meet with Lane
or other lawyers at the mental hospital.
   Hinckley, who initially did not identify the lawyer-author by
name, told U.S. District Judge June L. Green that he telephoned
Lane because ``he had somewhat of a reputation.''
   ``What kind of reputation?'' the judge said.
   ``He is just known nationwide in certain circles. I had heard of
him in the past representing a number of people.''
   ``He has certainly had many cases and done well with them,''
explained Hinckley, who wore a navy blazer over an open-neck plaid
sports shirt.
   Hospital lawyer Janet L. Maher contended that Hinckley would
expose himself to exploitation if allowed to interview prospective
attorneys without court supervision.
   ``Are you aware that in fact he has written a number of books
about political assassinations?'' she asked Hinckley.
   ``I know of one book he has written,'' Hinckley replied.
   ``What book is that?'' the judge interjected.
   ``Do you want me to just give this person's name because we are
going to lead into that?'' Hinckley said.
   After the judge indicated she did, Hinckley said: ``He has
written a book called `Rush to Judgment.' His name is Mark Lane.''
   Hospital authorities canceled his appointment with Lane,
Hinckley said.
   ``I should at least be permitted to talk to the man,'' Hinckley
said. ``If we don't get along, it stops right there.''
   In his 1966 book ``Rush to Judgment,'' Lane disputed the
findings of the Warren Commission that Lee Harvey Oswald alone shot
and killed President Kennedy in 1963 in Dallas.
   Hinckley also acknowledged that he knew that at one time Lane
had represented James Earl Ray, who killed the Rev. Martin Luther
King Jr.
   Asked if he knew that Lane had also written other books about
people he represented, Hinckley said: ``I don't think it's a crime
that he's written these books and interviewed these people. I am
sure that the subjects he has written about at some point gave
their consent.''
   ``I am capable of deciding whether I want my story told and it
is not the hospital's say to dictate whether I can do that,'' said
Hinckley, who spoke lucidly and appeared relaxed on the witness
stand.
   Vincent J. Fuller, the lawyer who successfully defended Hinckley
at the 1982 trial, did not oppose the motion for a new lawyer.
Fuller said he was relieved to be dismissed from the case.
   ``He wanted new counsel; he's entitled to it. I did not want to
stand in his way,'' Fuller said as he left the courthouse.
   A psychiatrist at St. Elizabeths Hospital here testified that
Hinckley was competent to pick a new lawyer but had been placed in
a maximum-security ward because he had ``difficulty handling the
privileges'' he had previously been given.
   Dr. Raymond Patterson said Hinckley still suffers from a serious
mental illness, ``continues to have difficulty in his judgment''
and has ``difficulty learning from his past experience.''
   He can't ``differentiate famous from infamous,'' Patterson said.
``He does not have a clear perception of how he is seen by others.''
   In 1987, Hinckley was living in a dormitory-style room when
federal prosecutors turned up evidence he was corresponding with
serial killer Ted Bundy, who was executed last year.
   That revelation and others prompted the hospital to drop its
attempt to give Hinckley an Easter weekend pass that year to visit
his family.
   Plans to take him on an outing with other patients last summer
were abandoned after authorities discovered a new cache of letters,
which remain under court seal.
   The flair for writing that Hinckley has shown in several
articles he has written has prompted widespread speculation that he
wants to write a book about his life.
   Sources who have spoke on condition of anonymity say that among
the papers seized from his possession was a well-written manuscript.
</TEXT>
