<FIRST>u i PM-Germany-Nazi     04-21 0334</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Germany-Nazi,0344</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nationwide Search Launched For Convicted Nazi War Criminal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WUPPERTAL, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police have launched a nationwide
manhunt for a Nazi war criminal convicted of murdering Auschwitz
prisoners during sadistic target practice exercises, officials said
today.
   In a statement to the news media, the Wuppertal prosecutor's
office said former Nazi SS Sgt. Gottfried Weise, 69, ``is believed
to have fled his home to avoid arrest.'' Wuppertal is 15 miles east
of Duesseldorf.
   Weise was convicted Jan. 28, 1988, of killing at least five
prisoners in 1944 at the Nazis' notorious Auschwitz concentration
camp in what is now Poland. He worked at the camp as a guard during
World War II.
   During his 15-month trial, Weise became know as the ``William
Tell of Auschwitz'' after witnesses testified he killed an
8-year-old boy and a 17-year-old girl by forcing them to balance
tin cans on their heads, which he then used for target practice.
   In addition to their deaths, Weise was found guilty of shooting
to death two male prisoners who tried to escape by hiding in a
supply truck, and another man who did not report quickly enough for
roll call.
   Weise was sentenced to life imprisonment but was allowed to
remain free pending an appeal.
   Horst Rosenbaum, the Wuppertal chief prosecutor, told reporters
police went to Weise's home in nearby Solingen on Thursday after
word was received that a federal court had turned down the
conviction appeal.
   He said Weise was not home and apparently had fled to avoid
arrest.
   ``We assume that he is on the run, and a nationwide search for
Weise has been started. All border crossing points have been
notified,'' Rosenbaum said.
   He added that the search would expand outside West Germany if
evidence is received indicating Weise may be in a foreign country.
   According to the prosecutor, Weise was not jailed pending the
outcome of the appeal ``because the court decided with his
retirement pension and home here, there was little danger of him
fleeing.''
</TEXT>
