<FIRST>u i PM-Philippines-Slaying 3rdLd-Writethru   04-21 0714</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Philippines-Slaying, 3rd Ld-Writethru,a0529,0736</SECOND>
<HEAD>Suspected Rebels Kill Decorated U.S. Army Officer</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs to ADD White House comment. Pickup 6th pvs,
`Rowe was...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos MLA1, NY7-8</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT H. REID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Suspected communist rebels firing
from a speeding car killed a U.S. Army officer and former Vietnam
prisoner of war today as he headed to work, officials said.
   Col. James N. Rowe, 51, of McAllen, Texas, was shot in the head
when at least two hooded assailants pulled up in an auto alongside
Rowe's car and shot him near his office at a military compound in
suburban Quezon City, the officials said.
   Col. Victor Tiangco of the Philippine military's Capital Region
Command said Rowe's driver, Joaquin Vinuya, was wounded in the 7
a.m. ambush but was not seriously injured.
   Tiangco said Rowe, a West Point graduate, was chief of the army
division at the Joint U.S. Military Advisory Group, which provides
training and logistical support for the Philippine armed forces.
   President Corazon Aquino said the Philippine military would
increase security around the six U.S. military installations in the
wake of the attack.
   At the White House, press secretary Marlin Fitzwater called the
killing ``a cowardly and heinous act.''
   ``We will work closely with the Philippine government in their
efforts to track down and bring to justice those responsible for
this assassination. The U.S. government's support for Philippine
democracy is unshaken,'' Fitzwater said.
   Rowe was held prisoner in a cage in the jungles of Vietnam by
the Viet Cong from October 1963 until he escaped on New Year's Eve
1968. He wrote a book about the ordeal titled ``Five Years to
Freedom.''
   ``After five years, I was out of the forest of darkness,'' Rowe
recalled after he gained his freedom. ``I could see the horizon and
the world seemed immense.''
   Police said a driver and at least two gunmen were in the
assailants' car. One had an M-16 rifle and another a .45-caliber
pistol, they said.
   Toto Austria, a cashier at a gasoline station, said he heard
shots and turned to see a white car pull alongside Rowe's
silver-gray vehicle.
   As the cars turned along a traffic circle, Austria said he saw
at least one man fire from a window. He said there was more gunfire
before the assailants made a U-turn and sped away.
   Police later found the assailants' car about 1{ miles west of
the ambush site, which was three blocks from the military compound.
Tiangco said 21 bullets struck Rowe's car.
   A U.S. Embassy spokesman, Jerry Huchel, said Rowe was dead on
arrival at a Philippine military hospital and that his body was
flown to Clark Air Base, 50 miles north of Manila.
   No group claimed responsibility for the slaying. But Defense
Secretary Fidel Ramos and other officials said they believed
communist rebels were responsible because of the weapons used and
the style of the attack.
   ``On the face of it, it is likely that this was perpetrated by
communist terrorists,'' Ramos said.
   U.S. Ambassador Nicholas Platt said: ``If anyone thinks that
killing this brave officer would alter in any way U.S. policy of
support for Philippine democracy, they are wrong.''
   In Alexandria, Va., F. Andy Messing Jr., executive director of
the National Defense Council Foundation, said Rowe had expressed
concern about rebel terrorism during a meeting last month in Manila.
   ``He had an idea that it was going to occur,'' Messing said.
   Sen. Ernesto Maceda, chairman of the Senate Defense Committee,
said the killing highlighted the seriousness of the Marxist
insurgency.
   ``They (rebels) are operating not only in the mountains and
(villages) but openly here in metro Manila. So I keep saying that
it is wrong for us to keep maintaining that everything is fine, we
are winning'' the war, Maceda said.
   In October 1987, communist rebels killed three Americans and a
Filipino of American descent in simultaneous attacks near Clark Air
Base.
   On April 9, rebels blasted a U.S. military communications
station in Benguet province of northern Luzon island. No one was
injured, but U.S. officials asked that security around American
installations be tightened.
   The rebels have threatened more attacks against Americans
because of ``American interference'' in the 20-year insurgency.
   Rowe is survived by a wife and two young children.
</TEXT>
