<FIRST>u a PM-Battleship-Remains 1stLd-Writethru a0491 04-21 0520</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Battleship-Remains, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0491,0527</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sailors' Remains Arrive at Dover Air Force Base</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with remains released, completion
of victims list. Picks up 4th graf, `Ball said...' SUBS 8-9th grafs, bgng
`By Thursday...', with 2 grafs to DELETE now-outdated material, add reference
to today's service, background on effort to identify bodies, picking up
10th graf pvs, `The remains...'.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Battleship-Families, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos DV1,2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THERESA HUMPHREY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DOVER AIR FORCE BASE, Del. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Navy today began
transporting the remains of some of the 47 sailors killed in an
explosion aboard the USS Iowa to their hometowns for burial.
   Navy officials said they were still trying to identify some of
the bodies, but had enough information to issue a list naming all
47 victims.
   A brief ceremony was held Thursday after the arrival of the
remains. The Navy secretary knelt in prayer on one knee before a
flag-draped casket as taps was played.
   Secretary William L. Ball III said he was representing President
Bush, who served in the Navy during World War II.
   Ball said Bush ``knows the special agony which is like no other
that attends the loss of a shipmate _ he knows the dangers of
serving at sea, he knows the incomparable sacrifices made by those
who choose to wear the uniform of our naval service.''
   Ball said he had sailed on the Iowa and had met a number of the
crewmen who were killed.
   ``I had sailed with them and had crawled around their turret,
shaken their greasy hands, felt the strong sure grip that only a
gunner's mate can give,'' he said. ``It is our prayer today that
they will go from here to their resting places certain in the
knowledge that a grateful nation will not forget.''
   Families of the victims did not attend. But there were nine
crewmen from the battleship who accompanied the remains, and more
than 100 Air Force personnel were on hand to pay tribute to their
fallen comrades.
   The process of identifying the remains was aided by some 50
volunteers who were counseled in advance to prepare them for the
shock of the carnage, officials said.
   A memorial service is scheduled for Monday in Norfolk, Va., the
ship's home port, Navy spokesman Mark Neuhart said. A smaller
service was planned for today.
   The remains arrived from Roosevelt Roads, Puerto Rico, aboard a
C-5A Galaxy cargo jet. As the plane was unloaded, a Navy honor
guard and other officials stood at attention while the Navy Band
from Washington alternately played the Navy hymn and ``America The
Beautiful.''
   The bodies were sent to Dover because it houses the nation's
largest military mortuary, operated by the Defense Department to
handle the remains of military personnel and dependents who die in
Europe, the Azores and Greenland.
   It also handled remains of sailors killed aboard the USS Stark
in May 1987, Marines killed in a terrorist bombing in Beirut in
October 1983 and the remains of military personnel and dependents
killed in the terrorist bombing of Pan Am flight 103 over Scotland.
</TEXT>
