<FIRST>u a PM-WrightPolls     04-21 0379</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wright Polls,0388</SECOND>
<HEAD>Polls Show Many Unaware of Wright Affair</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Wright Probe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Many Americans are unfamiliar with the ethics
charges against House Speaker Jim Wright, but majorities say he
should resign as speaker if he violated the rules of Congress, two
national polls have found.
   A fifth of the respondents in an ABC News poll said Wright
should quit as speaker immediately, and an additional 59 percent
said he should resign his leadership position if the charges
against him were found to be true.
   In an NBC News-Wall Street Journal survey, 75 percent said
Wright should quit as speaker if the House found that he broke its
rules. That poll did not ask if Wright should resign immediately.
   The ABC poll found Wright's popularity declining. In an April 3
poll, 53 percent approved of his performance as speaker. In the
poll done Wednesday, two days after the ethics committee charged
Wright, 29 percent approved.
   About half those who no longer approved of Wright said they
disapproved of him. The other half were undecided.
   In the NBC-Journal poll, about one quarter of the respondents
had a favorable opinion of Wright and about a quarter had an
unfavorable opinion. The rest, nearly half, had no opinion of him.
   Both polls found another indication that the issue has not
gripped public attention: Nearly half in the NBC-Journal poll and
40 percent in the ABC poll said they had not heard or read anything
about the Wright affair.
   NBC and the Journal polled 1,447 adults Sunday through Tuesday,
and their poll had a margin of error of plus or minus 3 percentage
points. ABC polled 540 adults Wednesday night; its survey had a
5-point margin of error.
   Poll results can vary because of the wording of questions and
because of changing events that prompt movements in public opinion.
The ethics committee charged Wright on Monday, while the
NBC-Journal poll was being conducted.
   Wright was cited Monday for 69 violations of House rules,
including allegations he improperly accepted nearly $145,000 in
gifts and that his wife was paid $72,000 for work she didn't do.
   He has denied charges he violated any House rules, including the
alleged use of book sales to avoid a limit on fees for speeches.
</TEXT>
