<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-89 1212EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-RoweBio     04-21 0606</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Rowe Bio,0627</SECOND>
<HEAD>Army Officer Killed in Terrorist Attack Had Escaped Viet Cong in
'68</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Philippines-Slaying</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto DN2</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Associated Press Writer Gary Garrison was based
in Harlingen, Texas, during the last two years of Col. James N.
Rowe's captivity and talked with Rowe's parents frequently. He
covered Rowe's return and his emotional reunion with his parents in
1969.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>By GARY GARRISON</NOTE>
<NOTE>Associated Press Writer</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The Viet Cong kept James N. Rowe in a cage in the jungle of
Vietnam for five years, but they couldn't break his spirit with a
constant barrage of propaganda and almost daily death threats.
   Instead, it was hooded gunmen in the Philippines who took the
life of the 51-year-old Army colonel. He was shot to death Friday
as he drove to work at the Joint U.S. Military Advisory Group
headquarters. No group immediately claimed responsiblity, but
investigators believed the killers were Communist rebels.
   Rowe, who was decorated for his Vietnamese ordeal, escaped from
his cage on New Year's Eve, 1968. He was nearly killed by U.S.
forces who thought the black-pajama-clad Special Forces officer was
a Viet Cong.
   He came home to Texas' Rio Grande Valley to a hero's welcome.
   Rowe, a native of McAllen, graduated from West Point in 1960,
and was captured by the Viet Cong Oct. 29, 1963.
   After he managed to escape, Rowe sighted a U.S. Cobra helicopter
and ran into a clearing, signaling for help.
   The first impulse of the men in the helicopter was to shoot the
man because he was dressed like the Viet Cong, but Army Maj. Dave
Thompson ordered the men not to shoot because he wanted to take him
prisoner.
   In his book, ``Five Years To Freedom,'' Rowe recalled that he
jumped into the helicopter and began trying to tell them who he was.
   ``After five years I was out of the forest of darkness,'' Rowe
recalled. ``I could see the horizon and the world seemed immense.''
   Rowe was taken to Brooke Army Medical Center in San Antonio for
a medical examination and treatment and then was allowed to fly
home.
   As the helicopter approached McAllen, Rowe wrote, ``I was
totally absorbed with my thoughts as I watched the towns pass
below, bringing me miles closer to my home; it had been such a
long, long journey both in time and space.''
   At his parents' home, it was an emotional scene as the young
officer dashed from the car to the front porch, where his father,
Lee Rowe, opened the door.
   ``Dad, dad, I'm sorry I didn't get home sooner; they just
wouldn't let me go,'' he said.
   Rowe earlier had told reporters he had asked his mother,
Florence, to bake some bread for his first meal at home.
   Rowe hugged his parents, describing it as ``five long years'
worth of hugging.''
   ``The three of us stood for a long moment, touching,
communicating without speaking,'' Rowe recalled. ``My world was
complete; I had reached out and touched the light.''
   A few weeks later, Rowe made a speech at McAllen High School's
football stadium and a parade was held. Thousands turned out for a
glimpse of the hometown hero.
   Lee Rowe died in 1973 and Mrs. Rowe died in 1982.
   John Ford, one of Rowe's cousins, remembered Rowe as a brave man
who knew what he was getting into when he was sent to Vietnam.
   ``He knew it was a hot spot when he went over there. He knew he
had to be careful,'' Ford said Friday from his McAllen home.
   ``He walked like an Army officer, he talked like one and he died
like one.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
