<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-89 1229EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-FirebombedBooks     04-21 0392</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Firebombed Books,0404</SECOND>
<HEAD>Library Fire Third Arson Attack Against Children's Books in Illinois
Town</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOLIET, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of children's books have gone up
in flames in this northern Illinois community, and authorities are
trying to determine who is behind firebomb attacks on the public
library and two schools.
   The third and latest incident was the firebombing of the Joliet
Public Library on Wednesday night. Children's Librarian Dianne
Harmon said today that damage estimates to the books and historic
building ranged from $800,000 to $1.5 million.
   ``I've been here 31 years, and I've never seen anyone burning
for books,'' Fire Chief George Plese said Thursday. ``I've seen
them burn for money, burn for spite, burn for all kinds of reasons.
But never for books.''
   No one has been injured in the three firebomb attacks, which
have been started with the same kind of incendiary device at about
the same time of day, said officials in this community of 75,000
about 35 miles southwest of Chicago.
   On Feb. 10, a bottle filled with a fire accelerant was thrown
into a book-storage room at Hufford Junior High School, causing
damage estimated at $15,000.
   On Monday, a Molotov cocktail was thrown through a window into a
book storage room at Marycrest Elementary School, causing at least
$10,000 in damage and closing the school for a day.
   And sometime after 9 p.m. Wednesday an incendiary device of some
type, believed to be a Molotov cocktail, was hurled through a
window at the public library, Plese said.
   Despite the similarities, police said they are not making any
assumptions about whether the firebombings are connected.
   Librarian James Johnston choked back tears as he surveyed the
damage from the fire.
   ``I went through my professional calm and I am going through my
combat rage,'' said Johnston, a Korean War veteran.
   The children's books section took the brunt of the damage, but
smoke damage was in evidence throughout the 86-year-old limestone
structure.
   The children's section of the library comprised about 48,000
books, and Harmon estimated that one-quarter to one-half of the
collection could be salvaged. Johnston said roughly 60 percent of
the books were out of print.
   He said the city's insurance should cover most of the loss.
   Joliet officials, the U.S. Treasury Department's Bureau of
Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms and the state fire marshal's office
were investigating.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
