<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-89 1233EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Chess-Soccer     04-21 0344</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chess-Soccer,0353</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chess Grandmasters Play Exhibition Soccer Match</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOODMAN</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BARCELONA, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   World chess champion Garri Kasparov and
other leading grandmasters put away their boards for a few hours
Friday and played an exhibition soccer match with some former
professional players.
   ``You get fresh air and enjoyment and it shows that we are
normal people who are interested in many things, not just chess,''
Kasparov said afterward.
   Seven grandmasters from the Chess World Cup tournament, which
ended Thursday, scored a 3-3 tie with a team representing chess
journalists and organizers.
   Both teams were bolstered by former professionals from Spanish
soccer powerhouse Barcelona. The grandmasters also fielded Manuel
Orantes, the former Spanish tennis champion who is the non-playing
captain of Spain's Davis Cup team.
   ``I had a very nice time,'' said Ljubomir Ljubojevic, a Yugoslav
grandmaster who tied for first place with Kasparov in the
tournament and who played for the youth soccer team of Red Star
Belgrade when he was 14. ``Unfortunately we only assisted in the
game. The ex-professionals played more among themselves.''
   When the tall, gangly figure of British Grandmaster Jonathan
Speelman ran too far down the field from his defensive position,
Soviet grandmasters Artur Yusupov and Valery Salov shouted in
English: ``Johnny, come back!''
   Several grandmasters, already exhausted by three weeks of
top-flight chess competition, only played in one of the two halves.
Kasparov, 26, was the only chess player to stay on the field for
the whole game.
   Soccer matches have been played at some international chess
events for years, but grandmasters have become far more careful
since Dutch grandmaster Jan Timman broke his leg at a match during
a tournament in 1984 in London.
   Despite impressive footwork from Salov and agressive running
from Kasparov, five of the six goals were scored by the
ex-professionals. The exception came when a Dutch journalist drove
the ball into the grandmasters' goal in the second half.
   ``Football (soccer) is a great game,'' said Miguel Illescas, a
Spanish grandmaster. ``We can forget all our rivalries and show
good team spirit.''
</TEXT>
