<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-89 1244EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-RocketContract     04-21 0348</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Rocket Contract,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>NASA Selects Lockheed For New Rocket Project In Mississippi</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lockheed Missile Systems Division of
Sunnyvale, Calif., has been selected as prime contractor for the
design, development and testing of a new solid-fueled rocket motor
for the space shuttle, NASA announced today.
   The space agency said negotiations will begin with Lockheed on
the details of a contract award for the new rocket. The contract is
expected to include an option for the production of up to 44 motor
sets. Total contract value is estimated at about $1.1 billion over
seven years.
   The National Aeronautics and Space Administration plans to
develop a new, more powerful solid rocket to use with the shuttle
in the mid-1990s. The new rocket is expected to be safer and more
reliable than the solid rocket now used with the shuttle. The new
rocket also has a design goal of being able to put an additional
12,000 pounds of payload into orbit.
   NASA announced earlier that facilities for production of the new
rocket motor will be built at Yellow Creek, a site in extreme
northeastern Mississippi near the town of Iuka. The site currently
is owned by the Tennessee Valley Authority, but will be transferred
to NASA.
   New testing facilities for the new rocket are planned for the
John C. Stennis Space Center near Bay St. Louis, Miss., the space
agency said.
   NASA said the rocket contract with Lockheed will require the
company to produce the first 12 operational motors for use in a
flight verification program consisting of six shuttle missions. The
first flight set of rocket motors is scheduled for delivery in
1994, and NASA is to phase the new rocket motor into the shuttle
fleet over the next three years. After about 1997, the old shuttle
solid-fueled rocket, manufacturered by Morton Thiokol Co. in Utah,
will no longer be used.
   Lockheed is teamed with Aeroject Space Booster Co. of
Sacramento, Calif., as its principal subcontractor for the rocket
motor, and with Rust International of Birmingham, Ala., as the
facility contractor.
</TEXT>
