<FIRST>u a PM-Battleship-Families 1stLd-Writethru a047</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Battleship-Families, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0471,0914</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grieving Begins For Families of USS Iowa Victims</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with ceremony. Picks up 5th graf
pvs, `Words, whatever...'.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By D.W. PAGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NORFOLK, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The governor and 750 other mourners turned
out today to pay tribute to 47 young men who ``died too soon'' in
the nation's worst naval disaster in more than a decade.
   In a brief memorial ceremony, a wreath of 47 carnations was
dropped into the Elizabeth River in honor of the men who were
killed in Wednesday's explosion on the battleship USS Iowa off
Puerto Rico.
   The Navy plans a second service Monday, which President Bush is
to attend.
   Many of the 750 people present today wept as a Navy bugler
played taps and a 21-gun salute boomed into the blue sky.
   Gov. Gerald L. Baliles told the mourners that ``47 young men
died too soon. That is the fact we face. We must accept that, but
we must not forget them. The commonwealth of Virginia and I offer
my deepest sympathy to the families, to the Navy and to the
community.''
   As relatives struggled to deal with their losses, the bodies of
the victims were flown Thursday to Dover Air Force Base in
Delaware, site of a large military mortuary. Some of the bodies
were being identified and shipped to hometowns beginning today.
   The USS Iowa, its forward gun turret damaged, was heading to
Norfolk, its home port, from Puerto Rico.
   ``Even when the tragedy strikes far away from here, it is felt
here. That ship is part of our community,'' Mayor Joe Leafe said
Thursday.
   Meanwhile, Navy chaplains and social workers across the country
tried to help the families.
   ``Words, whatever they are, come empty when you've just told
someone that their husband or loved one is dead,'' said Cmdr. Doug
Palmer, acting base chaplain at the Norfolk Naval Station.
   About 250 family members of the Iowa's 1,600 crewmen gathered in
a base gym Wednesday night awaiting word of their loved ones. About
midnight, the Navy dispatched teams across the country with the bad
news. A Navy officer, accompanied by a chaplain, went to each
family.
   Young Chang Ha, another chaplain, described arriving at a
Norfolk apartment at 3 a.m. Thursday in the company of a Navy
officer in dress blues to tell a woman that her husband was dead.
   ``She said, `Are you sure? Are you sure it is my husband?''' he
said.
   With that the woman began to cry.
   The all-night wait of the parents of Ernest Hanyecz Jr., a
27-year-old gunner's mate first class from Bordentown, N.J., ended
in anger Thursday morning with the news of his death.
   ``As long as they play their war games, there will be more
deaths and innocent people will die,'' said Ernest Hanyecz Sr.
   But in Cleveland, the mother of Clayton Michael Hartwig, said
her family does not blame the Navy for her son's death. Hartwig's
father, Earl, was also a gunner's mate on the Iowa during World War
II.
   ``We're not mad; it was just an unfortunate accident,'' Evelyn
Hartwig said. ``He knew the danger. He often told us how that
powder could go up in nothing flat.''
   Hartwig's sister, Kathy Kubicina, said her brother's death was
difficult because the battleship had been deployed without incident
in the Middle East.
   ``They never even fired their guns in the Persian Gulf for three
months and then they come home, go on war game maneuvers and this
crap has to happen,'' said Ms. Kubicina.
   In Greeneville, Tenn., relatives of Jack E. Thompson Jr. thought
he'd make it out of the Navy alive after he survived Mideast
duties, too.
   But his wife, Leasa, said: ``As soon as I heard it was turret
No. 2, I knew he was dead. I waited and waited, but I knew.''
   Thompson disliked the Navy and was scheduled to complete his
four-year stint in 140 days, his wife said Thursday as she gathered
with his parents and other relatives.
   ``He didn't like being out on the ocean for a long period of
time,'' she said. ``He was an outdoorsman, always hunting and
fishing, and he hated being cooped up. He was just trying to make
the best of it until he got out.''
   ``There is no single solace for all people in times of tragedy
like this,'' said Cmdr. John Mateczun, a Navy psychiatrist who
works with the service's Special Psychiatric Rapid Intervention
Team.
   The only thing certain, he said, is that people involved will
have two emotions: ``One is anger and one is sadness.''
   Teams are dispatched following armed services' disasters to help
the survivors cope. One team was put aboard the Iowa as it stood
off the Puerto Rico coast Thursday morning, unloading the bodies by
helicopter.
   Just as there was anger and sadness as the news made its way to
the families of the victims, the survivors' families felt relief.
   Jackie Hartke of Union in northern Kentucky received a call
about 2 a.m. Thursday from Navy officials that her son, Anthony,
was not on the casualty list.
   ``We feel a little better about the whole situation now, but
until we actually hear from him, we won't feel completely at
ease,'' she said. ``This whole thing has been very trying.''
</TEXT>
