<FIRST>r w AM-Obit-Amory     04-21 0191</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Amory,170</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former CIA Deputy Director, National Art Gallery Official Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Robert Amory Jr., a former deputy director of
the Central Intelligence Agency and retired secretary and general
counsel of the National Gallery of Art, has died of cancer. He was
74.
   Amory, who died Wednesday, joined the CIA in 1952, becoming
deputy director for intelligence the following year.
   He left the CIA in 1962 to become chief of the international
division of the Bureau of the Budget, the forerunner of the Office
of Management and Budget, for three years. He practiced law in
Washington for eight years before taking over the National Gallery
of Art position in 1973. He retired in 1980.
   Amory, a Boston native and a graduate of Harvard University and
Harvard Law School, also was a professor at the law school and
developed its first course on accounting.
   He served in the Army during World War II and was awarded a
Silver Star, Bronze Star and the Legion of Merit.
   He is survived by his wife, Mary Armstrong Amory, two sons and
three grandsons. Services are scheduled for Monday at the
Washington Cathedral.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
