<HEAD>Hundreds Occupy Philly City Council Chambers In Budget Protest</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with 12 people taken into custody.
Picks up 9th graf pvs, `Joe Rogers...'.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TED DUNCOMBE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 400 people upset about proposed cuts
in AIDS care and other social service programs today occupied City
Council chambers in a noisy protest, and 12 who refused to leave
were taken into custody.
   The protesters who packed the chamber gallery for a city budget
hearing began climbing over the railings and occupying council
members' seats and the main floor about 20 minutes into the
meeting. No damage was reported.
   Council president Joseph Coleman initially was unable to bring
order and recessed the hearing until the afternoon. When it
resumed, about 40 protesters remained, and 12 of them who refused
to go to the part of the room set aside for the public were
detained.
   The hearing eventually got under way with some protesters
holding signs but not disrupting proceedings. City Solicitor
Seymour Kurland said he was not sure whether the 12 protesters
would be charged.
   One of the 12, Robert Brand, said he was taking part ``to
guarantee that the city passes a budget that doesn't kill people.''
   ``People just came in protesting the budget as it's been
presented,'' Councilman Angel Ortiz said. ``I think it's driving
home the point that the budget is a very mean budget as it's been
described, and it's a budget that needs to be changed.''
   Mayor W. Wilson Goode, who was not present during today's
disturbance, last month proposed a $2.014 billion budget that would
cut spending for the homeless, AIDS and community organizations but
bolsters police and health clinic staffs.
   Joe Rogers, an activist with Project Share, an advocacy group
for the homeless and mentally ill, said activists would attend
every council meeting and budget hearing until the budget is
approved.
   ``We'll be demanding that they develop a human budget, a humane
budget that doesn't cut back at the cost of the poor,'' Rogers said.
   At several points, the crowd broke into chants such as, ``You
say, `Cut back.' We say, `Fight back.'''
   Protesters held up signs including ``AIDS Coalition To Unleash
Power,'' ``Save City Health Services,'' ``What is Brotherly Love
Without Brotherly Care?''
</TEXT>
