<FIRST>r w AM-Hinckley-Lane     04-21 0776</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hinckley-Lane,770</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lane Says Mental Hospital Stopped Him from Meeting Hinckley</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: St. Elizabeths without apostrophe is cq</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mark Lane, nationally known for his conspiracy
theories about President Kennedy's assassination, complained Friday
he has been kept from meeting John W. Hinckley Jr. by the mental
hospital where Hinckley has been since shooting President Reagan.
   A judge ruled Thursday that they could meet during regular
visiting hours.
   Lane said he has not decided whether to accept Hinckley's
request that he take on his case.
   However, the lawyer said, ``We had an appointment a couple of
weeks ago and the hospital authorities at the highest level decreed
that I could not meet with Mr. Hinckley. Instead they wanted to
meet with me, pulling together a summit meeting all the powers in
Washington to brief me. ...
   ``I said that was absurd and that if a man wanted to obtain me,
the sanctity of the attorney-client relationship is that it remains
between an attorney and a client.''
   Hinckley told a federal court judge Thursday, in his first
public testimony ever, that he wanted to hire Lane as his attorney
because ``he has done very well'' defending famous criminals.
   He said of the proposed March 28 meeting with Lane, ``On the
morning of the meeting, all of a sudden, it was pulled out from
under me.''
   Hinckley has been at St. Elizabeths mental hospital since his
1982 acquittal by reason of insanity in the 1981 shooting of Reagan
and three others.
   Expressing concern that Hinckley might expose himself to
exploitation, hospital authorities had sought court supervision of
his interviews with Lane or other attorneys.
   U.S. District Judge June L. Green overruled the hospital and
granted Hinckley permission to interview Lane or any other lawyer
during visiting hours.
   Lane said he was surprised when Hinckley called him in early
March.
   ``It was a funny conversation. I didn't get his last name
clearly, thought his name was Eakley,'' Lane said, laughing, during
a telephone interview from Daytona Beach, Fla., where he is
representing a man on death row.
   ``I told him I didn't know anything about his case, and he said
it was in all the newspapers.
   ``I had gotten calls from St. Elizabeths patients before who all
said their cases were famous, and I told him I must have missed
those newspapers, please tell me what it's about,'' Lane said.
   During their few telephone conversations, Lane said, Hinckley
told him he wanted to hire him as his attorney, but Lane told him
they had to meet so that Hinckley would know him better and Lane
would learn ``enough about the facts in his case to know if I could
be of assistance to him.''
   During the hearing Thursday, hospital lawyer Janet L. Maher
asked Hinckley whether he knew Lane had written books about
political assassinations and other people he represented.
   ``I don't think it's a crime that he's written these books and
interviewed these people,'' Hinckley said. ``I am sure that the
subjects he has written about at some point gave their consent.''
   ``I am capable of deciding whether I want my story told and it
is not the hospital's say to dictate whether I can do that,'' said
Hinckley.
   In his 1966 book ``Rush to Judgment,'' Lane disputed the
findings of the Warren Commission that Lee Harvey Oswald alone shot
and killed President Kennedy in 1963 in Dallas.
   Hinckley also said he knew that at one time Lane had represented
James Earl Ray, who killed the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr.
   Lane said he has represented clients after writing books on
their cases, including Ray and his current client, James
Richardson, but has ``never written a book as a result of my
representation of a client.''
   He said he has no plans to write a book about Hinckley and that
Hinckley's interest in retaining him was based solely on a desire
for effective legal counsel rather than to collaborate on a book.
   Hinckley has been involved in court matters several times in
recent years in connection with mental institution plans to allow
him to leave for a visit with his family and for an outing with
other patients. The plans were scuttled both times.
   Lane said, ``If the authorities at St. Elizabeths are as careful
in understanding and analyzing Mr. Hinckley's motives and condition
as they are in analyzing my motives for writing a book which I have
no intention to write ... then I think that Mr. Hinckley is
entitled to a new evaluation. If the keepers are nuts, you have to
be very careful about accepting their conclusions.''
</TEXT>
