<FIRST>r a AM-HaitianHijacking     04-21 0238</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Haitian Hijacking,0244</SECOND>
<HEAD>Haitians Plead Innocent To Air Piracy Charges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Haitians accused of hijacking a missionary
group's aircraft to Miami pleaded innocent to air piracy charges
Friday in federal court.
   Fadael Milord, 29, and Berlioze Guillaume, 25, were indicted
Thursday and jailed without bond until trial, which has not been
scheduled.
   Outside the courtroom, Guillaume's court-appointed attorney,
Henry Bugay, told The Associated Press: ``This was not a case of
air piracy. My client was seeking political asylum.''
   Milord's lawyer, Assistant Federal Public Defender Charles
Wishna, said the men were fleeing for their lives.
   At an earlier hearing, the men had said they decided to go to
the United States after passing an airport on the way to the
Dominican Republic on April 10. They were fleeing to the
neighboring country after taking part in a failed coup attempt
against Haitian leader Lt. Gen. Prosper Avril, they said.
   They commandeered a twin-engine plane owned by Missionary
Aviation Fellowship of Redlands, Calif., which makes regular runs
from Haiti to Fort Lauderdale, the FBI said.
   ``Our airplane, with our pilot Duer Smedley, had been loading on
the ramp at Cap Haitien on the north coast of Haiti when suddenly
two armed men burst out onto the ramp firing their pistols,'' Jack
Walker, a member of the fellowship, said at the time.
   The men diverted the aircraft to Miami, where they immediately
surrendered. No one was hurt.
</TEXT>
