<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-89 1519EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-India-Carbide     04-21 0216</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-India-Carbide,0221</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Orders Interim Monthly Payment for Heirs of Gas Victims</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court on Friday ordered the
government to pay $50 a month to heirs of about 2,000 adults who
died in the 1984 Bhopal gas leak, news reports said.
   The United News of India said a three-judge panel passed the
order while hearing petitions seeking interim relief for the
survivors of the Dec. 2, 1984 disaster, which has been described as
the world's worst industrial accident.
   More than 3,400 people were killed and at least 20,000 injured
when toxic methyl isocyanate gas leaked from a pesticide factory
operated by the Indian subsidiary of Union Carbide Corp. in the
central city of Bhopal.
   The Danbury, Conn.-based multinational was ordered to pay $470
million compensation to the victims after a Supreme
Court-supervised settlement in February. The settlement was reached
during the hearing of a $3 billion damage suit filed by the
government.
   Disbursal of the money was held up after several petitions in
the Supreme Court challenged a law empowering the government to
become the sole representative of the victims. The petitions are
being heard by a different panel than that which made Friday's
decision.
   The $50 monthly relief will be deducted from the compensation
awarded later, UNI said.
</TEXT>
