<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Brazil-Floods     04-21 0164</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Brazil-Floods,0169</SECOND>
<HEAD>Floods Leave 46,000 Homeless in Northern Brazil</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Heavy rains and floods have left
46,000 people homeless in Ceara state in northeastern Brazil, civil
defense authorities said Friday.
   The Jaguaribe River, one of Ceara's main rivers, overflowed its
banks and left 7 feet of water in fields and towns in nine
municipalities, according to civil defense worker Socorro Martins.
   ``The crops are lost and there are serious outbreaks of
pneumonia, fever and diarrhea,'' Miss Martins said by telephone
from Fortaleza, the Ceara state capital 1,700 miles northeast of
Rio de Janeiro.
   The homeless, mostly poor rural workers, were being put up in
schools, government buildings and canvas tents, she said.
   Gov. Tasso Jereissati declared a state of emergency in the nine
affected townships, Miss Martins said.
   Although it is the rainy season in the usually arid northeast,
showers have fallen almost without letup since February, Miss
Martins said. More rain was forecast in the coming days.
</TEXT>
