<FIRST>r i AM-Afghanistan     04-21 0315</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan,0323</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rebel Forces Fire Rockets Into Kabul</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHARON HERBAUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Moslem guerrillas fired at least 12
rockets into the capital on Friday, and initial reports said at
least two people were killed.
   Afghan soldiers returned fire, launching a barrage of missiles
into the mountains east of Kabul.
   The exchange of fire continued for about two hours. It was the
biggest strike on the capital since April 15, when 11 rockets were
fired, killing at least three people.
   The guerrillas, known as the mujahedeen or Islamic holy
warriors, are waging a war to oust the pro-Soviet government. The
rebels are supported by Pakistan, the United States, Saudi Arabia
and China.
   Rebel rockets struck the Soviet Embassy on Thursday, shattering
windows but causing no casualties, according to Soviet diplomats
who spoke on condition of anonymity. They said they did not believe
the strike, from about 20 miles northwest of the capital, was
deliberate.
   The United States closed its embassy in Kabul before Soviet
troops completed their withdrawal Feb. 15. Since then, Moslem
insurgents have attacked Kabul intermittently but have concentrated
their firepower on the strategic eastern city of Jalalabad.
   Radio Kabul, monitored in Pakistan, reported Thursday that rebel
rocket attacks on Jalalabad had killed two people. The guerrillas
reportedly were blasting the city from key positions to the south
and east, said Radio Kabul. The radio also said four people were
hurt Thursday when rockets landed in Kabul.
   Jalalabad's fall would be considered a major victory for the
rebels. It would be the biggest city they have captured and would
be a major blow to the morale of the government. Western observers
also have predicted a domino effect, ending with the capital of
Kabul.
   Soviet troops entered Afghanistan in December 1979 to back the
government and withdrew the last of their troops in February under
a U.N.-mediated accord.
</TEXT>
