<FIRST>r a AM-BattleshipGrief 1stLd-Writethru a0629 04-21 0417</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Battleship Grief, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0629,0424</SECOND>
<HEAD>Psychiatrists Say Sailors Will Need Help Working Through Emotions</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs last graf to CORRECT attribution to Mateczun.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Battleship Memorial, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HILARY APPELMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The sailors who survived the explosion
aboard the USS Iowa will need help coping with what may be the
first tragedy many of them have experienced, two psychiatrists said
Friday.
   Forty-seven crewmen, most of whom were in their early 20s, died
in the fiery explosion of a gun turret Wednesday as the battleship
took part in training exercises near Puerto Rico.
   ``Many aboard the ship are younger and may not have had to
experience grief before,'' said Navy psychiatrist Cmdr. John
Mateczun, who works with the Portsmouth-based Special Psychiatric
Rapid Intervention Team, or SPRINT.
   ``They won't have a model and may feel they can't have certain
emotions or can't cry. They may feel some shame.''
   ``It's a whole developmental task that is new for them,'' said
Dr. Jack Corazzini, director of university counseling services at
Virginia Commonwealth University in Richmond.
   Initial reactions to the tragedy by surviving crew members may
include shock and disbelief, relief they weren't killed, and guilt
over being alive when companions are not, Corazzini said. He said
it is important that the survivors talk about their feelings to
ward off problems later.
   A SPRINT team of mental health professionals boarded the Iowa
when it anchored off Puerto Rico to remove the bodies of the dead.
The team works with those at greatest risk of suffering from the
tragedy, Mateczun said, including friends of the men killed and
those whose lives were in the greatest danger during the explosion
and fire.
   ``A lot of what we do is educational,'' he said. ``We want to
give people information about what normal human reaction is to
extremely abnormal events.
   ``When people start talking about emotions, then others can say,
`Gee, I felt that way too.' Then they're no longer isolated. They
can say, `I was scared, I was afraid I was going to die,' and know
this is a normal human response. That has terrific therapeutic
value.''
   Follow-up counseling is crucial, both psychiatrists said.
   Corazzini said six months or six years later, an event that
triggers a memory of the tragedy will cause ``pain just like it was
yesterday'' among survivors.
   ``The 19th of April will forever be in these people's hearts and
minds,'' he said. ``It's not like you're ever cured of the grief,''
said Mateczun.
</TEXT>
