<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-89 1655EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-China-Economy     04-21 0542</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Economy,0559</SECOND>
<HEAD>Economic Slowdown Has Only Limited Success, Official Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China's seven-month austerity program has managed
to keep a lid on economic growth but has yet to solve problems of
inflation, overspending and excess investment, the government said
Friday.
   Zhang Zhongji of the State Statistical Bureau said industrial
output value for the first quarter of 1989 increased by 10.4
percent to $79 billion.
   That was well down from an industrial growth rate of more than
20 percent in 1988, although the March growth rate surged to 14
percent after two straight months in the 8 percent range.
   ``We have achieved initial results'' in cooling off the economy,
Zhang said. But he added that inflation is still too high,
``contradictions'' in the economy are worsening and restoring
economic order ``is still very difficult.''
   The government in September announced that for a two-three year
period there would be severe restrictions on new credit, cutbacks
in government spending and cancellations of construction projects.
It said economic reforms, including price reforms, would be put off
until inflation and excessive growth are overcome.
   Zhang said retail prices were unchanged from February to March,
but were up 27.9 percent compared with the same period last year.
The inflation rate has been over 30 percent in most Chinese cities
during the past year.
   Retail sales were up 22.6 percent to $56.4 billion, he said.
   Zhang said the government's drive to boost grain production
after four straight disappointing harvests appeared to be going
well. He said national funding for agricultural production was up
31.3 percent in the first quarter, to $746 million.
   But the economy continued to be plagued by what Zhang called the
``three highs and two irrationals.''
   The highs were inflation, government spending and the soaring
growth of consumer demand. He said government offices have ignored
demands for spending cutbacks, and that spending increased 16.3
percent in the first quarter while revenues were up only 4.9
percent.
   Zhang said the surplus purchasing power of households has hit
$135 billion and that worker bonuses and allowances were up 39 and
59 percent despite the austerity drive.
   The ``irrationals'' were the continued growth of inefficient and
non-productive industries and misplaced investment.
   Energy-wasting, consumer-oriented industries continue to lead
growth, while state-run basic and heavy industries lag behind, he
said. Production of color TV sets was up 53 percent, refrigerators
by 50 percent and cassette recorders by 22 percent.
   Electricity output, meanwhile, was up only 3 percent, coal 5.6
percent and crude oil output fell slightly. Factories have had to
cut back operating hours because of an increasingly serious energy
shortage.
   Although state investment in capital construction projects
dropped 8.3 percent to $2 billion, local governments increased
spending by 14.8 percent to $1.56 billion.
   Zhang said many local governments have taken a ``wait-and-see''
approach to Beijing orders to cancel or postpone construction
projects.
   Zhang said foreign trade on a customs statistics basis was up
15.5 percent in the first quarter to $21.2 billion. Exports were up
9.4 percent to $9.66 billion, and imports by 21.3 percent to $11.5
billion.
   He said the government had had little success in stopping the
import of luxury consumer items such as cars, motorcycles, cameras
and appliances.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
