<HEAD>Polish Leader to Visit Britain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Polish leader Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski will visit
Britain, probably in June, the foreign secretary said Friday.
   Sir Geoffrey Howe indicated the forthcoming visit by Jaruzelski
was part of a series of contacts between Britain and East European
countries now embarking on reforms.
   He welcomed moves toward greater democracy in Poland and the
legalization of the independent trade union Solidarity.
   At a dinner, the foreign secretary also suggested Britain was
ready to offer unspecified help to Poland.
   ``We believe that Poland has taken a decisive step forward. And
so in the weeks and months ahead if that progress is sustained we
shall be identifying with our friends, allies and the various
international bodies concerned the positive ways in which we can
help,'' Howe said.
   He renewed his warning that ``hard-headed calculation'' was
still needed when evaluating changes taking place in the Soviet
Union.
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher visited Poland in November 1988.
