<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-89 1709EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-AlohaAwards     04-21 0413</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Aloha Awards,410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Aloha Pilot, Crew Receive Award, Credit `Incredible Luck'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The pilot and surviving crew of the Aloha
Airlines jetliner that ripped open over Hawaii a year ago received
awards for heroism Friday as a federal agency neared the end of its
investigation of the incident.
   The pilot of the now-scrapped Boeing 737, Robert Schornstheimer,
credited ``incredible luck'' for his being able to land the plane
safely after a 20-foot section of fuselage tore away last April 28.
Chief flight attendant Clarabelle Lansing was flung out of the
airliner to her death, but all 95 other people aboard survived.
   The National Transportation Safety Board has tentatively set May
9 for final discussion of possible causes of the incident and
recommendations to prevent it from happening again. The Federal
Aviation Administration has already issued several orders for
increased inspections, repairs and replacements as a result of that
and other problems with older aircraft.
   Schornstheimer, accepting the Aeroclub of Washington award from
Transportation Secretary Samuel Skinner, said new airliners should
not be designed with so much sophisticated technology that it gets
in the way of a pilot flying manually in an emergency.
   ``Once programmed by pilots, state-of-the-art aircraft computers
can almost auto fly the airplane from one airport to another. We
must consider what would have happened to our aircraft without
humans not only being at the controls but with maintained
proficiency to fly it,'' Schornstheimer said.
   ``Pilots do not like to be totally reliant on these
ever-more-complex systems,'' he said.
   Also receiving awards were the flight's first officer, Madeline
``Mimi'' Tompkins, who is now an airline captain, and flight
attendants Michelle Honda and Jane Sato-Tomita. The club, which was
founded in 1909 to foster interest in aviation, also gave a
posthumous award to Ms. Lansing.
   Skinner read a letter to the crew from President Bush which said
their feat ``speaks eloquently of the strength of the human
spirit.'' The crew has received other awards and met with Bush last
year when he was vice president.
   ``Men and women around the globe will long remember that
miraculous landing and the bravery and skill that you ...
demonstrated on that fateful day,'' Bush wrote.
   Skinner, at the end of the ceremony, said that despite the
incident which has increased concern over aging airliners, travel
by plane is still one of the safest modes of transportation and
U.S. air travel is ``the safest in the world.''
</TEXT>
