<FIRST>r w AM-Pentagon-Spill     04-21 0418</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pentagon-Spill,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-Tanker Spill</HEAD>
<HEAD>Soviet Skimmer Bigger Than Any U.S. Has</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. military does not have an oil
skimming vessel as large as the 425-foot long Soviet ship
Vaidagubski, but has sent a fleet of smaller vessels to the cleanup
effort off the coast of Alaska, Pentagon spokesmen said Friday.
   The Army has dispatched two specially fitted dredges to help
skim the oil, the Essayons, 350-feet long, and the Yaquina, 200
feet long, said Ed Greene, a spokesman for the U.S. Army Corps of
Engineers, which owns the vessels.
   The Yaquina, based in Portland, Ore., reached the stricken area
on Wednesday and has collected an estimated 1,500 tons of oil, said
Maj. Kathy Wood, a Pentagon spokeswoman. The Essayons, based in San
Francisco, is being sent to the tip of the Kenai Peninsula, she
said.
   The Navy has 22 smaller skimmers at work off the Alaskan coast,
said Wood.
   Each skimmer is 36 feet long and 12 feet wide. Two boats pull
each skimmer and a 300-foot oil boom through the water. Every hour,
the skimmer can suck up 3,600 gallons of liquid, which is collected
in a bladder and can be pumped into another ship or replaced with
another bladder, said Wood.
   Additionally, a Navy amphibious transport dock, the USS Juneau,
is en route and expected to arrive at Prince William Sound on
Monday, Wood said. The Juneau, 570 feet long and 84 feet abeam, is
equipped with two CH-46 Sea Knight helicopters, can house 900
people and has been loaded with oil skimming, dredge and bladder
materials.
   ``It will provide a command and control capability in the sound
which we do not currently have,'' said Wood.
   The Army Corps of Engineers has two dredges that are larger than
the Essayons and Yaquina, the Wheeler, 409 feet long, stationed in
the Gulf of Mexico, and the McFarland, 300 feet long, stationed on
the Atlantic Coast.
   The Coast Guard, which has taken over direction of the cleanup
effort, has not requested use of the McFarland or the Wheeler, said
Greene. Both would need to be fitted with special equipment to skim
oil, and would require ``many days'' to transit the Panama Canal
and reach the Alaskan coast, he said.
   The first two Navy skimmers on the scene were flown in a C-5
transport plane from Travis Air Force Base, Calif., arrived there
on March 27, three days after the spill, and began work on March 28.
</TEXT>
