<FIRST>r w AM-Cattle-Feedlots     04-21 0358</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cattle-Feedlots,250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Inventories Total 9.68 Million Head</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cattle feedlot inventories in the nation's 13
leading beef states totaled 9.68 million head as of April 1, up 3
percent from a year ago and 10 percent more than two years ago, the
Agriculture Department said Friday.
   Only Arizona, Illinois, Nebraska and Washington showed declines
from a year ago, while increases were reported in California,
Colorado, Idaho, Iowa, Kansas, Minnesota, Oklahoma and Texas. South
Dakota was reported as unchanged.
   Marketings of fed cattle for slaughter during January, February
and March totaled 5.6 million head, down 4 percent from the same
period of 1988 and 3 percent below the figure for that period in
1987, the report said.
   But the placement of new cattle and calves on feed during the
first quarter of the year totaled 6.21 million head, up 7 percent
from last year and 9 percent more than two years ago.
   That was the largest first-quarter placement of cattle in
feedlots in 18 years, the report said.
   Cattle feeders indicated they expect to market 6.09 million head
during April, May and June, up 4 percent from last year's second
quarter and 8 percent more than in 1987, the report said.
   State feedlot cattle inventories are listed here for the 13
states, which account for about 85 percent of the nation's beef.
The first number is the number of cattle, in thousands, as of April
1, and the second number is the percentage of a year earlier.
