<HEAD>Bush Rewards Lasker</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush on Friday bestowed the
congressional medal on medical research philanthropist Mary Lasker,
honoring her for longtime support of research and education in such
areas as cancer, heart disease and cerebral palsy.
   Bush, in a Rose Garden presentation ceremony, told Mrs. Lasker
she was an example of what he means when he speaks of ``1,000
points of light'' as the many components of society that work to
improve life for everyone.
   ``We're here today to honor a veritable beacon of light, a woman
who has focused an enormous amount of energy on finding solutions
to life-threatening diseases.
   Mrs. Lasker and her husband in 1942 founded the Albert and Mary
Lasker Foundation to encourage medical research and public
awareness of crippling diseases.
   She urged the president to beef up support for the National
Institutes of Health, where the Mary W. Lasker Center for Health
Research and Education conducts medical research.
   ``We look to you now, Mr. President, for leadership and helping
to support at the National Institutes,'' she said. ``Cancer still
kills 500,000 people a year in this country, more people than have
been killed in all our wars combined.''
   Mrs. Lasker also has been involved in beautification efforts in
Washington, and has donated more than 1 million daffodil bulbs for
Rock Creek Park and Lady Byrd Johnson Park, the White House said.
   The medal she was awarded Friday was voted by Congress, and was
struck by the U.S. Mint.
