<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-89 1758EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Sakharov     04-21 0460</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sakharov,0474</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sakharov Completes Comeback With Congressional Victory</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Human rights activist Andrei D. Sakharov, sent
into internal exile for criticizing the Soviet intervention in
Afghanistan, completed his political rehabilitation by winning a
seat in the new national legislature.
   Sakharov's election to the Congress of People's Deputies ``will
be a great success for perestroika,'' said one of his backers,
Alexander Sobianen, using the word for President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev's reform program.
   Sakharov's victory was among the results of balloting Thursday
by members of the prestigious Academy of Sciences for 12 seats in
the new parliament.
   Also elected were space scientist Roald Z. Sagdeev, economist
Nikolai Shmelev and Georgy A. Arbatov, director of the U.S.A. and
Canada Institute, the official Tass news agency reported Friday.
   Tass said Shmelev, who has proposed radical solutions to the
Soviet Union's economic problems, won the most votes, 869 of 1,101.
Sakharov received 806 and Sagdeev received 739, it said.
   Sakharov, Sagdeev and Shmelev were among a slate of reformers on
the list of 28 candidates. Other reformers who won election were
Vitaly Ginzburg and Yuri Karyakin, Tass said.
   The 2,250-member congress is to meet for the first time on May
25 to choose from among its members the country's president and a
Supreme Soviet, which will make policy for the nation.
   Twenty seats in the congress have been reserved for members of
the academy. Sakharov originally was nominated in January, but the
academy's screening committee eliminated him and other reformers
when it cut the list of candidates on the final ballot from more
than 100 to 23.
   However, Sakharov's supporters, charged the nominees were
old-style academic bureaucrats and organized a campaign to reject
them. In the first election last month, only eight of the 23 were
approved.
   This time, 28 candidates were nominated for the 12 seats still
open, and Sakharov, Sagdeev, Shmelev and other reformers were
nominated once again.
   Sakharov, winner of the 1975 Nobel Peace Prize for his rights
activities, was exiled to the closed city of Gorky in January 1980
for criticizing the Soviet intervention in Afghanistan. In 1986,
Gorbachev allowed him to return to Moscow.
   Sakharov has since resumed his scientific work and continues to
speak out on social issues. He supports Gorbachev's reforms but
criticizes what he sees as efforts to slow or reverse them.
   The Communist Party, trade unions and social and professional
groups such as the academy will elect 750 congressional members.
The 1,500 others are elected from geographical districts.
   In balloting for the geographical districts on March 26, voters
rejected dozens of top party and government officials, many of whom
were running unopposed.
   Repeat elections will be held May 14 for almost 200 seats that
remain unfilled.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
