<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Economy     04-21 0481</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Economy,0497</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ideologist Warns Flood of Money Could Sink Perestroika</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN IAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet economic reform is in danger of drowning in
a flood of too much money in circulation, the Kremlin's chief
ideologist warned Friday.
   Vadim A. Medvedev, speaking at a meeting to celebrate the 119th
anniversary of Soviet founder Vladimir I. Lenin's birth, said if
the country ``can't curb the stream of money that has overflowed,''
then the result could be ``the failure of economic reform.''
   Medvedev was referring to the fact that Soviet citizens have
lots of money but little to buy in the stores. As a result, new
shipments of consumer goods sell out quickly and many items are
hard to find.
   A senior government statistician revealed Friday the problem is
worsening.
   Average wages rose 9.5 percent in the first three months of
1989, compared with the same period a year earlier. But
productivity increased just 4.5 percent and consumer goods
production rose 5.8 percent, said Nikolai G. Belov, first deputy
chief of the state statistics board.
   Soviet statistics, unlike Western ones, do not account for
inflation.
   ``Wages have risen much faster than projected, much faster than
productivity of labor, which adversely affects the market
situation,'' Belov said.
   The average wage of Soviet workers jumped from $347 to $379 a
month in the first three months, Belov said.
   As a result of the deficit of goods, Soviets are saving massive
amounts of money. Belov said about $497 billion is being kept in
savings accounts and is out of circulation.
   Medvedev, the member of the ruling Politburo responsible for
ideology, culture and propaganda, said that ``without a hard,
stable ruble, the whole system of economic regulators cannot work.''
   The Soviet ruble-exchange rate is set by the government at $1.62
per ruble, but the black market rate is 12 cents to 25 cents per
ruble.
   Medvedev also said the move toward a more market-oriented
economy is proceeding slower than desired. Factories are supposed
to be developing their own suppliers and customers instead of
depending on centralized allocations.
   He also cited pricing and the government deficit as key
problems. Soviet prices are set by bureaucrats with no regard to
cost of production. The budget deficit is estimated at $160 billion
this year.
   The ideologist emphasized the justice of paying people according
to their ability and output. President Mikhail S. Gorbachev has
also said the old system of encouraging equality must end.
   ``Demagogic calls to equalize everything and everybody are alien
to socialism,'' Medvedev said.
   The 60-year-old ideologist spoke in the giant hall of the
Kremlin's Palace of Congresses before the Politburo and a capacity
audience of workers, military officers and other dignitaries.
   Medvedev has come out in favor of a moderate course for
perestroika, saying the party is steering a course between
extremists who want either no reform or too much, too fast.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
