<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-89 1630EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-DuckMonster Bjt   04-21 0670</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Duck Monster, Bjt,650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Search for Duck-Eating `Monster' Ends</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The search for a mysterious ``monster from the
black lagoon'' that may be gobbling helpless baby ducklings in a
downtown nature pond ended Friday with the sighting of two well-fed
catfish swishing lazily through the shallows.
   The catfish were spotted by National Park Service ranger Helen
Horton, who was slogging through the muck wearing rubber hip waders
and armed with a long-handled rake and fish net after the pond,
normally about three feet deep, had been all but drained.
   ``The catfish are a strong possibility,'' pronounced her boss,
biological engineer John Hoke. ``They just love ducks. Yes, the
catfish are an awfully good smoking gun.''
   Hoke said he would refill the pond outside the main entrance to
Interior Department headquarters and set an underwater trap for the
catfish as soon as possible. Meantime, the remaining three
ducklings will have to take their chances on survival.
   The ducklings' plight has aroused the sympathy and worried
concern of scores of federal office workers who stroll past Bolivar
Pond or pause for a midday picnic in the small, surrounding park
that also features an equestrian statue of South American liberator
Simon Bolivar.
   A female mallard duck that had taken up residence in the pond
with several male companions gave birth to 11 ducklings last week.
On Monday, nine of the fluffy, yellow-faced babies remained. The
next day, there were seven.
   Kathie O'Toole, an Interior Department budget analyst, became
alarmed and telephoned the Park Service. She feared the ducklings
were victims of a snapping turtle. Workmen began slowly draining
the pond on Thursday to try to find what a Park Service spokesman
jokingly called ``the monster from the black lagoon.''
   By Friday morning, only three ducklings were left, darting here
and there under the protective gaze of their mother.
   ``Jeez, it's devastating,'' said Cindy Archer, a graphic artist
from nearby American Red Cross headquarters who has visited the
pond frequently this week.
   Other passersby, including bemedaled Daughters of the American
Revolution conventioneers, peered anxiously down at the remaining
ducklings. Some tossed them bread crumbs or popcorn.
   ``I can see it _ the Loch Ness monster comes up at night and ...
glump!'' said one woman. ``Maybe there's an alligator in there,''
said another.
   Ms. Horton's rake failed to uncover any snapping turtles under
the large, partially submerged log or the planters containing
irises, cattails and spiky water cannon, or hiding on a little
island in the shadow of a bald cypress.
   Other early suspects were racoons or rats known to inhabit
neighboring shrubbery or burrows. Both animals are meat eaters who
can swim underwater. But Hoke eliminated them because no trace of
the missing ducklings, such as feathers or scraps of meat or bone,
has ever been found.
   ``Racoons are very fastidious, even washing their hands after a
meal, but I can't believe they would eat feathers,'' he said.
``These ducklings simply disappear. It's either a gulper or people
or something that would remove them entirely.''
   Hoke said the catfish probably were dumped into the pond by what
he derisively calls ``midnight environmentalists,''
well-intentioned nature lovers who introduce hazardous creatures
into a carefully balanced natural habitat in an urban setting.
   Wildlife experts were much more sanguine about the ducklings'
disappearance than the passersby who crowded around the pond this
week.
   ``The loss of ducklings is always unfortunate but it is not
abnormal to lose 50 percent of a brood in the wild,'' said Mike
Smith, a spokesman for the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service.
``Freshly hatched ducklings are extremely vulnerable and very easy
targets for predators.''
   Said Ms. Horton:
   ``Animals have more offspring than can possibly survive, and
once they die they provide a valuable source of food for other
animals. It's all part of the natural order of things.
   ``It happens all the time in the wilderness, but it's hard for
people right here in the city to watch nature doing its thing.''
</TEXT>
