<DOCNO> AP890421-0143 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-89 1644EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-PressFreedom     04-21 0430</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Press Freedom,0443</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Says Communist States Violating Press Freedom Accord</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States accused hard-line Communist
states on Friday of repeatedly violating an East-West accord on
free speech. As one example, it cited the imprisonment of
Czechoslovak playwright Vaclav Havel.
   Dusan Spacil, the chief Czechoslovak delegate at a 35-nation
conference to monitor the ageement, retorted that the United States
had no right to tell East bloc countries how to comply.
   ``What gives Marks (Ambassador Leonard H. Marks, the U.S.
delegation chief) the authority to say who are the good guys and
who are the bad guys?'' asked Spacil. ``I don't think we need it.''
   Spacil attacked the U.S. delegation at the end of opening
addresses in which Western countries, headed by the United States
and Canada, singled out Czechoslovakia, Romania, Bulgaria and East
Germany as the accord's worst offenders.
   Western countries have contrasted the records of the four states
with moves in the Soviet Union, Poland and Hungary toward greater
press and other freedoms.
   The conference began Tuesday and is to last a month. It is a
follow-up to the accord signed by the 35 nations last January at
the end of the Conference on European Security and Cooperation in
Vienna. Negotiations on the accord began in Helsinki in the 1970s.
   Marks, a former director of the U.S. Information Agency, said
Havel was jailed partly on allegations that he ``sought to incite
disturbances through foreign radio broadcasts.''
   ``Is that in the spirit of Helsinki?'' said Marks.
   Marks added in his opening address to the conference that in
Romania ``foreign journalists have been ill-treated and three
Romanian journalists remain under arrest for allegedly producing a
leaflet critical of the government.''
   He accused Bulgarian authorities of suppressing the Soviet
policy of glasnost, or greater openness, and said the East German
government continued strict press censorship.
   Marks was the last speaker in four days of public sessions that
have been marked by a conciliatory attitude on the part of the
Soviet delegation while Western delegates turned on the four least
reformist of the Kremlin's allies.
   Soviet officials complained, however, that London-based Soviet
journalists have been prevented from covering a series of British
disasters because they need British government permission to travel
more than 25 miles outside London.
   Similar restrictions apply to Western journalists in the Soviet
Union.
   Recent disasters in Britain included such major international
stories as the Pan Am bombing over Scotland in December, which
killed 270 people, and a crush at a soccer match in Sheffield,
northern England a week ago, in which 95 spectators died.
</TEXT>
