<FIRST>r a AM-EagleDies     04-21 0212</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eagle Dies,0218</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eagle Featured At Bicentennial, Nature Shows Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Omega, a bald eagle that helped educate
thousands of people about the endangered species, has died at the
Dickerson Park Zoo.
   The female eagle, estimated to be about 20, suffered from an
undetermined ailment and was put to sleep Wednesday, zoo director
Mike Crocker said Friday.
   The eagle became ill in February and its condition worsened
despite treatment with drugs. Omega eventually became unable to
stand and would not eat, Crocker said.
   ``Our feeling, and the feeling of the veterinarian, was she was
suffering and there was nothing we could do for her,'' he said.
   A necropsy showed an enlarged liver, but ``we're not real
optimistic that the cause of death will be known,'' he said.
   The bird may have died from long-term effects of lead poisoning,
Crocker said. Omega was found wounded in northern Missouri in 1971
and took up residence at the Springfield zoo in 1975.
   She was the star of the Missouri Department of Conservation
Department's Eagle Days, a program designed to educate residents
about the endangered birds. ``About 10,000 people saw her in the
past year alone at Eagle Days,'' Crocker said.
   Eagles have been known to live into their 30s, Crocker said.
</TEXT>
