<FIRST>r w AM-EnergyPolicy     04-21 0370</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Energy Policy,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Congressional Aide Said Chosen To Direct Energy Policy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Energy Department has hired Linda Stuntz,
a Washington lawyer and former congressional aide, to direct the
formation of a new national energy policy, a department source said
Friday.
   Mrs. Stuntz, reached by telephone at her law office, said it
would be ``inappropriate'' for her to discuss the matter.
   ``I really can't talk about it,'' she said. She did not deny she
had taken the job.
   Henson Moore, the deputy energy secretary, disclosed earlier
this week that he had persuaded a woman, whom he declined to
identify by name, to take the policy planning job. He said she
twice turned him down before finally accepting.
   Moore said she would start May 1. Ms. Stuntz was identified by
the source, who spoke only on condition of anonymity.
   At his swearing-in ceremony on Thursday, Moore it was a top
priority of the department to ``fashion the first real national
energy policy this country has ever had.''
   Stuntz served as minority staff director of the House Energy and
Commerce Committee before joining the Washington office of the law
firm Jones, Day, Reavis &amp; Pogue.
   In a separate development, the department announced that Energy
Secretary James E. Watkins would travel to the Savannah River Site
nuclear weapons complex, near Aiken, S.C., next Friday to tour the
facilities and talk with employees.
   It will be Watkins' first visit to one of the department's 16
major weapons plants, spread across 12 states, since he took office
last month. Modernizing the cleaning up hazardous wastes at the
sites is one of Watkins' chief aims.
   The South Carolina site includes three disabled nuclear reactors
that are the nation's only source of tritium, a radioactive gas
needed in the manufacture of nuclear warheads. The department is
expected to decide later this spring or summer on a timetable for
restarting the reactors, which were closed down last spring for
safety reasons.
   The department said Watkins would be accompanied by Paul Lego,
president of Westinghouse Electric Corp., which earlier this month
took over as manager of the facility, and by chairmen of the House
and Senate armed services committees.
</TEXT>
