<HEAD>Panel to Hold Hearings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The top members of the Senate Armed Services
Committee said Friday the panel will hold hearings on the fiery
explosion aboard the USS Iowa that claimed 47 lives.
   Sens. Sam Nunn, D-Ga., the chairman, and the ranking Republican,
John Warner of Virginia, said the hearings will begin after the
Navy's board of inquiry completes its probe into the accident.
   The hearings will focus on safety procedures used in the past,
whether changes in the procedures are necessary and possible
conditions imposed on the continued use of the 16-inch weapons
found on the Iowa battleship, the senators said in a joint
statement.
   The Navy on Thursday imposed a moratorium on firing of the
16-inch weapons pending an investigation.
   Nunn and Warner also expressed their deep sorrow over the loss
of life aboard the Iowa, saying, ``It reminds us that every day,
even in peacetime, our soldiers, sailors, airmen and Marines are
serving their country `in harm's way.'''
