<SECOND>AM-People's Park,0196</SECOND>
<HEAD>Toilet Construction Thwarted</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERKELEY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Workers and campus police tore up a
concrete slab and carted away building materials at People's Park
early Friday, thwarting activists' attempts to build a permanent
toilet.
   The ``restroom brigade,'' as they called themselves, dug a
trench and poured concrete Thursday following a rally and march
commemorating the 20th anniversary of the establishment of the
``park,'' which is on land owned by the University of California at
Berkeley.
   Some of the builders camped overnight to guard materials, but
moved aside and did not confront police. The group was back working
at the site after the university crew left, vowing they would not
give up. University police watched from a short distance away.
   In 1969, activists occupied an empty lot owned by the
university. One man was killed and hundreds wounded in riots that
erupted when the university fenced in the lot and tore up greenery
planted by activists.
   Protesters tore down the fence in 1972 and the university has
allowed the public limited use of the land. But university
spokesman Ray Colvig said the university's rules include a ban on
permanent structures.
