<FIRST>r w AM-Donovan     04-21 0251</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Donovan,260</SECOND>
<HEAD>Donovan Wants Government to Pay Legal Bills</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Labor Secretary Raymond Donovan is
asking the federal government to pay $112,281 in legal bills he
says he incurred during an investigation of an alleged kickback
supposedly paid Donovan in 1977.
   Donovan and his lawyers say the legal fees and expenses are for
the period March 1987 through October 1987 in connection with the
probe by independent counsel Leon Silverman.
   The information was released Friday by a special three-member
panel of appeals court judges which appointed Silverman.
   Federal law on independent counsels provides for the government
to pay legal fees if the subject of the criminal investigation
isn't indicted.
   William Bittman, another partner, seven associates and three
paralegals of the law firm Pierson, Ball and Dowd provided legal
services and incurred expenses totaling $79,228 said the
application. Paul Curran, four associates and one paralegal of the
firm Kaye, Scholer, Fierman, Hays and Handler are seeking $33,052
in fees and expenses.
   Donovan was cleared in the probe of accusations that he may have
lied when he denied knowing anything about the alleged kickback
scheme which involved a former supplier of Schiavone Construction
Co. where Donovan was working at the time.
   Silverman concluded that although there was ``some evidence to
support an indictment,'' a conviction is ``unlikely'' and charges
``not warranted.''
   One witness in the probe was elderly, ailing and had a failing
memory, said Silverman, while another was a convicted felon
awaiting sentencing who had given inconsistent statements.
</TEXT>
