<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-89 1958EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Solzhenitsyn     04-21 0370</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Solzhenitsyn,0385</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Magazine To Publish Parts Of `The Gulag Archipelago'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet literary journal will publish selections
from ``The Gulag Archipelago,'' Alexander Solzhenitsyn's banned
book on Stalin's labor camps, a secretary at the magazine said
Friday.
   Some chapters from the long work will appear this year in the
monthly magazine Novy Mir, Valentina Ivanovna said in a telephone
interview.
   She refused to say who in the Soviet leadership had approved
publication of the gripping tale of repression under Stalin.
   In November, Communist Party ideology chief Vadim A. Medvedev
told a news conference that said exposing Soviets to such books
would undermine society.
   ``I am against the publication of a number works by
Solzhenitsyn, and in the first place such works as `Lenin in
Zurich' and `The Gulag Archipelago,''' he said.
   But The Washington Post on Friday quoted Novy Mir's chief
editor, Sergei P. Zalygin, as saying in an interview that President
Mikhail S. Gorbachev supported publication of Solzhenitsyn's works.
Ms. Ivanovna said Zalygin was unreachable.
   Novy Mir published Solzhenitsyn's short novel, ``One Day in the
Life of Ivan Denisovich'' in November 1962.
   The Gulag is a triology that maintains widescale political
repression began in the Soviet Union under founder Vladimir I.
Lenin.
   Zalygin said last year he was negotiating for the rights to
print Solzhenitsyn's novel ``Cancer Ward.'' Ms. Ivanovna said no
decision had been made about publishing works of Solzhenitsyn other
than the Gulag.
   Several writers, artists and activists have clamored for
publication of Solzhenitsyn's works, citing Gorbachev's policy of
glasnost, which among other things allows re-examination of sore
points in Soviet history like Stalin's reign of terror.
   In February, a journal of the Soviet Peace Committee titled
Twentieth Century and Peace carried a commentary crediting
Solzhenitsyn for helping pave the way for Gorbachev's reforms.
   The reforms have led to publication of Soviet authors that had
been long banned. Others that have come into the open include the
novel ``Doctor Zhivago'' by Boris Pasternak and the political
satire ``Heart of a Dog'' by Mikhail Bulgakov.
   Solzhenitsyn was arrested, branded a traitor and expelled for
his writings.
   Solzhenitsyn, 70, gained U.S. citizenship in 1974. A Nobel
laureate, he is living in rural isolation in Vermont.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
