<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-89 2014EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-OklahomaCentennial     04-21 0611</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oklahoma Centennial,0630</SECOND>
<HEAD>Celebrants Gather For Centennial Of Land Rush</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto KO4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GIL BROYLES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GUTHRIE, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mile-long wagon train creaked into this
former territorial capital Friday to the cheers of celebrants
gathering for the centennial of the state's first historic land
rush.
   An estimated 1,000 people came to the windswept banks of the
Cimarron River to greet the wagons and horseback riders who trekked
75 miles from Caldwell and Arkansas City, Kan., to re-trace the
route of their pioneer predecessors.
   On April 22, 1889, more than 40,000 hopeful settlers converged
on the borders of the 2 million-acre Unassigned Lands in what is
now central Oklahoma.
   But in Oklahoma City, 25 miles to the south, Native Americans at
a Capitol steps rally were told that they should no more celebrate
the centennial of the run than Jews should celebrate the Holocaust.
   ``It offends me that Indian tax dollars are going to promote
this celebration,'' said Frances Wise, director of Oklahoma City's
Native American Center.
   ``The only time the state of Oklahoma tries to be nice to us ...
is when they want us to sing and dance for them,'' she said.
   President Benjamin Harrison authorized white settlement of the
former Indian land. The result was a mad dash for 160-acre parcels
and town lots in what was called ``Harrison's Hoss Race.''
   Oklahomans trace their state's roots to the Run of '89 at noon
on that April 22nd.
   It was the first in a series of land openings _ rushes,
lotteries, allotments and biddings _ that paved the way for
Oklahoma to become the 46th state in 1907.
   Guthrie served as the state's capital until 1910 and its
architecture has remained largely frozen in the Victorian era. Some
40 blocks of the town of 10,000 is in the National Register of
Historic Places.
   Women in 19th century garb strolled the town's brick sidewalks
Friday. Cavalry troops pounded in tent pegs to bivouac on a grassy
downtown lot while schoolchildren arrived by the busload to sample
the town's historic fare.
   The town primped for a Saturday crowd officials estimated would
be around 50,000. Officials prepared for gigantic traffic jams
should the total go higher.
   ``Any more and I think we'll be walking on each other,'' said
Carl Sachs, Guthrie Economic Development director. ``I don't think
there's anything we can do to stop it now.''
   In Oklahoma City, an estimated 10,000 people lined downtown
streets Friday afternoon to cheer high school bands, waving
politicians and centennial parade floats.
   Both Guthrie and Oklahoma City sprang full-grown from the
prairie as tent cities of 10,000 on the day of the run, which
settled part or all of six counties.
   Ms. Wise and other speakers said Friday's two-hour rally, which
culminated in a five-mile march through downtown Oklahoma City
hours before the start of the centennial parade, was the first in a
series of counter events scheduled for the centennial year.
   Some of the marchers wore black armbands and many wore T-shirts
proclaiming ``Sooners Run Over Indian Nation.'' Other T-shirts had
a picture of a covered wagon and the slogan, ``There Goes the
Neighborhood.''
   Historians say there is little argument that the government
cheated Indians of their land in Oklahoma. Organizers of centennial
observances say they have tried to be sensitive to Indian concerns.
   Wilma Mankiller, chief of the Cherokee Nation of Oklahoma, said
her primary concern is that celebrators recognize the land rush did
not bring the first civilization to Oklahoma.
   The Cherokees and other tribes in eastern Oklahoma had a
Democratic government, brick buildings, and some of the nation's
first schools for women 50 years earlier, she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890421-0161 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-89 2014EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-PeaceReport     04-21 0565</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Peace Report,0580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Peace Movement At A `Difficult Juncture,' New Report Concludes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANA KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's peace movement is at a difficult
juncture as concerns over the environment, AIDS, and the homeless
overshadow powderkegs like the Middle East, South Africa and
Central America, a new report concludes.
   Despite shifting attentions, peace activism has become a
national institution, having consolidated power and influence in
the arms control establishment and in citizens groups throughout
the country, the report says.
   The next challenge, says the inaugural issue of what will be a
yearly report, is to meld peace activism with the changing issues
of the 1990s _ with the Vietnam war a distant memory and the Soviet
Union a lessening threat.
   ``Our task now is make policymakers realize the Cold War is
winding down,'' said John Tirman, editor of the Annual Review of
Peace Activism and head of the Boston-based Winston Foundation for
World Peace.
   ``The kind of bitter, ideological military confrontation that
has marked the last 40 years is dissipating. We're trying to
develop a more positive vision of change.''
   The report has 15 essays by political scientists, activists and
environmentalists on such topics as ``The Plutonium Challenge in
the American West,'' ``The Human Rights Challenge'' and ``The
Battle for Nuclear Age Education.''
   Since its inception in the mid-1960s during the Vietnam war, the
peace movement has gone through two distinct stages, Tirman said.
The youth-oriented activism of the Vietnam era lasted until about
1973, he said.
   But when people began turning their attention to the environment
and women's issues, the peace movement waned. The movement was not
revived until then-President Jimmy Carter's decision to build and
deploy the MX missile in 1979, and later President Reagan's
description of the Soviet Union as the `'evil empire.''
   The peace movement's image must stay in step with the times or
risk losing touch with issues of international security and the
environment that threaten the country as much as the Vietnam war
two decades ago, Tirman said.
   ``Until 1986, this movement was basically in opposition to
something,'' Tirman said. ``Now we're in a state of flux. We need
to address other issues, like the fact that the U.S. is being left
with a $300 billion defense budget at a time when Gorbachev is
ahead of us in making concessions.''
   Though still predominantly a ``white, middle class'' movement,
peace activism has claimed a more diverse membership in recent
years.
   ``It's everyone from homemakers concerned about what their
children eat to businessmen and women angry at the amount of waste
in the Pentagon to people who are just plain angry about the
nuclear war,'' said Tirman.
   As a result, the peace movement has helped shape policy more
effectively than in the past, Tirman said.
   Tirman credits the peace movement with Reagan's decision to sign
the Intermediate-range Nuclear Forces Treaty, although some
contributors to the report say peace activism in the 1980s was only
moderately successful.
   ``In the end, the peace movement of the Reagan era had to settle
for indirect influence and partial success,'' writes Pam Solo in a
review article entitled ``The Reagan Era: The Freeze Campaign and
Political Power.''
   More than $50 million is donated toward the peace movement every
year, according to the report. There are more than 50 research
organizations and about 7,300 smaller groups dedicated to the peace
movement.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890421-0162 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-89 2022EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     04-21 0425</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0431</SECOND>
<HEAD>Record Heat in Plains and Southwest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Temperatures were in the 70s or 80s across much of the nation
Friday with records set as readings reached into the 80s to around
90 degrees across the central and southern Plains and into the mid
90s in southwest Texas.
   Temperatures were in the 50s and 60s from North Dakota through
the upper Great Lakes into New England and from the central and
northern Pacific Coast into the northern Rockies.
   A cold front draped across the northwestern U.S. Showers and a
few thunderstorms were scattered from the northern Rockies into the
central Pacific Coast region. Gusty thunderstorm winds flipped an
awning over and carried it up to 70 feet near Great Falls, Mont.
   Records were broken for this date in Colorado in Alamosa, where
it was 78, breaking a 1958 record of 77 and in Colorado Springs
where it was 82, breaking a 1960 record of 81. Denver, with 85,
tied its 1960 record. Goodland, Texas, broke a 1925 record of 86
with a high of 87. Lincoln, Neb., with 91 broke a 1980 record of
90; Scottsbluff, Neb., with 91, broke a 1980 record of 88; and in
Tucson, Ariz., where it was 100, a 1965 record of 98 was broken.
   The low in the nation Friday was 24 degrees at Concord, N.H.;
Houlton, Maine; Massena, N.Y., and Montpelier and St. Johnsbury, Vt.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. ranged from 39 degrees
at Klamath Falls, Ore., to 100 degrees at Tucson, Ariz.
   The forecast for Saturday called for widespread showers and
widely scattered thunderstorms from the Pacific Northwest through
the northern Plateau into the northern Rockies. Widely scattered
showers were expected from eastern North Dakota and western
Minnesota into southwest Wisconsin and across northern Maine. Much
of the remainder of the nation was expected to be sunny and warm.
   High temperatures were forecast for the 70s or 80s across much
of the nation. Highs in the 60s were predicted from the Northern
California coast through the Great Basin into the northern Rockies
with highs in the 50s across the Pacific Northwest and in the 50s
and 60s from the upper Great Lakes through the central Appalachians
into the mid-Atlantic Coast. Highs were predicted in the 40s from
the northeastern parts of the Great Lakes into much of New England.
Temperatures in the 90s were expected from the Desert Southwest
through the southern Rockies into the central and southern high
Plains and in the Rio Grande Valley of Texas.
</TEXT>
