<FIRST>r w AM-US-Mideast     04-21 0264</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Mideast,270</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Praises Lebanon Proposal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. officials said Friday the United States
is energetically supporting an Arab League proposal for cease-fire
in Lebanon and is not tilting to Syria.
   ``We very strongly support this effort by the Arab League and
we're very encouraged by the reports that we've seen'' about it,
State Department spokesman Richard Boucher said.
   He said the United States is ``engaged in an energetic
initiative to support the Arab League...we're talking to the Arab
League, we're talking to the Syrians, we're talking to the parties
in Lebanon about the Arab League initiative and our hopes and our
support that it go forward.''
   He described the Arab League proposal as ``a peace plan'' that
involves cease-fire negotiations with Syria on its role in Lebanon
and a dialogue among Lebanese leaders for political reform.
   At the White House, President Bush met a group of
Lebanese-American leaders, and across the street 2,000 people
demonstrated to urge the Bush administration to use pressure to get
Syria to withdraw its troops from Lebanon and halt attacks against
Lebanese Christian enclaves.
   Presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said the United States
would like to see a cease-fire and ``an end to violence on all
sides by all parties.''
   Boucher brushed aside Palestine Liberation Organization leader
Yasser Arafat's latest proposal to meet Secretary of State James
Baker III, saying merely that current U.S.-PLO meetings would
continue in Tunis.
   On PLO support of elections in Israeli-occupied areas, Boucher
said, ``We've noted what he said about the election idea. We want
to continue to explore the idea.''
