<DOCNO> AP890421-0165 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-89 2034EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Korea     04-21 0422</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea,0437</SECOND>
<HEAD>Radical Students Aligned with Militant Unions Battle Police</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY RENFREW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of radical students aligned
with militant labor unions battled police Friday around university
campuses in Seoul and the southeastern cities of Kwangju and Iri.
   The Defense Ministry announced Friday it would mobilize up to
80,000 military technicians and engineers to keep key industries
running if workers go on strike.
   The government of President Roh Tae-woo said this week it would
use troops to keep important industries operating.
   The government has said strikes in recent months have cost the
economy $2 billion in lost production.
   More than 2,000 students left the campuses of Konkuk, Hankook,
Seoul National and Yonsei universitites in Seoul and used firebombs
and rocks to fight with police who respondsed with volleys of tear
gas.
   ``Punish Roh Tae-woo!'' and ``Yankee go home!'' the students
yelled as they beat drums and brass gongs in the third day of
campus demonstrations in the capital.
   The Yonhap news agency reported hundreds of student activists
clashed with police in Kwangju and Iri.
   Police officials said some people were injured but they had no
figures on the number or how many arrests were made.
   In other developments, National Assemblyman Suh Suk-jae was
arrested on charges of bribing a candidate to drop out of a
by-election, prosecutors announced.
   They said Suh,a member of the opposition Reunification
Democratic Party, had paid $75,000 to candicate Lee Hong-sup of the
minor New Democratic Republican Party to abandon the race in the
four-way election Friday in the eastern electoral district of
Tonhgae.
   The candidate of the governing Democratic Justice Party won the
seat. The scandal surfaced just before the election when Lee
acknowledged receiving money from Suh. Lee subsequently was
arrested and accused of accepting a bribe.
   Suh resigned as secretary-general of the Reunification
Democratic Party on Saturday after telling a news conference he had
given money to Lee and assumed responsibility for the incident.
   Yonhap reported immigration authorities refused to grant
permission to land to 49 Vietnamese boat people rescued at sea by a
British freighter.
   It said the permission was denied because South Korea's only
camp for such refugees is overcrowded. The camp has 235 Vietnamese,
55 more than it can accommodate, according to the agency.
   Yonhap said the boat people were picked up April 16 betwen
Malaysia and Vietnam by the British vessel Cardigan Bay.
   Since 1976 South Korea has temporarily accepted about 2,000
Vietnamese refugees with the condition they resettle in third
nations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
