<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-89 2035EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Sudan     04-21 0462</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sudan,0474</SECOND>
<HEAD>Unitd Nations Begins Relief Shipments To Southern Sudan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KAMPALA, Uganda (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A huge C-130 cargo plane carrying 15{
tons of corn landed in the southern Sudanese city of Torit on
Friday as the United Nations started up relief operations after a
deadly ambush caused a three-day delay.
   Paul Mitchell, a spokesman for the United Nations' Operation
Lifeline Sudan, told the Associated Press the plane arrived safely
in the beleaguered town after leaving Uganda's Entebbe airport
before dawn.
   A 47-truck relief convoy carrying 1,100 tons to southern Sudan
also began Friday with the first trucks rolling out of Kampala
before noon, said Gote Hertz, a U.N. spokesman in Kampala.
   Mitchell said the C-130, leased from and operated by the
Miami-based Southern Air Transport company, will make three flights
daily to Torit until it has delivered 1,100 tons.
   The airlift and convoy are part of a massive, $132 million U.N.
effort to stock more than 110,000 tons of food and supplies in
wartorn southern Sudan before heavy seasonal rains begin in four
weeks.
   The operation hopes to avoid a repetition of last year's
tragedy, when up to 500,000 people died of famine induced by
drought, floods and a rebellion by the Sudan People's Liberation
Army.
   The Liberation Army began its rebellion in early 1983, demanding
greater autonomy and economic reforms in the three southern
provinces of Bahr Ghazal, Upper Nile and Equatoria.
   The first U.N. convoy in rebel-held southern Sudan was ambushed
on Tuesday as it traveled west to Torit from the Sudan People's
Liberation Army base of Kapoeta. Eight rebel escorts were killed
and the lead truck was destroyed. U.N. officials have not assessed
blame, but suspicion fell on tribal raiders, government troops or
government militias fighting the rebels.
   Mitchell said Friday's flight represented the start of the first
significant shipment of relief food to Torit. The Norwegian
People's Aid and World Vision relief agencies have delivered just
under 100 tons to Torit since April 1, he said.
   The C-130 until Tuesday was one of two planes carrying food into
the southern Sudanese provincial capital of Juba, which is
continuing to receive 55 tons of relief supplies daily on the
remaining C-130, said Hertz.
   He said the truck convoy will head first to the Sudanese border
town of Nimule, and leave perhaps 110 tons of food and supplies for
an unknown number of displaced people there, said Hertz.
   From Nimule, it will continue on to Torit only if convoy leaders
believe conditions are safe and no threat exists of land mines
along the route, he said.
   In recent weeks, Torit's civilian population swelled from 3,000
to 25,000 as displaced southerners pour in from the surrounding
bush. U.N. officials expect the population to climb to 50,000 in
the coming weeks.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
