<FIRST>r w AM-Skinner-Europe     04-21 0642</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Skinner-Europe,660</SECOND>
<HEAD>Skinner To Europe To Push Aviation Security Steps</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Transportation Secretary Samuel Skinner set
out Friday for Europe on a quest to improve international aviation
security, while rejecting calls from victims of the Pan Am Flight
103 bombing for a broad investigation into the incident.
   ``My job is to get this problem solved and to put the best, most
effective program of antiterrorism into place,'' Skinner said in a
statement prior to his departure for Naples, Italy, aboard a
Federal Aviation Administration plane.
   Skinner is to meet during the weekend with the administration's
nominee for FAA administrator, Adm. James B. Busey, who is U.S.
Navy commander for Europe. The secretary is meeting next week with
government and airline officials in Italy, West Germany,
Switzerland, France and England to push for security initiatives he
said would ``encourage international travelers to retain their
justified confidence in the system's safety.''
   Skinner, in a news conference for foreign journalists covering
Washington, said U.S. carriers have given ``unbelievable
attention'' to security and are the safest in the world.
   His spokesman, David Prosperi, said Skinner and other
transportation and security officials were flying most of the way
on a government plane to meet a tight schedule but would likely
make at least part of the trip aboard a commercial airline.
   Skinner, in a letter Friday to the brother of one of the 270
people killed in the Pan Am explosion over Scotland, said President
Bush had rejected the relatives' request that he appoint an
independent commission to investigate the Dec. 21 bombing.
   ``For a variety of reasons, we do not believe formation of an
independent commission is necessary or prudent,'' said Skinner in
the letter to Bert Ammerman, which was accompanied by a five-page
outline of administration action since the Pan Am explosion.
   Ammerman, of Demarest, N.J., said in a telephone interview the
victims' families still believe there is enough evidence to justify
a full investigation by Congress. Among concerns of the relatives
of 200 Americans killed in the bombing are the lack of a public
warning of threats against the flight, security procedures that
failed to detect the plastic explosive which authorities say was
believed planted by terrorists, and inadequate government response
after the incident.
   Ammerman said he met recently with Secretary of State James
Baker III and received assurances that relatives will receive
better treatment than they have, including State Department escorts
for those who visit the town of Lockerbie, Scotland, where the
plane went down.
   Prosperi said Skinner had no plan to go to Lockerbie during his
European visit.
   Skinner said he had confidence in the investigation by Scottish
and West German authorities and the FBI and believed those
responsible for planting the bomb, which investigators have said
was hidden in a radio-cassette, will be apprehended and prosecuted.
   ``I can assure you that in my opinion the investigation is
moving at full speed,'' Skinner said. ``I think that eventually and
hopefully in the not too distant future, the public will know the
full story there.'' He said it was important not to disclose
targets of the investigation or the information being sought.
   Skinner said his trip would review screening given foreign
nationals hired by U.S. airlines abroad and seek diplomatic
approval for installation of devices to detect plastic explosives
in airports used by U.S. carriers abroad.
   The secretary said he has no evidence that large numbers of
government employees cancelled reservations on Flight 103 after a
notice of a terrorist threat against U.S. carriers was erroneously
posted in the U.S. embassy in Moscow.
   In both the news conference and documents sent to Ammerman, he
reiterated the policy that ``if there's a significant enough threat
to advise government employees, the American public will be
advised.''
   He noted that several government employees were among those
killed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
