<FIRST>r a AM-SonoraSlayings     04-21 0661</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sonora Slayings,0681</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sonoran Murders Suspect Facing Extradition or Deportation, Feds Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARTHUR H. ROTSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The No. 1 suspect in 12 drug-related
torture slayings near Agua Prieta, Mexico, was in U.S. custody
Friday, awaiting extradition or deportation, Border Patrol
officials said.
   Hector Fragoso Burgueno, 45, was arrested late Thursday at a
mobile home in an isolated desert area south of Three Points, a
small community about 30 miles west of Tucson, Pima County Sheriff
Clarence Dupnik said.
   Like the ritual slayings of 15 people in Matamoros discovered
last week, authorities consider the Agua Prieta ranch killings to
be drug-related.
   Fragoso, who owned the ranch where the bodies were found last
month, had shaved his moustache, changed his hair style and altered
his eyebrows, but ``he was readily identifiable,'' said Pima County
Sheriff's Maj. Dennis Douglas.
   Enrique Cecena, zone commander with the Sonora State Judicial
Police, said the Sonora attorney general's office will file the
formal request for Fragoso's return to Mexico that U.S. authorities
said they were awaiting.
   ``He's the principal one, according to the witnesses,'' Cecena
said from Nogales, Mexico.
   Scott Coffin, deputy chief agent for the Border Patrol in
Tucson, said Fragoso was being held as an illegal alien under a
federal immigration arrest warrant on administrative charges.
   Authorities have not yet decided on whether extradition or
deportation proceedings would be the best way to return Fragosa to
Mexico, said Border Patrol spokesman Ed Pyeatt.
   Douglas and the Drug Enforcement Administration said Fragoso and
the Agua Prieta slayings may be linked to the torture and stabbing
deaths of two men from Arizona and three from Sonora whose bodies
were found in a Tucson shed shortly before the Agua Prieta bodies
were discovered.
   Tucson homicide detectives have declined comment on that point.
However, Dupnik said Tucson's homicide detail was among officers at
the arrest site.
   Douglas said investigators developed leads on Fragoso's
whereabouts through various tips, including a local crime hotline,
calls to the television show ``America's Most Wanted'' and
confidential sources.
   The TV show aired a segment on Fragoso last week that prompted
116 phone calls, Douglas said. He said the show was ``a building
block in our investigation'' but not a principal factor in finding
Fragoso.
   A woman taken into custody with Fragoso was listed in a DEA
statement as Anna Marie Fregosa and described as his wife, but
Border Patrol and sheriff's officials said they did not have the
woman's identification and that her relationship was unclear.
   The DEA said she will be deported voluntarily to Mexico.
   Various reports had described Fragoso as a United States
citizen, but Coffin said ``all the evidence'' in Fragoso's file
pointed to his being a Mexican citizen.
   The 12 Agua Prieta victims included nine who were found March 29
and three others found April 12, all at the ranch two miles west of
the Sonoran border city directly across from Douglas. Some of the
mutilated bodies had been dumped in a well; others were buried in a
septic tank.
   Cecena said 11 of the victims apparently were killed after they
witnessed the murder of another person.
   Fragoso, described by Mexican police as a drug trafficker, also
is known as ``Tombstone'' for what's alleged to be his practice of
burying competitors. Authorities say he may have been the enforcer
for a drug ring called Los Tios, ``The Uncles.''
   The DEA said it first became aware of Fragoso when he was
arrested in 1974 for possession of 2,400 pounds of marijuana. He
was convicted and sentenced to five years in prison. He escaped in
January 1978 but was recaptured the following March in Safford, the
DEA said.
   While in jail, Fragoso was convicted of assault on a federal
officer, the DEA said. He was released in the early 1980s but
subsequently was arrested in the United States on charges of rape
and armed robbery, the DEA said without giving the outcome of those
cases.
</TEXT>
