<FIRST>r a AM-Wright-Interviews     04-21 0453</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wright-Interviews,0468</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wright, Mallick Go on Offensive in Interviews</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Speaker Jim Wright's wife gave
important investment advice to the local partnership targeted in a
House ethics committee inquiry of Wright, chief partner George
Mallick says.
   ``She earned her money,'' Mallick told the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram in an interview published Friday. ``She was a
bona-fide employee.''
   The speaker faces 69 allegations of House rules violations
brought by the ethics committee. Among the accusations is that his
wife, Betty, was paid an $18,000-a-year salary by Mallick for work
she did not do for the Fort Worth-based investment firm, Mallightco
Inc.
   The ethics committee's special counsel, Richard Phelan, said in
a statement April 11 that Betty Wright had failed to document that
she worked more than 12 days over a four-year period for Mallick.
An attorney for Jim Wright, William Oldaker, said he presented
``specific testimony'' that she worked five to seven days a month.
   In an interview in The Washington Post published Friday, Mrs.
Wright said the firm was a ``a piddling little mom-and-pop
operation'' and she never kept any records of her work.
   Mallick, however, said Mrs. Wright was ``an integral part of the
decision-making'' when Mallightco was considering investments.
   In one instance, Mallick said he changed his mind on her advice
and decided against entering an oil company deal in which
Mallightco ``would have lost at least $25,000 and maybe up to
$200,000.''
   The House ethics committee is trying to determine whether
Mallick tried to influence legislation through his relationship to
Wright. Mallick said he never has.
   ``I've never asked the speaker, in the 30 years I've known him,
to vote one way or another on a piece of legislation,'' he said.
   He also said Wright had no knowledge of a 1988 gas well
investment in which Mallightco turned a $340,880 profit because the
speaker had put his holdings in a blind trust in 1987.
   Mallick criticized Phelan's report, saying he was ``convinced
(the report) was written in the cycle of the full moon _ it's
lunacy.''
   In a separate interview, Wright told the Star-Telegram that the
ethics probe has been an ``agonizing experience'' and he ``never
dreamed it would drag on this long.''
   ``I have tried to cultivate a quality of forgiveness. I must not
allow myself to be embittered against those who have said vicious
things about me. It isn't easy,'' he said.
   Wright said he believes his detractors have engaged in more
unethical behavior than anything he has been accused of.
   ``The most unethical behavior I've observed by any colleague is
the deliberate attempt to ruin another colleague's reputation,''
Wright said, in an obvious reference to his Republican foe, Rep.
Newt Gingrich, R-Ga.
</TEXT>
