<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-89 2050EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Japan     04-21 0411</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan,0424</SECOND>
<HEAD>Poll Says A Third of Ruling Party's Lawmakers Want Takeshita Out</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than a third of his party's parliamentary
members who responded to a poll think Prime Minister Noboru
Takeshita should resign soon because of the Recruit bribery
scandal, a newspaper reported Friday.
   The nationwide daily Mainichi Shimbun polled all 296 Liberal
Democrats in the 512-member House of Representatives from April
17-19.
   It said that of 168 lawmakers who responded to the survey, 35.7
percent thought Takeshita should resign to restore public
confidence in the government.
   They included 3.6 percent who said he should step down
immediately; 25.6 percent who said he should wait until the fiscal
1989 national budget is enacted, and 6.5 percent who said the
budget should just pass the House first.
   Opposition parties have boycotted parliamentary debate on the
budget for the fiscal year that began April 1, demanding that
Takeshita resign.
   They also want former Prime Minister Yasuhiro Nakasone to
testify in parliament on his involvement in the scandal surrounding
Recruit Co., an information services conglomerate suspected of
using political contributions and other financial transactions to
gain favors from politicians and bureaucrats.
   The Mainichi poll indicated 37.5 percent of the respondents were
in favor of Nakasone's testifying.
   The government is operating on a 50-day provisional budget.
Political analysts say Takeshita must resolve the budget stalemate
before leaving on April 28 for a summit of the Association of
Southeast Asian Nations in Jakarta, Indonesia.
   Takeshita has rejected calls for his resignation, vowing instead
to carry out political reforms to restore public trust in
government. Nakasone refuses to appear before parliament, saying
his links to Recruit were clarified at a news conference.
   In a poll conducted by Kyodo News Service released this month,
the prime minister's popular support rating dropped to an all-time
low of 3.9 percent. The poll was conducted shortly after Takeshita
acknowledged he received more than 130 million yen (about $1
million) from Recruit Co.
   Recuit also sold hundreds of thousands of unlisted shares in a
subsidiary at bargain prices to about 160 influential politicians,
public officials and business people. The purchasers reaped
substantial profits when the price of the shares soared after
over-the-counter trading began in October 1986.
   Seventeen politicians and their aides reportedly profited from
the stock transactions.
   Three Cabinet members resigned in connection with the Recruit
scandal, and 14 people, including two former vice ministers, were
arrested on suspicion of bribery or securities exchange law
violations.
</TEXT>
