<FIRST>r i AM-Italy-Gangland     04-21 0292</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Italy-Gangland,0302</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crime Boss Wounded, Three Bodyguards Die in Italian Shooting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAPLES, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A squad of gunmen ambushed a reputed boss
of the Camorra organized crime syndicate Friday, killing three of
his bodyguards in a hail of more than 100 bullets but only wounding
their main target, police reported.
   Another bodyguard and a 7-year-old passer-by also were wounded
in the midday shooting in the Naples suburb of Castellammare di
Stabia, police and hospital officials said.
   Authorities said Michele D'Alessandro was ambushed as he and his
guards were riding on three motorcycles to the local police
station. He is free pending appeal of a life sentence for murder,
but must report to police daily.
   The Italian news agency AGI said the group was blocked by a team
of at least 10 assassins who fired submachine guns, pistols and
sawed-off shotguns. The killers fled in two cars and several
motorcyles.
   The dead were identified as Giovanni Grieco, 21, Pasquale
Santarpia, 32, and D'Alessandro's 26-year-old brother, Domenico.
   Michele D'Alessandro, 44, who was on the back of his brother's
motorcycle, was hit by three bullets in the right leg. Police said
the motorcycle fell on top of him, acting as a shield.
   One guard, Giuseppe Sicignano, 31, was in critical condition.
Carmine Iovine, a boy who was riding nearby on a motorbike with his
grandfather, was wounded in the ankle.
   Police believed the shooting was part of a war between rival
clans of the Camorra, the Neapolitan version of the Mafia which
controls drug trafficking and extortion rackets in this southern
city.
   Police described D'Alessandro as the top boss of the Camorra in
Castellammare di Stabia.
   Dozens of police guarded D'Alessandro at a local hospital.
Police said he refused to cooperate with investigators.
</TEXT>
