<FIRST>r i AM-Hungary-Romanian     04-21 0258</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hungary-Romanian,0265</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Romanian Foreign Minister Reported Ill, Under House Arrest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Romania's former Foreign Minister
Corneliu Manescu, who denounced abuses in Romania in a letter to
President Nicolae Ceausescu, is under house arrest and in critical
condition, a Hungarian daily said Friday.
   In an article carried by the Communist Party newspaper
Nepszabadsag, Hungarian former Foreign Minister Janos Peter said
the 73-year-old Manescu is also threatened with deportation from
Romania and a court trial.
   Peter said he learned about Manescu's problems from reliable
sources. He invited him to Hungary for medical treatment and said
he hoped Romanian authorities would allow the visit out of
humanitarian considerations.
   Manescu was Romania's chief diplomat from 1961-1972.
   He was one of six top Romanian Communists who wrote Ceausescu
last month demanding an immediate halt to food exports from
shortage-plagued Romania. They detailed other abuses, such as
forced Sunday labor and systematic violations of private mail and
telephone communications.
   Following publication of the letter in the West last month, the
signatories reported police harassment and threats of deportation
and expulsion from the party if they don't recant on the letter.
   ``I have been reliably informed that Manescu is being kept short
of food. The news is particularly alarming since I know that (he)
suffers from a grave constriction of vessels and has had a new
attack of gastric ulcer,'' Nepszabadsag quoted Peter as saying.
   ``Isolation, even if it is only house arrest, may cause his
death. It is no exaggeration to say that Manescu's life is in the
balance.''
</TEXT>
