<FIRST>r i AM-Salvador     04-21 0196</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salvador,0202</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rebels Fire Rockets at Navy Compound</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Left-wing guerrillas fired four
anti-tank rockets at the national navy compound in San Salvador
Friday, and two servicemen were wounded, the armed forces reported.
   An officer, who identified himself only as Capt. Castellanos,
said the two men were struck by shrapnel. He said damage was minor
to the compound, in a densely populated district in southern San
Salvador.
   The officer refused to allow reporters to enter the compound but
showed them holes that he said were made by the shoulder-fired
rockets.
   On April 7, guerrillas fired rockets at the national police
compound in San Salvador and three struck adjacent houses, killing
one civilian and wounding six others. No police injuries were
reported.
   The guerrillas in recent weeks have increased their activities
in the capital and have vowed to present President-elect Alfredo
Cristiani with ``an ungovernable country'' when he takes office
June 1.
   Cristiani, of the rightist Republican Nationalist Alliance,
defeated the candidate of the incumbent Christian Democratic Party
in the March 19 election.
   More than 70,000 people have been killed in the 9-year-old civil
war between the rebels and U.S.-backed government.
</TEXT>
