<FIRST>r a AM-UMW-Pittston 1stLd-Writethru a0695 04-21 0666</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UMW-Pittston, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0695,0679</SECOND>
<HEAD>UMW To Spread Strike; Battle Spills Into Court</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 2nd graf, ``We've decided ..., to UPDATE
with more violence; SUBS 9th graf, `Other UMW ..., with 2 grafs to UPDATE
with more testimony from hearing; picks up 10th graf: `A day ...; ADDS
3 grafs with violence reported elsewhere.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK PAXTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOGAN, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A United Mine Workers official said Friday
the union is expanding its violence-marred strike against The
Pittston Coal Group to companies that are aiding Pittston.
   ``We've decided it has come to a head,'' said Howard Green, an
international board member from UMW District 17.
   The violence continued with rock-throwing at coal-truck convoys
near Pittston operations in Russell County, Va., Virginia state
police said.
   State troopers arrested 29 people and charged most of them with
throwing rocks at occupied vehicles, said Capt. Tom Flanary,
commander of the state police's 4th Division in Wytheville.
   Also Friday, UMW lawyers asked a Logan County judge to bar
Pittston security guards from harassing union pickets. That
followed Pittston's request that Judge Eric O'Briant limit the
number of union pickets in the county.
   About 1,700 UMW members have been on strike at Pittston
operations in Virginia and West Virginia since April 5. The union
accused the company of unfair labor practices in negotiating a
contract to replace one that expired 14 months ago. Pittston denies
the charges and has been hiring replacement workers.
   Green told The Charleston (W.Va.) Daily Mail that the union will
expand its 2-week-old strike to any company that is supplying coal
to Pittston to help it fulfill its contracts.
   ``We're not going to sit idly by and watch companies fill orders
for Pittston,'' he said. ``If you supply a renegade company like
Pittston, you will be considered a renegade yourself. The word is
going out.''
   Green also said that action later could include other companies
that have not signed a contract with the union. Green said as many
as 150 miners could go on strike by next week.
   At Friday's hearing in Logan County Circuit Court, a union
witness testified that he saw two Pittston guards drive past a
picket line with an uncased rifle or shotgun in the back seat.
   Other UMW witnesses said Pittston employees and guards sped past
picket lines, in one case coming within three feet of a union
shack. Some witnesses said they thought they had been followed by
the guards.
   Company lawyer John R. Woodrum said there was no evidence any
guards or employees did anything wrong.
   A day earlier, lawyers for two Pittston subsidiaries, Buffalo
and Elkay mining companies, asked O'Briant to limit the UMW to two
pickets at a time. The company contends that union members have
intimidated and harassed its employees and workers from companies
with which it does business.
   A judge in Russell County, Va., last week rejected Pittston's
request that the union be limited to two pickets at more than 30
sites but restricted the UMW to 10 pickets at two mines.
   About 40 UMW wives earlier this week staged a sit-in in the
lobby of Pittston's offices at Lebanon, Va. On Thursday, 35
strikers were arrested after a coal truck convoy was hit by a
barrage of rocks at Pittson's Moss No. 3 coal preparation plant in
Russell County, Va.
   In Buchanan County, Va., on Thursday, two miners attempting to
leave the R&amp;H Mine, a non-union contract producer for Pittston,
were injured when their truck was pelted by rocks and ran off the
road, Flanary said.
   The passenger in the truck was hit in the head with a metal pole
wielded by one of several UMW and non-union miners picketing at the
mine, Flanary said. The driver suffered a head injury when the
truck crashed.
   One of the picketing miners was charged with assault for the
attack with the metal pole and four others were charged with
throwing rocks at an occupied vehicle, Flanary said.
</TEXT>
