<FIRST>r w AM-Army-Rowe 2ndLd-Writethru a0700 04-21 0642</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Army-Rowe, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0700,650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Much-Decorated Former POW Killed in Philippines</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: To update with Cheney stam, adds 2 gafs after 6th graf previous,
the president</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush and other U.S. officials
reacted with grief and anger Friday to the killing of Col. James
``Nick'' Rowe, the highly decorated former Vietnam prisoner of war
who was shot in the Philippines by suspected communist terrorists.
   At the White House, press secretary Marlin Fitzwater called the
killing of Rowe ``a cowardly and heinous act.''
   ``Colonel Rowe was in the Philippines to help the Filipino
people in their efforts to defend democracy,'' Fitzwater said. ``We
will work closely with the Philippine government in their efforts
to track down and bring to justice those responsible for this
assassination.
   ``The U.S. government's support for Philippine democracy is
unshaken,'' said the White House spokesman.
   Rowe was ambushed by assassins who sprayed his armored car with
automatic weapons fire Friday morning as he was driven to his job
in suburban Manila. He was chief of the ground forces division of
the Army contingent at the Joint U.S. Military Assistance Group in
the Philippines.
   ``The president and Mrs. Bush extend their deepest sympathy to
the family and friends of Colonel Rowe,'' said Fitzwater.
   Defense Secretary Dick Cheney called Rowe ``a true hero whose
military career exemplified dedication to his country and to
freedom.''
   ``This cowardly act of terrorism against this brave and
dedicated individual is a tragic reminder that the freedom we
cherish has been obtained at great cost by those who have been
willing to protect it,'' Cheney said in a statement.
   Rowe was to be buried next week at Arlington National Cemetery,
but the date had not been set, said Lt. Col. John Chapla. Rowe's
remains were to be flown first to Fayetteville, N.C., near the
Special Forces base at Fort Bragg, where he spent much of his
career.
   Army Chief of Staff Gen. Carl E. Vuono called Rowe ``a personal
friend ... who I knew to be a selfless and faithful soldier'' and a
defender of ``democracy and freedom at home and around the globe.''
   Born in McAllen, Texas, in 1938, Rowe graduated from West Point
Military Academy in 1960, and was commissioned as a second
lieutenant in the field artillery.
   Assigned to Vietnam in mid-1963, Rowe was captured in October
that year, held for five years by the Viet Cong, then escaped on
New Year's Eve 1968. He chronicled his ordeal in a book, ``Five
Years to Freedom.''
   ``A courageous soldier in Vietnam, Colonel Rowe kept faith with
the ideals of America even through his five years as a prisoner of
war,'' Vuono said in a statement.
   Rowe ``never let the enemy break his spirit, continuing to
resist throughout his captivity and eventually escaping,'' Vuono
added.
   Rowe left the Army but returned to active duty in 1981, serving
at the U.S. Army Center for Military Assistance at Fort Bragg,
running the center's survival, evasion, resistance and escape
division until he assumed command of the Special Warfare Training
Battalion there in May 1985.
   He was married and had three children, according to the Army.
   Vuono said that Rowe ``returned from his incarceration in
Vietnam with even greater determination to advance the cause of
freedom and democracy. He was pursuing that goal when the bullet of
a cowardly assassin cut him down''
   ``All of us who are left behind must take stock in the
courageous and determined example that Nick has given us,'' the
statement said.
   An Army biography of Rowe said that he had won the following
medals and awards, but did not give their dates: Silver Star,
Legion of Merit, Bronze Star (twice), Purple Heart (twice),
Meritorious Service Medal, National Defense Service Medal, Vietnam
Service Medal, Army Service Ribbon, Republic of Vietnam Gallantry
Cross Unit Citation.
</TEXT>
