<FIRST>r a AM-African-AmericanSummit 1stLd-Writethru a0669 04-21 0553</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-African-American Summit, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0669,0563</SECOND>
<HEAD>King Laments Lack Of Unity, Dellums Blasts Budget Priorities</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS 5 grafs Hatcher comment.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN McGILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Coretta Scott King lamented a lack of unity
among blacks and Rep. Ron Dellums blasted the budget priorities of
the president and Congress as the African American Summit '89
opened Friday.
   ``Today, we have more of what we fought for, more
African-American elected officials, more educational opportunity,
more access to public accommodations,'' said Mrs. King, widow of
Martin Luther King. ``Yet we have less unity than we had during the
civil rights movement.''
   Such unity must be regained if blacks are to overcome burgeoning
poverty and rise to positions of power in business and politics,
she said in her opening speech to the summit _ the first such
gathering since then-Mayor Richard Hatcher helped organize one in
Gary, Ind., in 1972.
   Hatcher is chairman of this conference, called to develop a
social and political agenda for blacks in the 1990s and deal with
such issues as threats to the black family, teen-age pregnancy and
drug abuse.
   A panel discussion on criminal justice was to include Angela
Davis, an activist who gained renown in the 1970s with her arrest
and acquittal on charges stemming from a 1970 shootout at the
Marion County Courthouse in northern California.
   Dellums, D-Calif., in his keynote speech before nearly 1,000
people, said blacks must concern themselves not just with domestic
problems, but also with oppression and poverty that afflict blacks
throughout the world.
   And he chastised Republican President George Bush and the
Democratic leadership of the Congress for this month's
much-heralded budget compromise.
   ``Most of the Congress and, as far as I'm concerned, the
executive branch have failed the moral test of what a national
budget ought to be,'' Dellums said.
   Dellums, chairman of the Congressional Black Caucus, said that
group's own budget proposal would reduce the federal deficit by
$92.4 billion by placing a heavier tax burden on the wealthy and
reducing the military budget while increasing spending to feed the
poor, improve schools and build homes.
   ``We don't need MX missiles, and Midgetman and Trident missiles
and B-2 bombers and Star Wars,'' said Dellums. ``You can't feed
anybody with it, you can't educate anybody with it, you can't
create housing with it. It's madness.''
   In welcoming participants to the summit, Hatcher made an oblique
reference to the absence of National Black Republican Chairman Fred
Brown of New York, who last month withdrew after organizers
extended invitations to Davis and Black Muslim leader Louis
Farrakhan, who did not attend.
   ``This isn't about the people who aren't here,'' Hatcher said.
``It is about the people who are here.''
   Hatcher said he regretted the Republican leader's absence
because his early help in the conference was valuable and ``he has
something to offer that would certainly make this a better
meeting.''
   Fewer than 1,000 people were in the hall for speeches by
Dellums, Mrs. King and others, but Hatcher said he was not
perturbed by the relatively low attendance.
   ``It was the media that got into numbers,'' he said. ``The
people that cared enough to come, spend their own money, ... if
they cared enough to be here, then let me tell you something: my
expectations have been met.''
</TEXT>
