<FIRST>u a AM-RitualSlayings     04-21 0453</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ritual Slayings,0468</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mexican Judge Indicts Five Jailed In Drug-Cult Slayings</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note that 9th graf may be offensive to readers.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOEL WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MATAMOROS, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five men jailed here in connection with
15 alleged drug-cult slayings were indicted Friday by a Mexican
federal judge who said they could serve up to 50 years in prison if
found guilty.
   Only one defendant, Domingo Reyes Bustamante, was eligible for
bond, which Judge Francisco Salvador Perez of the Fourth Federal
Court set at 8 million pesos, or about $3,330.
   Reyes was caretaker at the Santa Elena ranch where authorities
last week found 13 bodies buried. He is accused of ``cover-up'' for
alleged failure to report crimes committed at the ranch 20 miles
west of this border city.
   More serious charges were filed against the other four: Sergio
Martinez Salinas, 23; David Serna Valdez, 22; Elio Hernandez
Rivera, 22; and his nephew, Serafin Hernandez Garcia Jr., 20.
   The four men also are among 11 people indicted by a U.S. federal
grand jury Tuesday in McAllen, Texas, including Serafin Hernandez
Garcia's father, Serafin Hernandez Rivera. The elder Serafin
Hernandez is in custody in Houston.
   The judge said charges that the four face in Mexico are
first-degree murder, kidnapping, violations of federal firearms and
explosives laws, marijuana and cocaine trafficking, violation of
federal burial and exhumation laws, criminal conspiracy and
impersonating federal officials.
   The judge said it probably would take a year to receive
evidence, try the case and assess punishments if the men are found
guilty of crimes including murder, kidnapping and drug trafficking.
   Two more bodies found near the ranch on Sunday also are believed
to be victims of the same drug trafficking organization, officials
have said.
   Many of the victims, all male, were horribly mutilated, with
genitals, hearts, brains and other organs removed in occult
sacrificial rituals designed to bring mystical protection to the
drug ring, according to confessions from some of the defendants.
   The five defendants remained jailed at a detention center in
Matamoros, where guards said the men were unavailable for comment
Friday afternoon.
   Even if found guilty of all the crimes listed, the judge said
that under Mexican law none of the defendants could be sentenced to
more than a total of 50 years in prison.
   ``Never in one single case can one accumulate punishment of more
than 50 years,'' Perez said.
   He said the defendants ``have all their rights and gurantees''
including access to legal representation.
   Authorities in the United States and Mexico, meanwhile,
continued a search for the cult's reported high-priestess, Sara
Aldrete Villarreal, 24, its ``godfather,'' Adolfo de Jesus
Constanzo, 26, and other suspects. Constanzo and Ms. Aldrete were
indicted Tuesday in McAllen.
</TEXT>
