<HEAD>Fire Kills At Least Six; Man Charged With Murder</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 9 grafs to UPDATE that two more bodies found; total
expected to stand at seven; includes IDs; Godfry is cq in 7th graf; picks
up 7th graf: `The state medical ...</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MOR2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAY FORMANEK Jr.</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FAIRMONT, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who burned as she plunged to her
death was among seven people killed Friday when fire swept through
a four-story apartment building, watched by a man who later
admitted to setting the blaze.
   ``To the best of our knowledge, all of the victims are accounted
for,'' said Assistant State Fire Marshal Paul Gill after
firefighters recovered six bodies from the building which housed a
bar-restaurant and eight apartments.
   James A. Stuckey, 23, was charged with murder after police said
he confessed to starting the early-morning fire. Stuckey told
police he had been depressed ``for quite some time.''
   Firefighters had the blaze under control within a few hours, but
a flare-up and the collapse of part of the roof and the fourth
floor hampered the search for bodies.
   ``It's terrible, I feel sorry for the people who were inside,''
said Vincent Tropea, whose mother owns the 85-year-old building,
which also was heavily damaged in a 1983 fire.
   ``I've been crying all morning,'' Tropea said. ``There's a fire
escape, I guess they just couldn't make it over there.''
   Paulita S. Ilagan, 35, fell or jumped to her death from a
second-story window, Gill said.
   Police officers at the scene said they saw Ilagan standing in
the window and told her to jump. She hesitated, the fire suddenly
engulfed her, and she then plunged from the window aflame, they
said.
   Gill said firefighters recovered the bodies of residents Robert
Jones, 36, Kenneth Godfry, who was in his 40s, and William Hayes,
who was in his 50s. Later Friday they found the bodies of Katherine
Hayes, 69, Nancy Moore, 43, and Jack Pheasant, 53.
   The state medical examiner began performing autopsies on the
bodies Friday afternoon, Gill said.
   One person was injured _ a man who broke both feet jumping out
of the building. He was in fair condition at Fairmont General
Hospital and authorities said he asked them not to release his name.
   Police Chief Edward DeVito said Stuckey is a suspect in at least
one other Fairmont area fire. Marion County Prosecutor Monty Brown
said he was not aware of any prior arrests for Stuckey, who was
jailed without bond.
   In a signed statement, Stuckey said he lighted a matchbook and
dropped it on a hallway carpet inside the brick-and-wood building.
   ``It just went `poof,' everything happened so fast,'' said Bill
Ledsome, 39, who was rescued from a second-floor window. He was
visiting a friend who lived in the building.
   ``The next thing I know there were flames out the back window
and the apartment just filled up with smoke,'' Ledsome said. ``I
kept hollering for my friend but I didn't hear nothing.
   ``I went back into the apartment three times, but it got so bad,
the only thing I could think of was going through the window.
   ``My friend never made it out.''
</TEXT>
