<SECOND>AM-Winery Slayings, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0715,0760</SECOND>
<HEAD>Salcido Faces Arraignment For `Incomprehensible' Bloodbath</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 10 grafs to UPDATE with gag order, estimated cost
of trial, prosecutors to seek the death penalty; picks up 10th graf pvs:
`A widespread ...</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto SRO5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER McNULTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA ROSA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A winery worker was arraigned on
murder charges Friday stemming from a bloodbath ``so bizarre, so
incomprehensible'' that the county public defender said he believed
a brain disorder might explain the crimes.
   A glum, unshaven, shackled Ramon Salcido, wearing an orange jail
jumpsuit, was charged with seven counts of murder and three counts
of attempted murder in the April 14 killing spree. Prosecutors said
they would seek the death penalty.
   His court appearance came a day after an enraged mob greeted his
arrival from Mexico with shouts of ``Kill him'' and picket signs
supporting capital punishment.
   Salcido delayed entering a plea and was ordered back to court
May 5. He was returned to Sonoma County Jail, where he will remain
under heavy guard and a suicide watch.
   Judge Knoel Owen granted the prosecution's request for a gag
order on lawyers involved in the case. The order bars officials
from talking about the case with the exception of referring without
comment to public records.
   Before the order issued, Sonoma County District Attorney Gene
Tunney said prosecutors would seek the death penalty. He discounted
speculation that Salcido's alleged rampage was fueled in part by a
two-day binge on alcohol and cocaine.
   He also said he believed Salcido is legally sane. ``The final
decision about his state of mind will be made in court,'' he said.
``Those (the slayings) were not the acts of an irrational
berserker.''
   Sonoma County Chief Public Defender Marteen Miller said he will
have Salcido undergo psychiatric and neurological tests. ``I expect
to find some brain lesion or tumor,'' he said, calling the crimes
``so bizarre, so incomprehensible.''
   ``God, I hope I find something,'' Miller said.
   Miller said the cost of the trial would be $3 million to $4
million and said he would seek a change of venue to Orange, San
Diego or Los Angeles county.
   A widespread manhunt that began after the killings Friday and
Saturday ended Wednesday when Salcido was arrested in western
Mexico near his hometown of Los Mochis. He was brought to Mexico
City on Thursday afternoon, deported by Mexico and returned to
California.
   The 28-year-old forklift driver was whisked into the county jail
Thursday night, smiling slightly as 200 people waiting outside
shouted ``Kill him!'' Inside, he was kept under a suicide watch,
officials said.
   Signs reading ``Yes on capital punishment'' and ``Salcido
doesn't deserve to live'' greeted him upon his return at Sonoma
County Airport.
   ``I want to see him tortured. I think he deserves it, what he
did to those kids,'' Douglas Drake, 28, of Santa Rosa said Friday,
adding that he thought it would be appropriate to skin Salcido
alive.
   Shawn Kennedy, 19, the mother of two young children, said
Salcido doesn't deserve a trial and added that she would pull the
switch on the electric chair. ``I wouldn't even hesitate if they
asked me to do that,'' she said.
   Sheriff's officials said Salcido was held in a maximum-security
cell, isolated from other inmates.
   ``With this type of prisoner, you have a threat from other
inmates,'' said reserve sheriff's Deputy John Childers.
   Salcido told Mexican television reporters and law enforcement
agents he killed his American-born wife, Angela, 24, and a winery
co-worker, Tracy Toovey, in a jealous rage, believing Toovey and
his wife were romantically involved, according to federal officials.
   ``It's ludicrous,'' said the Rev. Rich Gantenbein, a family
friend who led a memorial service for Toovey. ``Ramon has created
his own hell and now he's trying to drag everyone into it.''
   Also killed in a brutal shooting and slashing spree were
Salcido's mother-in-law, his two sisters-in-law and two of his
young daughters. The two sisters-in-law, 8 and 12, also were raped
and sodomized, and one was nearly decapitated.
   His daughter Carmina, who turns 3 on Monday, is recovering from
a slashed throat. She and the bodies of her sisters, 1 and 4, were
found Saturday at a Sonoma County dump. Carmina identified her
father as their attacker, authorities said.
   Additional murder charges will depend on whether lab tests show
that Salcido was at the home of his mother-in-law and her young
children when they died, Tunney said.
</TEXT>
