<FIRST>u a AM-LouisianaSpill 1stLd-Writethru a0630 04-21 0475</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Louisiana Spill, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0630,0484</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil-Tainted Water Spills Into Lake Near Baton Rouge</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 5 grafs to UPDATE with spill downgraded to 10,000
gallons, sted 100,000; DELETE outdated quote; picks up 6th graf pvs: `The
spill occurred ...</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BT1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY COATES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAYOU SORREL, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 10,000 gallons of oil-tainted
water spilled Friday into a stream feeding the lush Atchafalaya
Basin as a barge was being unloaded at a waste disposal site,
authorities said.
   The barge, carrying 900,000 gallons of wastewater from an Exxon
plant in Houston, buckled in the middle after an estimated 280,000
gallons had been siphoned into tanker trucks, said spokesman Bobby
Mayweather of GSX Land Treatment of White Castle.
   ``It looked like a giant had stepped on the barge smack in the
middle,'' said state police Lt. Ronnie Jones.
   State police originally estimated the spill at up to 400,000
gallons, while GSX said their estimate was 180,000. Exxon
spokeswoman Jill Johnson in Dallas later downgraded the spill to
about 10,000 gallons.
   No one was injured in the accident, but Ms. Johnson said a small
number of fish were killed at the outset. The waste, according to
Exxon, was 90 percent water, 7 percent alcohol and 3 percent light
oil, said Jones.
   The spill occurred at a remote area about 35 miles southwest of
Baton Rouge on the edge of the Atchafalaya Basin, a vast hardwood
swamp and marshland that is a breeding ground for a variety of fish
and wildlife.
   Iberville Parish Sheriff Freddie Pitre said he believed the
tanker truck crew had siphoned the waste from the front and rear
ends of the 300-foot-long barge, leaving most of the weight in the
middle.
   ``Oil-absorbing booms were in place shortly after the spill and
we believe most of the waste was confined to the immediate area of
Grand River,'' said Jones. ``We may not know tomorrow or even the
next day if we got it all because there is no visible slick.''
   Some of the waste could find its way into the basin, but the
spill is no disaster, said Jones.
   ``Things could have been an awful lot worse but because of the
waste involved and the quick response by Iberville Parish
officials, we've got a good handle on the situation,'' he said.
   Paul Dubois, a spokesman for the Palmer Co., owner of the barge,
said the waste is commonly known in the oil industry as slop water,
used to wash out tanks and ships. When it's dirty with oil residue,
it becomes waste water, he said.
   GSX was paid by Exxon to treat the non-hazardous waste and
dispose of it in the company's land farm operation, Mayweather said.
   The barge was leased by GSX, and Exxon had no responsibility for
the barge after it left the Texas site, said Pitre.
</TEXT>
