<HEAD>Reagan Plans Trip To Japan In Fall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former President Reagan will make his first
overseas visit since leaving the White House when he goes to Japan
in October to address business and political leaders.
   The trip, announced Thursday by the Fujisankei Communications
Group, will mark the first time a former president has spoken
before the Fujisankei forum.
   Although details about the trip were not released, Fujisankei
said in a statement that Reagan will meet with Japanese leaders
during the trip.
   ``We have many fond memories of our visits to Japan and look
forward to being back among our friends during our trip this coming
fall,'' the Fujisankei statement quoted Reagan as saying.
   Hiroaki Shikanai, joint chairman and chief executive officer of
Fujisankei, said the corporation first invited Reagan to speak at
its forum in 1983 and repeated the offer at a White House dinner in
January.
   ``Mr. Reagan is well-known and admired for his charm and sense
of humor, even in difficult times of stress,'' Shikanai said.
   The Fujisankei Communications Group includes the Fuji Television
Network and the Sankei Shimbun newspaper chain.
