<FIRST>r a AM-DrugBear     04-21 0312</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drug Bear,0323</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mother Arraigned In Teddy Bear-Drug-Gear Incident</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HAYWARD, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The mother of a blind child who brought a
teddy bear stuffed with drug paraphernalia to school pleaded
innocent Thursday to a charge of child endangerment.
   Alicia Mae Tapia, 42, was ordered back to San Leandro-Hayward
Municipal Court on May 11 for further proceedings on the
misdemeanor charge, the Alameda County District Attorney's office
said.
   Her 8-year-old daughter, blind since birth, brought the teddy
bear called ``Ticklebear'' to show her classmates at Castro Valley
Elementary School. It was part of a school event called ``Share
Day.''
   The girl, who attends a class for the visually impaired, told
teacher's aide Diane Oxford that Ticklebear used to laugh when
hugged, but that the battery-operated voice box inside no longer
worked, a sheriff's report said.
   Oxford told sheriff's deputies she unzipped the brown teddy's
back to see what was wrong, and pulled out a bag with a syringe, a
broken plunger, a bottle cap fashioned into a drug cooker, and the
residue of an unknown drug.
   The aide took the bear to the principal, who called deputies.
   Sheriff's Sgt. Dale Toussaint said the girl told Oxford that the
items belonged to her mother.
   The girl and her 6-year-old brother matter-of-factly described
terms used by drug users and how the ``medicine'' is injected in
arms, Toussaint said. The boy said both his parents used drugs in
the home, the deputy said.
   The children were taken into protective custody and Tapia was
booked in lieu of $10,000 bail.
   Toussaint said a search of the Tapia home produced another teddy
bear whose zippered compartment contained part of a syringe.
   After her arrest she told officers she didn't know the materials
were in the bear, hidden there by her estranged husband. Toussaint
quoted the woman as saying she was trying to kick a 25-year habit.

</TEXT>
