<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-89 2122EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f PM-BusinessMirror Adv24   04-21 0570</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 24,0583</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv24</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release PMs Monday, April 24</HEAD>
<HEAD>A Reader's Guide To Economic Data</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John A. Tuccillo thinks economic statistics
should be subject to quality control if they are to have any
significance in our lives. He believes a good many of them don't
mean very much.
   He fears they are just thrown around like confetti, and that
like confetti they are to be brushed off and forgotten. About all
they demonstrate, he suggests, is the offender's ability to use a
pocket calculator.
   Quality control might also be applied to some of the
``profound'' insights offered these days, but unlike the recent
storm of statistics, those insights have always been offered and
probably always will be.
   In on way or another, that is, Calvin Coolidge's dazzling dictum
_ ``When more and more people are thrown out of work, unemployment
results'' _ is likely to be restated just about every day. Get used
to it.
   With the numbers, however, it might be better to simply brush
them off and forget them, suggests Tuccillo, the chief economist of
the National Association of Realtors. To assist, he offers a
Reader's Guide to Economic Data.
   First: Numbers don't matter; what they represent does matter.
Inflation, for instance, is a problem only if the core rate of
inflation for the economy is rising.
   In February the Producer Price Index rose sharply because of
food and energy price jumps.
   Significant? Yes, if the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries can continue to push up the price of oil and the drought
of 1988 becomes the drought of 1989. ``If not, then these are
short-term increases, and inflation will not be a continuing
problem.''
   Next: Weekly numbers are not worth printing; monthly numbers may
be little better.
   ``The only weekly number that shouuld have any validity in your
lives is the number on your pay stub.'' In the world of economics,
weekly numbers are the product of random static. Real changes take
much longer to develop.
   Third: Some popular numbers simply do not matter.
   The Dow Jones industrial average, ``like the national political
conventions and the Academy Award presentations, is essentially a
private party that has no business being thrust on the
consciousness of the average American.''
   Immediately after the stock market crash of October 1987, says
Tuccillo, we learned ``how little that number either says about, or
influences, economic life.'' Economic life went on, of course, and
the market came back as well.
   Still, several weeks passed before some people believed the
world hadn't ended. Then the facts came out, one of them being that
most people don't own stocks and so weren't hurt, proving that the
stock market is not the economy.
   Finally: Figures don't lie; liars figure. Americans are sprayed
with numbers which seem to add up but which really don't. The use
of decimaled numbers, for instance, can suggest that the message
itself is also precise.
   But, says Tuccillo, ``statistics are meaningful only in context,
and without the context they take on the flavor of `three out of
four doctors recommend asparagus souffle for a fever.'''
   The doctors, he warns, could be the fictional Drs. Seuss and
Doolittle, and Dr. J., the professional basketball player. That
demonstrates, he says, that you should look not only at the
message's content but its source too.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Mon., April 24.</NOTE>
