<FIRST>a e AM-APArts:JazzFestival Adv26   04-21 0748</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AP Arts: Jazz Festival, Adv 26,0766</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv26</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Wed AMs, April 26, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Two Decades of Good Music at Louisiana Jazz and Heritage Festival</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY FOSTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   All you need for the annual Louisiana Jazz
and Heritage Festival is a good set of ears, some comfortable
clothes and lots of napkins to wipe the grease from your lips.
   The festival launches its 20th anniversary this month with a
two-week, $3 million celebration featuring 3,000 musicians and tons
of good food.
   ``I honestly think the New Orleans festival is not only the
largest but the most important in the world,'' said George Wein,
the producer who founded the New Orleans event and helped launch
others, including the famed Newport Jazz Festival.
   ``Lots of big name artists come to the Jazz Fest and hide
themselves in the crowd so they can enjoy it.''
   The formula for success has been fine-tuned since that first
1969 festival in Congo Square off Rampart Street, and this year's
event, scheduled April 28 through May 7, will look a lot like the
one last year.
   ``It's been so successful that we didn't see any reason to
change it,'' said Anna Zimmerman, spokeswoman for the festival.
   ``We're always looking for ways to make things work better, but
we looked into the archives about when it started and it's
basically the same _ it's just bigger. ... We're expecting 300,000
and we'll be happy with that.''
   The festival is really two events _ a series of evening jazz
concerts and a pair of weekend heritage fairs with open-air stages
surrounded by food and crafts.
   This year's concerts feature Wynton Marsalis, Miles Davis,
George Benson, Jimmy Buffett, Al Green and Santana.
   Some of their performances will be in a new riverside tent on
the banks of the Mississippi River _ the most conspicuous change in
the way the festival is staged this year.
   In the past, nightly riverboat concerts aboard the President
were an integral part of the program, but the owners moved the old
paddlewheeler to a new station at St. Louis, leaving festival
organizers to find a new forum.
   They resorted to a big tent, which will have more seats, better
views and _ they hope _ better acoustics than the boat.
   The weekend concerts will be held at the Fair Grounds, the
nation's second oldest horse race track. Eleven performing areas in
stages, tents and gazebos, each strategically positioned to cut
down on overlapping sound, will be set up on the infield inside the
dirt track.
   The schedule calls for continuous music from midday to dark _
Cajun, country and western, rhythm and blues and, of course, lots
of jazz.
   ``The heritage of the area includes a large variety of music,''
said Wein. ``People can choose the type of music they want.''
   Performers at the Fair Grounds range from dozens of local
favorites to some of the stars of evening concerts, plus such
drawing cards as Fats Domino, Robert Cray, Ricky Skaggs, Pete
Fountain, Rita Coolidge, the Neville Brothers, Pete Seeger, Bonnie
Raitt and Irma Thomas.
   ``You just put on your cutoffs and your T-shirt and join in,''
said Thomas, who performs April 30. ``It's great _ the music and
the food. All you need is some money and your Rolaids because you
always eat too much.'' Food booths will feature local samplers to
exotic imports: crawfish, alligator, goat, oyster, shrimp, chicken,
and red beans and rice.
   Organizers counted 124 food dishes on the menu this year. Their
only estimate on volume came from one of the festival sponsors, who
sold 9,000 pounds of rice in the two weekends last year.
   ``Everyone has a Louisiana taste,'' said Sonny Vaucresson who
serves up Cajun and Creole sausages. ``Every year we get more
people trying them. We just dish it up and watch them walk away
happy.''
   ``We sure do cook it up,'' said Joseph McDermott, in charge of
the Second Mount Triumph Missionary Baptist Church food booth. The
church sells $2 and $4 portions of fried chicken and potato salad,
which McDermott describes as ``just good old home style cooking.''
   Crafts from Louisiana's many cultures are also on sale in long
lines of tents: handmade jewelry, Indian pottery, Mardi Gras masks,
Acadian accordians, African jewelry, quilts and a variety of folk
arts.
   ``If you don't enjoy it ... if you don't enjoy New Orleans and
the festival, then you don't enjoy living,'' said Wein.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv</NOTE>
</DOC>
