<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-89 2125EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e AM-APArts:JazzFestival-Thomas Adv26   04-21 0541</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AP Arts: Jazz Festival-Thomas, Adv 26,0554</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv26</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Wed AMs, April 26, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Irma Thomas Doesn't Have to Sing the Blues</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-AP Arts: Jazz Festival</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY FOSTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Irma Thomas never misses Jazz Fest. If the
famed blues artist isn't on stage, she's out front listening or at
a food booth eating.
   ``Oh, yes, indeed!,'' she said. ``I try to be everywhere at
once. That's the only bad part. There are always two or three
things going on at once and you can't hit them all.
   ``There's so much good music, I try to listen to it all. And the
food is just as bad. I try to have some of it all, too. Everyone
overeats at the Jazz Fest.''
   The two-week celebration, formally known as the New Orleans Jazz
and Heritage Festival, begins April 28. In the lineup are 3,000
musicians, with the weekend fairs featuring continuous music on 11
stages. Thomas will perform April 30, continuing an uninterrupted
string of appearances that began in 1974.
   ``You get a real international audience at the Jazz Fest,'' she
said. ``People from all over the world are in the crowd and they
are all very knowledgeable.
   ``They will let me do some new things and some popular numbers,
but they always want to hear my oldies _ `It's Raining,' `Wish
Someone Would Care' _ the songs they remember.''
   Although she performs her soulful rendition of the blues all
over the world, Thomas is still considered a ``New Orleans artist.''
   ``It's OK. I have no problem with being a New Orleans artist
even though most of the major labels seem to shy away from you once
you're known as one. I think it's because we're all kind of
stubborn when it comes to change. We know how we want our music to
sound and we won't agree to strings instead of brass or
synthesizers or different things producers in other places think
sound right,'' she said.
   Thomas' most recent recording, ``The Way I Feel,'' on the
Rounder label, maintains the New Orleans feeling.
   At 48, Thomas, who has been performing for 31 years, has
developed a large and loyal following.
   ``Rita Coolidge and I have really become good friends and mutual
fans,'' she said. ``We try to do a set or two together at the Jazz
Fest. And you can always see other singers and musicians out in the
audience. A lot of those who perform there also stick around to
listen to the others.''
   Jazz Fest is as much a food fair as a music festival, and Thomas
is known among family and friends for virtuoso performances in the
kitchen as well.
   ``People are always telling me I should write a cook book,'' she
said with a laugh. ``I like cooking and I know good food, that's
for sure.''
   Her four children are grown and have left home, as have the
three of her husband-manager, Emile Jackson. But she still spends
plenty of time at the stove.
   ``I'm always making something, or Emile wants a treat, or I just
want to taste some real food,'' she said. ``If I ever stop singing,
I could make my living cooking.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv</NOTE>
</DOC>
