<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-89 1350EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s i BC-KoreanEducation Adv30-2Takes   04-21 0749</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Korean Education, Adv 30-2 Takes,0770</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv30</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, April 30, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>South Korean System Teaches Memory, Not Thought</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: an accompanying story is BC-A Korean Schoolday, b0626</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLY TUNNEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Six-year-olds bundled in coats sit
shoulder to shoulder on benches in the classroom, each working
desperately to solve an algebra problem and beat the others.
   Eager hands shoot into the air as the 54 children vie to get the
answer first and be noticed in a country where education in a
tough, regimented school system is a national obsession.
   ``Koreans are the hardest workers in the world,'' said Lee
Jean-jae, director of the National Institute of Education
Evaluation. ``They study without letup.''
   The system produces pupils who achieve some of the highest
scores in international testing, but:
   Can it teach the thinking and reasoning processes needed to
apply the information and deal with life? Does their education
prepare youngsters to be good citizens? Does it produce innovative,
creative thinkers needed for the future?
   Some critics say no.
   Korean education, like the system in neighboring Japan, is based
on rote memorization. That enables a student who works hard to
produce enormous amounts of facts and data that result in
impressive scores on tests designed for such a regimen.
   In South Korea, education is equated with success. The argument
goes: The more education, the more success; the more people
educated, the greater success for the nation.
   Detractors say the system clones human computers who can pour
out endless streams of information but cannot think creatively, and
that it contributes to the insecurity and tension that beset South
Korean society.
   The American manager of a company in Seoul said he hired a dozen
Koreans with master's degrees in business administration who
recited verbatim the case studies in any textbook they had read but
had difficulty being creative about daily tasks.
   Robert A. Brown, a linguistics professor at Ewha Women's
University in Seoul, says the rote approach suits the society's
traditional Confucian respect for the scholar.
   As he explained it, ``The teacher knows something, talks to the
students, who absorb it. They don't doubt, they memorize, and that
ties into the exam.
   ``They teach what they test for. You can't change the test
without changing the curriculum.''
   Under that system, Brown said, a student fails to memorize ``at
his own risk.''
   A South Korean professor said privately his country is
``educating barbarians.'' He said students become disillusioned and
feel deceived when they go to college, start asking questions and
face conflicting opinions for the first time.
   Many become alienated and join the ranks of radical students
who, although a small minority, have become extremely vocal and
demonstrate, often violently, to demand the overthrow of the
government and the expulsion of U.S. troops from South Korea.
   Increasingly militant labor unions include thousands of high
school graduates who could not get into a university and feel the
system cheated them.
   A high score on the college entrance exam often is a ticket to
the elite class through a good college, prestigious job and higher
standard of living. It is family insurance in a nation that was
ravaged by war only 36 years ago.
   Like marching ranks of well-trained soldiers, young Koreans
slave over books and endure physical and psychological hardship to
pursue prestige and success in the scholastic sweepstakes.
   A recent assessment of mathematics and science by the
Educational Testing Service compared 24,000 13-year-olds in
Ireland, Spain, Britain, the United States, South Korea and Canada.
   South Korean 13-year-olds were highest in mathematics and tied
for the honors in science with youngsters from British Columbia,
Canada.
   Several Korean educators who saw the test involved said it would
be easy for a Korean 13-year-old. An Education Ministry said he
would come down hard on 9- and 10-year-old Koreans if they could
not answer the questions.
   Lee, the National Institute of Education Evaluation director,
said he was not surprised by the high Korean scores or by those in
the United States, which ran last. He said said U.S. math and
science texts are too easy.
   Children in South Korea devote countless hours to memorizing
facts and copying from textbooks.
   Some as young as 10 stay up all night doing homework. By the
last years of high school, they study more than 12 hours a day in a
stressful contest said by its critics to waste minds rather than
building them.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
