<FIRST>s a BC-AbortionLawyer-Susman Adv23   04-21 0611</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Abortion Lawyer-Susman, Adv 23,0626</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv23</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, April 23, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Pro-Choice Attorney Prepares for Showdown, Feels the Pressure</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LORI DODGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLAYTON, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Frank Susman's commitment to abortion rights
began 20 years ago when, as a legal volunteer for a suicide
hotline, he realized how many women with unwanted pregnancies were
considering killing themselves.
   This week, that commitment takes him before the U.S. Supreme
Court to argue the most important abortion case since the procedure
was legalized in 1973.
   On Wednesday, Susman will present oral arguments against a
Missouri law that he and other pro-choice advocates believe poses a
serious threat to abortion rights. The anti-abortion side will be
argued by Missouri Attorney General William Webster, in support of
the law, and Harvard professor Charles Fried, representing the Bush
administration, which seeks to overturn the landmark Roe vs. Wade
decision of 1973.
   ``Clearly this is the greatest threat to women's liberty in
those 16 years,'' said the 47-year-old Susman, who acknowledges
feeling great pressure. ``You spend most of your time thinking,
cogitating, meditating, just thinking about it and reshuffling the
cards.''
   It was in the late 1960s and early '70s that Susman, working as
a volunteer lawyer for Suicide Prevention Inc., realized the
anguish of women with unwanted pregnancies.
   ``It was difficult then, as it is now, to imagine anything as
horrendous as being pregnant and not wanting to be,'' he said in an
interview Friday.
   That work led him to help another group that assisted women
seeking legal abortions out of state or illegal abortions locally.
   ``I had never known a person who had had an abortion until
then,'' he said.
   Susman has argued abortion cases before the Supreme Court
before, but never one as potentially damaging to abortion rights as
Webster vs. Reproductive Health Services.
   The Missouri law, passed in 1986, restricts abortion by banning
the procedure in publicly funded hospitals and forbidding the use
of public funds, and declares that human life begins at conception.
   The law was blocked from going into effect by a class-action
suit led by Reproductive Health Services of St. Louis, Planned
Parenthood of Greater Kansas City and others.
   The U.S. District Court in Kansas City declared major sections
of the law unconstitutional. The 8th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
upheld the decision. The Supreme Court agreed earlier this year to
hear the case.
   Susman, who represents about 20 abortion clinics nationwide on a
part-time basis, once stopped at a clinic to help escort clients
past pickets.
   ``I just happened to be driving by and saw this mob scene,''
Susman said. Later, one of the picketers sued him for $250,000,
claiming he'd assaulted her as he walked a woman to the clinic. A
jury cleared him.
   Susman's commitment to his belief that women should be allowed
to make their own decisions on abortion has made him a target for
harassment by mail and telephone. Someone once placed a bogus ad in
a St. Louis paper that said his house was for sale. More recently,
the phone lines to his home were cut.
   ``The threats don't bother me at all for myself,'' he said.
``They bother me for members of my family. That concerns me.''
   Susman said he respected his opponents' depth of commitment to
their belief. ``But I strongly criticize their total intolerance
and inability to perceive how anyone could disagree with them,'' he
said.
   ``No one really knows what they think about abortion until they
are faced with a pregnancy that they don't want,'' he said. ``I've
never seen an abortion for convenience. It's a gut-wrenching,
agonizing decision.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, April 23</NOTE>
</DOC>
