<DOCNO> AP890421-0209 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-89 1553EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s w BC-AbortionLawyer-Fried Adv23   04-21 0491</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Abortion Lawyer-Fried, Adv 23,0503</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv23</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, April 23, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Scholar and Litigator to Argue Bush Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Charles Fried, who will represent the Bush
administration when the Supreme Court hears arguments Wednesday in
a Missouri abortion case, says he considers himself more a legal
scholar than a litigator.
   The Harvard University law school professor, author of six books
on the law, has the proper academic credentials. But he also served
as solicitor general _ the government's top-ranked courtroom lawyer
_ for four years.
   During that tenure, he was criticized by those who said he was
too willing to mix litigation with ideological politics.
   In the Justice Department's No. 3 job, Fried was viewed as a
champion of the Reagan administration's conservative social agenda.
In appearances before the Supreme Court, he vigorously opposed
broad use of affirmative action and expansive interpretations of
civil rights law.
   And he once urged the court to overturn its landmark Roe vs.
Wade decision, which legalized abortion in 1973.
   In a 1985 friend-of-the-court brief supporting Pennsylvania
abortion regulations that were later invalidated by a 4-4 high
court vote, Fried said Roe vs. Wade ``is so far flawed that this
court should overrule it.''
   ``There is no explicit textual warrant in the Constitution for a
right to an abortion,'' Fried wrote in that brief.
   The chances of the court reversing its seminal abortion ruling
at that time were viewed as very slim.
   But Fried dismissed the criticism generated by his brief's
approach. ``I think there's something condescending about only
saying things which, on some kind of nose-counting prognostication,
the court is going to adopt,'' he said.
   He accused the news media of doing a poor job in reporting the
1985 brief.
   ``The press, which does not like to read things but prefers to
call people up on the telephone and provoke them into
indiscretions, called me a lot when that brief was filed,'' Fried
told a U.S. Chamber of Commerce audience.
   ``They said, `What was the reason for you taking the position
you did?' And that gave me a chance to say, `You don't understand.
A brief is not like a symphony. It's not like a directive. It's not
even like a proclamation. A brief is nothing but reasons.'''
   Although he left his government post to return to Harvard last
January, Fried was asked to return to represent the solicitor
general's office in Wednesday's argument.
   Fried, 53, is the son of a Jewish-Czech industrialist. When he
was 4, his family fled the Nazis and moved to England, then to the
United States.
   A brilliant student, Fried excelled at Princeton, Oxford and
Columbia's law school. He served as a law clerk to the late Supreme
Court Justice John Harlan during the court's 1960-61 term before
becoming one of the youngest individuals ever appointed as a member
of the Harvard faculty.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, April 23</NOTE>
</DOC>
