<DOCNO> AP890421-0210 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-89 1609EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s w BC-100Days-Bush Adv23   04-21 1101</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-100 Days-Bush, Adv 23,1139</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv23</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, April 23, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bush, in First 100 Days, Offers Few Clues About Where He's Going</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush is nearing the 100-day milestone
of his presidency boasting of scattered achievements and riding
high in the polls, but offering few clues about the mystery that
has long surrounded him.
   The questions: where is he going, what does he stand for, what
does he want to do?
   He wants to be known as the education president but draws
criticism for his proposed $441 million program, inexpensive by
Washington standards, to reward excellence among students and
schools.
   He calls himself an environmentalist but comes under attack for
not moving more quickly to limit the spread of the America's worst
oil spill.
   He takes a stand against tougher gun controls but then turns
around and authorizes a temporary ban on imports of semiautomatic
assault weapons.
   ``I think his grade is incomplete,'' said presidential scholar
James David Barber of Duke University. ``We still have yet to see
what he is going to do, if anything.''
   ``There is a puzzlement about what George Bush stands for,''
agreed Thomas Cronin, a political scientist at Colorado College.
   ``Ronald Reagan was able to be a Mr. Rogers and a John Wayne
back and forth. He was neighborly and friendly but he occasionally
took a hard ideological stand,'' Cronin said. ``Bush is neither.
He's not defined. The American people are not sure who he is.''
   Countering claims that he's off to a slow start, Bush cites his
budget and deficit-reduction agreement with Congress and a
bipartisan plan for humanitarian aid for Contra rebels in Nicaragua.
   Moreover, he points to his proposal for rescuing the ailing
savings and loan industry, his plan to tighten ethical standards in
government, his diplomacy with leaders from the Middle East, and a
new formula to ease Third World debt.
   ``I think we're moving reasonably well,'' Bush said Thursday.
``And I don't even think in terms of 100 days because we aren't
radically shifting things. ... We didn't come in here throwing the
rascals out to try to do something _ correct all the ills of the
world in 100 days.''
   White House chief of staff John Sununu bristles at suggestions
that Bush is moving too cautiously, taking too much time, for
instance, reviewing foreign policy strategy before renewing arms
talks with the Soviet Union.
   ``When George Bush had to make quick decisions, you got them,''
Sununu said.
   ``You got the savings and loan plan in two weeks. You got a
budget plan laid out on Feb. 9.
   ``Everytime there's an opportunity there, he's gone out and
jumped on it,'' Sununu said. ``And where opportunities do exist for
considered evaluation, you get that, too.''
   Many people think it's unrealistic to judge a president by his
first 100 days, a standard first applied to Franklin D. Roosevelt's
administration as he tried to pull America out of the Depression.
   For Bush, the 100th day falls next Saturday.
   ``Rather than look at 100 days, look at the first crisis test.
That will tell you more about this White House,'' said Tom Griscom,
former White House communications chief under Reagan.
   Norman Ornstein, a political analyst at the American Enteprise
Institute, said a president should be judged by his first six
months, not first three.
   ``In the first phase of a presidency, we see set in place a
stereotype, an image as it were, of what kind of president we
have,'' Ornstein said. ``It takes a while for that to set in. First
it sets in among the opinion leaders, then it spreads out beyond
the beltway.''
   As much as Americans loved Reagan and his bigger-than-life
image, they seem charmed by Bush's openness and down-to-earth style.
   He plays with puppies, pitches horseshoes and coddles his
grandchildren. He likes to fish and drive a fast boat. Every
Sunday, he takes his wife to church.
   In sharp contrast to Reagan, Bush seems to love to hold news
conferences.
   ``He is not a managed president,'' said Griscom. ``He is not
scripted out. Everything is not timed out to the half second.''
   Polls show Bush enjoys widespread public support, with job
approval ratings as high as 71 percent. ``That's higher than Reagan
at this time in his adminstration,'' says Republican pollster Linda
Divall.
   Ed Lazarus, partner in a Democratic polling and strategy
company, discounts Bush's good ratings.
   ``There is novelty to him and we always like all things that are
new,'' Lazarus said. ``There's no reason to dislike him.''
   Lazarzus said Bush runs the risk that ``he may simply become
less relevant if he goes along and doesn't do anything and the
economy starts to look shaky.''
   Cronin, the Colorado College professor, said Bush ``runs the
risk of having a very vague, very murky message and having so many
minor priorities and not being associated with any major priorities
that there is no particular theme.''
   High-ranking officials from Reagan's White House, speaking
privately, say Bush is not doing a good job projecting his goals.
   ``It's not so much that he doesn't know what he wants to do,''
one official said. ``It's how do you enunciate it. How do you lay
it out?''
   The official said the inexperience of Bush's staff was largely
to blame.
   ``Sununu is capable but who does he turn to to ask, `How does
this evolve'? That is a glaring error.''
   Democrats who were bruised by Reagan's confrontational approach
have taken a public posture of being delighted with Bush, praising
him for cooperating and trying to reestablish trust between the
White House and Congress.
   The battle over John Tower's failed nomination as secretary of
defense seems forgotten.
   ``How's he done in the first 100 days? For those of us in the
Congress who want the system to work, it's been fabulous,'' said
Rep. Tony Coelho of California, the House Democratic whip, who
cites Bush's agreements with lawmakers on a budget and Contra aid.
   ``His success can be tremendous is he keeps this up,'' Coelho
said.
   House Majority Leader Tom Foley, D-Wash., said Bush's
administration has been ``slow but steady.''
   ``In recent years,'' Foley said, ``we've gotten into kind of an
agenda-setting mood where we have to have dramatic, even theatrical
kinds of displays.'' He said that approach ``usually has less
substance that it has public relations value.''
   A onetime congressman, Bush knows how to make lamwkers happy.
   ``The great thing about this guy,'' Coelho said, ``I can call
him and in 15 minutes he calls me back.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, April 23</NOTE>
</DOC>
