<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-89 1620EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s w BC-100Days-Sununu Adv23   04-21 0509</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-100 Days-Sununu, Adv 23,0517</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv23</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, April 23, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Sununu Says Bush a Lot Tougher Than He First Thought</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-100 Days-Bush</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   White House chief of staff John Sununu says
he's learned some things about George Bush over the first 100 days
of his presidency. None seems likely to upset his boss.
   ``He's a lot tougher in the clinches. With all the respect I had
for him in the political side of the process, when it comes down to
holding firm on issues, he's a lot tougher,'' Sununu said in an
interview.
   ``He is _ more than anybody else I've seen in Washington _ less
willing to have his agenda set by the headlines of the day. I
respect that. I wasn't sure as we got to the nitty gritty how that
would go. I am amazed by that.
   ``I am amazed at how much at peace with himself he is and really
knows where he wants to go, how he wants to do it. There is a
structure and a discipline to what he wants and how he wants things
done that consistently shows day to day. I respect that. I like
that kind of an orderly approach.''
   Sununu also is an admirer of Bush's management style and shrugs
off criticism that Bush has been too cautious, reacting too much to
events instead of initiating things. ``You'll always have folks
that have grand ideas of how something ought to be done, but, with
all due respect, they're usually founded on comments shot from the
hip.''
   Speaking of Bush, Sununu said:
   ``When George Bush had to make quick decisions, you got them.
You got the savings and loan plan in two weeks. You got a budget
plan laid out on Feb. 9. You had an opportunity to get an agreement
with Congress on Central America and he took advantage of the
slightest wedge that was presented to him and came up with an
agreement with Congress in a matter or three or four weeks.
   ``Every time there's been an opportunity there, he's gone out
and jumped on it. And where opportunities do exist for considered
evaluation, you get that, too.
   ``It is someone who's got the experience and the sense enough to
know when you have to act quickly and is willing to act quickly,
the sense enough and the experience enough to know that it's just
not the right time to do something and get more information.
   ``Of all things that I think are characterized by what George
Bush has is a sense of good timing as to when a decision has to be
made. When that time comes, you get the decision.
   ``So there are some times where he wants detail, but once the
clock moves past the hour at which he thought a decision should be
made, you get the decision. And he's not going to be rushed, but
he's not going to be delayed.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, April 23</NOTE>
