<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0837</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Crude oil prices hit the highest point in more
than three years on news of a possible monthlong shutdown of a
vital North Sea pipeline.
   In frantic trading on the the New York Mercantile Exchange, the
May contract for West Texas Intermediate crude soared $2.04
Thursday to finish at $24.65 a barrel, reaching levels last seen in
January 1986.

</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Motors Corp.'s first-quarter earnings
jumped 42.2 percent on improved North American automobile
operations and cost-saving measures at the nation's largest company.
   GM said Thursday it earned $1.55 billion, or $2.37 per share, on
revenue of $29.6 billion in the three months ending March 31, vs.
$1.09 billion, or $1.56 per share, on revenue of $26.4 billion for
the same 1988 period. The improvement came despite a decline in car
and light truck sales.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   RJR Nabisco Inc. reported a 62 percent drop in
first-quarter earnings, blaming the decline on the costs of its
failed smokeless cigarette and takeover by the investment firm
Kohlberg Kravis Roberts &amp; Co.
   The company said Thursday it earned $103 million, or 44 cents a
share, on sales of $4 billion, vs. $273 million, or $1.09 a share,
on sales of $3.8 billion a year earlier.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's central bank, citing
continued high monetary growth, raised key interest rates and
spurred other European banks to do likewise.
   The moves Thursday were unexpected and depressed the dollar by
making investments denominated in European currencies worth more.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil billionaire Marvin Davis took his bid for
Northwest Airlines directly to stockholders, offering $90 a share
in cash in a hostile takeover valuing the nation's fourth-largest
carrier at $2.7 billion.
   Davis Acquisition Inc., an investment group he formed to finance
the takeover, said Thursday the offer for parent NWA Inc. could
total $3.1 billion. He also reiterated earlier claims he would not
break up the company, as management has claimed.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Rocky Mountain region for the first time
replaced the Southeast at the bottom of the nation's per capita
income scale last year, reflecting weakness in the region's
oil-and-gas industry.
   Per capita personal income in the Rocky Mountain states averaged
$14,282 last year, 13 percent below the national average of
$16,444, the Commerce Department said Thursday. New England claimed
the top slot for the fifth straight year, with income of $20,013,
22 percent above the national average.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>VALDEZ, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet oil-skimmer began pumping up
America's worst oil spill while Interior Secretary Manual Lujan
toured the region at a time of rising criticism of the Bush
administration's handling of the disaster.
   Lujan avoided reporters Thursday when he arrived in Valdez,
headquarters of the cleanup effort and southern terminus of the
trans-Alaska pipeline, from which the tanker Exxon Valdez was
loaded with crude oil before ripping its hull on a reef 25 miles
out into the sound on March 24.
