<FIRST>r f PM-Eastern Bjt   04-21 0625</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern, Bjt,0648</SECOND>
<HEAD>Speculation Grows Over Fourth Bidder for Eastern</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Washington property developer and a former
associate of presidents Nixon and Bush have become the latest
subjects of speculation about possible buyers for troubled Eastern
Airlines.
   Speculation intensified Thursday over a fourth possible suitor
for Eastern. Union sources said Mohamed Hadid, a real estate
investor who recently agreed to buy the Ritz-Carlton hotels in
Washington and New York, has contacted Eastern's striking unions to
express his interest.
   The federal bankruptcy court overseeing Eastern's
reorganization, which must approve any sale of the Miami-based
airline, also has been informed, said the sources, who spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   Speculation in other quarters pointed to Frederic V. Malek, a
former staff member in the Nixon administration and Bush
presidential campaign who is a principal of the Carlyle Group, a
Washington investment firm.
   The firm's vice chairman is former defense secretary Frank
Carlucci, who reportedly almost was chosen by U.S. Bankruptcy Judge
Burton R. Lifland as a court-appointed trustee to oversee Eastern.
   Malek and Carlucci are among the investors buying the Coldwell
Banker commercial real-estate business from Sears, Roebuck and Co.
Malek also is part of an investor group vying for Northwest
Airlines against billionaire oilman Marvin Davis.
   Malek, former president of the Marriott Hotels division of
Marriott Corp., is a longtime Republican party activist and friend
of President Bush. He was a senior Bush operative on the Republican
National Committee, but resigned after admitting that he had
collected information on Jewish officials in the Bureau of Labor
Statistics for President Nixon in 1971.
   Malek denied that his collecting the data had anything to do
with the Jewish officials' later demotions.
   A secretary at Malek's office said he was traveling and
unavailable to comment. Ritz-Carlton managers in Washington
declined to give Hadid's telephone number and there were no phone
listings for him in that city.
   The bankruptcy examiner for Eastern, David I. Shapiro, had asked
Eastern union leaders to meet with him in New York on Thursday
evening, sources said, but it was unclear what they would discuss.
   Attorneys for Eastern and the unions recently said there are
four potentially serious suitors for the airline, which has been
grounded by a strike since March 4. It filed for bankruptcy
protection five days later.
   They said the bidders as ex-baseball commissioner Peter V.
Ueberroth, whose $464 million deal to buy Eastern collapsed last
week; takeover strategist Carl Icahn; billionaire hotel executive
Jay Pritzker; and an unnamed bidder.
   Frank Lorenzo, chairman of Eastern parent Texas Air Corp.,
insisted Wednesday that Eastern isn't for sale and that there is no
serious fourth bidder.
   Separately, the committee representing Eastern's major creditors
discussed Thursday the carrier's financial situation, sources close
to the situation said.
   In a six-hour meeting at a Manhattan law firm, representatives
of investment firm Goldman Sachs &amp; Co. presented their financial
review of Eastern to the creditors committee, said participants in
the talks, who asked not to be identified.
   ``It was nothing earth-shattering,'' one participant said.
``Everyone's sort of being held in a limbo situation.''
   Last week, shortly before the collapse of Ueberroth's deal with
Lorenzo, the creditors panel had expressed reservations about the
deal and requested that Goldman Sachs review Eastern's financial
situation.
   The creditors committee, which includes representatives of
Eastern's unions, still is waiting to hear management's plan to
sharply reduce the airline's size and sell some substantial assets.
   Eastern has not yet presented specifics of the plan to the
panel. Lorenzo said Wednesday the plan will be presented to
creditors next week.
   Lifland has ordered Eastern to explain at a hearing Monday why
the airline should not be put up for auction in its entirety.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
