<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-89 0159EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-HighestPaid     04-21 0374</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Highest Paid,0394</SECOND>
<HEAD>Walt Disney Chief Highest Paid CEO at $40.1 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The man who transformed Walt Disney Co. from a
sleepy movie studio and theme-park operator into an entertainment
powerhouse was the highest-paid corporate executive last year, a
magazine reports.
   Walt Disney Chairman Michael D. Eisner earned $40.1 million in
1988, Business Week said Thursday.
   Right behind him is Disney's president, Frank G. Wells, who
garnered $32.1 million, the magazine reported in its May 1 edition.
The bulk of money earned by Eisner and Wells came from stock
options they exercised.
   Business Week said the biggest surprise in its 39th annual
survey of executive pay in the United States was the average salary
and bonus for chief executive officers topped $1 million for the
first time, and the average total compensation exceeded $2 million.
   The survey of 354 corporations found the average CEO's salary
and bonus rose to nearly $1.13 million, an increase of 17 percent
over a year earlier. Stock options and long-term pay upped the
figure to more than $2.02 million, up 14 percent over a year
earlier.
   The advances far exceeded the 1988 average inflation rate of 4.4
percent.
   In the magazine's own analysis of how the CEO's performed
considering the money they make, Business Week gave the best rating
to Holly Farms Corp.'s R. Lee Taylor II, whom it said ``gets paid
chicken feed by today's standards.''
   Taylor made a total of $816,000 over the past three years for
running a company with $1.8 billion in annual sales.
   Here in descending order are the top 10 earners ranked by
Business Week in terms of 1988 total pay, which includes salary,
bonus and long-term compensation:
   Michael D. Eisner, chairman, Walt Disney, $40.09 million.
   Frank G. Wells, president, Walt Disney, $32.13 million.
   E. A. Horrigan Jr., former vice chairman, RJR Nabisco Inc.,
$21.73 million. F. Ross Johnson, former chief executive, RJR
Nabisco, $21.07 million.
   Martin S. Davis, chairman, Gulf &amp; Western Inc., $16.25 million.
   Richard L. Gelb, chairman, Bristol-Myers Co., $14.05 million.
   William P. Stiritz, chairman, Ralston Purina Co., $12.95 million.
   Baine P. Kerr, chairman, executive committee, Pennzoil Co.,
$11.55 million.
   J. Hugh Liedtke, chairman, Pennzoil, $11.54 million.
   Paul Fireman, chairman, Reebok International Ltd., $11.44
million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890421-0215 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-89 0212EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-ImprovedTelevision Bjt   04-21 0690</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Improved Television, Bjt,0713</SECOND>
<HEAD>Improved Television Signal Broadcast By New York Station</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRINCETON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fifty years after television's debut, a
station has demonstrated the first commercial broadcast of an
improved TV signal that could show the way for the next generation
of viewing.
   Viewers at a research center here were treated Thursday to the
first glimpse of the signal, which was used by a New York
television station to broadcast a segment of its evening news show.
   Viewers with regular televisions saw little or no difference in
the signal, but it showed up as a bright, wide picture on prototype
sets at the David Sarnoff Research Center center in this university
town about 50 miles southwest of Manhattan.
   The broadcast _ on the anniversary of television's debut at the
1939 New York World's Fair _ was another milestone on the road
toward a new generation of televisions for the 1990s, called
high-definition TV, that will have nearly the brightness and
sharpness of magazine pictures.
   Those sets may not arrive until 1994 or 1995 and initially could
cost $3,000 to $4,000, said James Tietjen, president of the
research center.
   ``Today's broadcast is to television what Kitty Hawk was to
flight,'' said Michael J. Sherlock, NBC's president for operations
and technical services.
   The broadcast by NBC's New York affiliate, WNBC-TV, is part of a
wave of experimental transmissions recently authorized by the
Federal Communications Commission.
   KHJ-TV, an independent station in Los Angeles, on Wednesday
began testing an enhancement of the standard TV signal that is
intended to remove distortions on the edges of brightly colored
objects as they appear on regular sets.
   At the end of April, KBLR in Las Vegas, Nev., is scheduled to
begin testing a different system for enhancing the signal received
by standard sets.
   In addition, more highly advanced television signals have been
transmitted over Channels 58 and 59 in Washington, D.C., which are
low-powered and exclusively for research purposes.
   WNBC-TV, however, is the only commercial station that is
transmitting a signal that can be displayed on special wide screens
that have the proportions of a movie theater screen.
   The system falls short of full-fledged, high-definition
television because it has to fit into the same narrow portion of
the broadcast spectrum as the regular television signal does.
   Engineers say full HDTV will require at least 50 percent more
band width than regular channels provide.
   Thursday's test was part of a six-year, $60 million research
effort at the Sarnoff center that is supported by NBC; NBC's local
affiliates; NBC's parent, General Electric Co.; and RCA Consumer
Electronics, which is owned by France's Thomson SA.
   At one time, RCA, NBC and the Sarnoff center were all under the
same ownership. The research center now is operated by SRI
International, a Menlo Park, Calif., non-profit research concern.
   The advanced TV demonstration shown during the news program
``Live at Five'' was a videotape from the Tournament of Roses
parade that had been recorded on a special video camera.
   It was encoded, transmitted from the top of New York's World
Trade Cneter and then decoded by the prototype equipment in
Princeton.
   WNBC had been quietly testing the system during the early
morning hours since March 12, according to James Carnes, the
Sarnoff center's vice president for the consumer electronics and
information sciences division.
   Fifty years ago to the day Thursday, Gen. David Sarnoff,
then-chairman of the Radio Corp. of America, the former RCA,
introduced television at the New York World's Fair.
   The wider, sharper picture is squeezed into a standard channel
with computer techniques. The extra side panels are compressed so
they appear on regular sets as invisibly thin lines along the
edges. The experimental sets decompress those panels to fill up the
wider screen.
   Extra detail for the side panels and for the entire picture is
transmitted in unused spaces in the signal.
   ``When we started this program five years ago, 90 percent of the
scientists in this industry would have said, `Forget it, this can't
be done.' But we did it,'' said Steven Bonica, a vice president for
engineering at NBC.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890421-0216 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-89 0249EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Northwest-Davis Bjt   04-21 0565</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Northwest-Davis, Bjt,0586</SECOND>
<HEAD>Northwest Urges Shareholders To Wait Before Tendering To Davis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KARREN MILLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NWA Inc., parent of Northwest Airlines, is
urging its shareholders to wait for the advice of its board of
directors before deciding whether to sell shares to Marvin Davis,
who is appealing to them with a hostile tender offer.
   But it would seem unlikely that Davis would have many takers at
$90 a share as long as the stock continues to command a higher
price on the New York Stock Exchange. Davis' offer, announced
Thursday, is the same price he offered the board late last month in
proposing a negotiated deal.
   The board rejected the offer as inadequate. The company said it
preferred all-cash, fully financed offers, and Davis apparently
sought to meet that requirement.
   On Thursday, NWA stock closed at $98.87{, down 62{ cents from
Wednesday's record-high of $99.50, on volume of 1.57 million shares.
   It was the third day of heavy trading in the stock since the NWA
board said Monday it would consider all serious offers for the
airline, the nation's fourth-largest. Alternatively, it said it
would consider selling part of the airline, buying back shares,
buying another company or issuing a special dividend to
shareholders.
   Northwest, based in suburban Eagan, released a statement
Thursday telling shareholders that the NWA board will review the
tender offer and make a recommendation to them no later than April
30.
   ``We are studying Mr. Davis' actions,'' Kevin Whalen, NWA's
director of corporate communications, said of the hostile takeover
bid.
   The $2.7 billion tender offer by Davis Acquisition Inc. will
expire at midnight EDT on May 17 unless extended.
   Including related fees, the deal could total $3.1 billion, the
Davis group said. The group owns 850,000 shares of NWA common
stock, or about 2.8 percent of the total outstanding.
   ``It should be absolutely clear: We do not intend to `bust up'
the company,'' Davis said in a statement. ``Our financing
arrangements will not necessitate the sale of any of NWA's airline
assets, and will ... allow the expansion of the airline and the
fulfillment of its capital expenditure plans.''
   In a letter to NWA's board, Davis Acquisition reaffirmed its
willingness to negotiate all aspects of the offer, including price.
   ``We hope that the NWA board of directors will determine to
pursue the sale of the company, rather than the other alternatives
listed in its recent announcement,'' Davis said.
   ``Since NWA apparently will give serious consideration to the
other, non-sale alternatives, we have determined to bring our offer
directly to the stockholders,'' he added.
   Davis Acquisition said it has obtained a letter from Citibank
and Citicorp North America Inc. stating they would syndicate with a
group of major banks up to $1.4 billion of financing for the offer,
with Citibank committed to lending up to $500 milion of the amount
itself.
   The company said it hoped to obtain other financing, including
an arrangement of up to $1.25 billion of preferred stock financing
by Donaldson, Lufkin &amp; Jenrette Securities Corp.
   In addition, $300 million in common equity would be contributed
by a Davis family partnership, with the partnership committed to
purchase an additional $150 million of junior preferred stock.
   State officials have led a campaign to stop a takeover of
Northwest, fearing it would lead to the sale of Northwest assets
and a loss of jobs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
