<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-89 0727EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     04-21 0338</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0358</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Mixed, Gold Rises</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar was mixed in early European
trading today as foreign currency dealers assessed the impact of
Thursday's unexpected interest rate hike in West Germany. Gold
prices rose.
   Dealers said the market had calmed down after late Thursday's
hectic trading following the Deutsche Bundesbank's announcement it
was raising key interest rates by half a percentage point.
   ``It's quiet today,'' said Ernst Pullman, chief trader at
Deutsche Girozentrale in Frankfurt. ``People were expecting the
Japanese to raise their interest rates, but it looks like that's
not going to happen right away.''
   Earlier today, Japanese Finance Minister Tatsuo Murayama said
the Bank of Japan has no plans to raise interest rates and that he
doesn't think an increase is needed.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar fell 0.83 yen to a closing 131.45 yen. Later, in
London, it was quoted at 131.08 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Thursday:
   _1.8458 West German marks, up from 1.8450
   _1.6320 Swiss francs, up from 1.6275
   _6.2590 French francs, down from 6.2925
   _2.0835 Dutch guilders, down from 2.0990
   _1,357.75 Italian lire, down from 1,361.50
   _1.1840 Canadian dollars, unchanged
   In London, one British pound cost $1.7185, slightly more
expensive for buyers than late Thursday's $1.7115.
   Gold prices rose in quiet European dealings as bullion dealers
awaited developments in oil prices and in the dollar before acting
more decisively. Soaring oil prices and a sinking dollar on
Thursday gave the recently sluggish precious metal a healthy kick
higher.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $385.50 a troy ounce, up
from $383.25 bid late Thursday. At midmorning, the city's five
major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $385.25.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $385, up from $382.70 bid late
Thursday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose 96 cents to close at a bid
$386.41.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $5.79 a troy
ounce, up from Thursday's $5.76.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
