<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-89 0738EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Earns-Autos Bjt   04-21 0440</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Earns-Autos, Bjt,0458</SECOND>
<HEAD>First-Quarter Earnings At GM Up 42.2 Percent</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Motors Corp.'s 42.2 percent first-quarter
profit surge may not be sustainable, especially when the newest
incentive package takes its toll, analysts say.
   GM reported Thursday that it earned $1.55 billion, or $2.37 a
share, in the first three months of this year, compared with $1.09
billion, or $1.56 a share, in the same 1988 period.
   Revenue rose 11.9 percent to $29.6 billion from $26.4 billion.
The nation's largest automaker said profits rose because of
stronger performance in North America and an ongoing cost-saving
program.
   ``Really, what distinguished the first quarter is that sales
were not great, but they have structured themselves that they can
make a lot of money at lower sales levels,'' said auto analyst
Jeannette Garretty of the Bank of America in San Francisco.
   ``The quarter-over-quarter difference is most dramatic in the
North American (operations),'' she said.
   But Garretty added she doubted GM could continue its
first-quarter earnings pace, especially as the costs of an
incentive program GM announced March 30 begin to take hold.
   ``I think it's seriously doubtful that (incentives) will
generate enough sales to offset the cost of incentives,'' Garretty
said.
   During the first three months of this year, GM's car and light
truck sales ran 12.1 percent lower than the same time last year,
the second best year in industry history.
   Partly because of lower-than-expected sales, GM announced a new
incentive package on March 30. The package expires June 5.
   Incentives, which can boost sales on a short-term basis, are
costly for automakers, since they assume nearly all financing, with
dealers contributing only a fraction of the total cost.
   Earnings and revenue figures for 1988 reflect an accounting
change GM exercised Jan. 1, 1988. The per-share earnings for both
periods reflect a 2-for-1 stock split effective March 31.
   The company said its North American operations, which had been
lagging recently, contributed significantly to first-quarter
profits. GM also said its overseas earnings during the first
quarter this year exceeded last year's record first-quarter profits.
   GM spokesman Terry Sullivan declined to provide specific numbers
or approximations about GM's North American automotive operations,
other than to say ``they were profitable and up from last year.''
   The company said it cut costs by about $1 billion in the first
quarter. That brings to $9.5 billion the amount GM said it has cut
in a program aimed at slashing $12.5 billion to $13 billion by the
end of 1990.
   Ford is expected to release its first-quarter earnings report
next week and Chrysler in the first week of May.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
