<FIRST>r f PM-Cineplex-MCA     04-21 0345</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cineplex-MCA,0357</SECOND>
<HEAD>MCA Tries To Block Cineplex Takeover</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. entertainment giant MCA Inc. has won the
preliminary court support in a battle to stop a group led by
Cineplex Odeon Corp. from locking up control of the U.S. and
Canadian movie house chain.
   The Ontario Supreme Court issued an interim injunction
prohibiting the group from acquiring shares in the Toronto-based
company from sellers led by Montreal financier Charles Bronfman,
MCA said Thursday in a statement.
   Cineplex Chairman Garth Drabinsky and his allies cannot buy
``until further order,'' the court said.
   Officials of Los Angeles-based MCA, the biggest single
shareholder in Cineplex, and Drabinsky could not be reached for
comment. The court order came on the eve of a Quebec Securities
Commission hearing on the issue.
   At the hearing Friday, MCA will seek to block the plans of
Drabinsky and his allies to buy a 30 percent chunk of Cineplex
stock from the Bronfman group in a $127-million private deal
announced last week. Bronfman is co-chairman of the Seagram Co. Ltd.
   In documents MCA filed Thursday with the U.S. Securities and
Exchange Commission in Washington, the company said it might take
other steps ``to impede'' Drabinsky from winning control of
Cineplex.
   In one of the documents _ a letter to Drabinsky and all Cineplex
board members _ MCA called on the Cineplex board to set up a
committee of the independent directors to rule on the Drabinsky
group's bid and, if necessary, suggest alternatives.
   Drabinsky's group has said it would settle for 5.9 million
shares instead of the 7.3 million announced last week. That would
leave them with 34.2 percent of the votes, putting them ahead of
MCA.
   Because of Canadian restrictions on foreign ownership imposed
when MCA acquired its 49.6 percent stake in Cineplex in 1986, the
U.S. company can exercise only one-third of the votes in the
company minus one share.
   MCA wants the Quebec securities watchdog to refuse to grant the
exemption the Drabinsky group is seeking from having to make a
comparable $17.50-a-share offer to other Cineplex shareholders.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
