<FIRST>r f BC-AmericanExpress-Arrest     04-21 0256</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-American Express-Arrest,0265</SECOND>
<HEAD>American Express Executive Arrested on Drug Charges in France</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The former president of American Express Carte
France was arrested and charged with drug-related offenses two days
after the company announced he was being replaced, the company said
Friday.
   Hector Cuellar has taken a leave of absence pending completion
of a police investigation, said Gerard Dijoud, spokesman for
American Express Travel Related Services in France.
   Cuellar, 50, an American of Colombian origin, was detained for
questioning April 13 at Charles de Gaulle airport following the
October drug smuggling arrest of a man with alleged ties to him,
the French news agency Agence France-Presse reported Thursday.
   On April 11, the French subsidiary of American Express Co.,
announced that Cuellar would be replaced by Charles Petrucelli, a
senior vice-president of American Express in the United States. The
change was to be effective May 15.
   The announcement said the changes were being made as part of a
management structuring plan initiated by Cuellar.
   French drug agents, in collaboration with the U.S. Drug
Enforcement Agency, learned that Cuellar allegedly had ties to
Roland Badier, who was arrested on his return from Colombia October
13 carrying cocaine paste, AFP reported, quoting unidentified
sources.
   The news agency said Badier had documents showing ''proof'' of
his ties to Cuellar.
   AFP reported that investigators believe Cuellar allegedly may
have received money from Badier then transferred it to the account
of a third person, a Colombian stockbroker implicated in the United
States in cocaine smuggling and money laundering schemes.
</TEXT>
