<FIRST>r f PM-RadioDeal     04-21 0503</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Radio Deal,0520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Westinghouse Agrees to Buy 10 Radio Stations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Westinghouse Broadcasting Co. Inc. has
tentatively agreed to buy the 10 Metropolitan-Legacy radio stations
in a deal that it said would create the nation's second-largest
radio station group.
   Westinghouse Broadcasting, which is also known as Group W,
already owns 14 radio stations: 8 AM stations and 6 FM stations.
   ``With this one agreement, the company that inaugurated radio
broadcasting in America in 1920 will dramatically increase its base
of operations, which will insure that Westinghouse will remain the
first name in radio on into the next century,'' Richard Harris,
Group W Radio chairman, said in a statement Thursday.
   Terms of the purchase were not disclosed, but one condition of
the proposed agreement called for repayment of the outstanding debt
of Legacy Broadcasting and Metropolitan Broadcasting for no more
than $135 million.
   The New York Times reported today that the sale was believed to
be worth about $385 million, making it the largest radio deal ever.
   New York-based Westinghouse Broadcasting said it had signed a
letter of intent to buy AM and FM stations in Washington, Houston
and Minneapolis and FM stations in New York, Los Angeles, Detroit
and Philadelphia.
   It said the deal is subject to reaching a definitive agreement
as well as approval by the appropriate boards of directors and
government regulators.
   If the deal were completed, Westinghouse said it would be
required by Federal Communications Commission rules to sell one of
the two Houston FM stations that it would then own. It said it
would seek a waiver of FCC rules so that it could operate the FM
station in Philadelphia, where it already owns an AM station and a
television station.
   Westinghouse said the deal would create a radio station group
second only to Capital Cities-ABC Inc.'s ABC Radio Station Group in
annual sales.
   The top officials of the Metropolitan Legacy stations are
Chairman Robert F.X. Sillerman and Vice Chairman Carl E. Hirsh.
   The statement said Sillerman, a veteran broadcaster, would
retain a minority interest in Group W Radio under terms of the deal.
   Burton B. Staniar, chairman of Westinghouse Broadcasting, said
the transaction would strengthen Group W's ability to serve several
local communities and give it a presence in nine of the top 10 U.S.
markets.
   He said it would also provide ``important new sales synergies''
for Group W that could offer advertisers combination buys of AM and
FM stations in a number of cities.
   The stations that would be acquired are WNEW-FM, New York;
KTWV-FM, Los Angeles; WMMR-FM, Philadelphia; WCXR-FM and WCPT-AM,
Washington, D.C.; WLLZ-FM, Detroit; KILT-AM and KILT-FM, Houston;
and KDWB-AM and KDWB-FM, Minneapolis.
   Group W already owns WBZ-AM, Boston; WINS-AM, New York; KYW-AM,
Philadelphia; KDKA-AM, Pittsburgh; WMAQ-AM, Chicago; KODA-FM,
Houston; KQZY-FM, Dallas-Fort Worth; KQXT-FM, San Antonio; KMEO-AM
and KMEO-FM, Phoenix; KFWB-AM, Los Angeles; KFBK-AM and KAER-FM,
Sacramento; and KJQY-FM, San Diego.
   Westinghouse Broadcasting is a wholly-owned subsidiary of the
Westinghouse Electric Corp., based in Pittsburgh.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
