<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-89 0933EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Britain-Plessey     04-21 0349</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-Plessey,0363</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Gives Conditional Clearance To $2.9 Billion Bid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain on Friday conditionally approved the joint
$2.9 billion bid for Plessey Co. by Siemens AG of West Germany and
General Electric Co. PLC of Britain.
   Britain's Monopolies and Mergers Commission unanimously decided
that the acquisition of the British electronics company should be
allowed to proceed, provided that the buyers pledge to resolve some
competition concerns.
   Earlier this week, the European Commission said it would clear
the hostile bid for Plessey because it ``had come to the conclusion
that the proposed arrangements do not raise objections'' to EC
competition rules.
   Plessey said it would continue to fight the takeover.
   The British commission said that in connection with GEC it found
that the merger raised competition concerns in defense radar,
military communications and traffic-control equipment.
   In addition, the commission found that a merger raised concerns
for competition in a large defense avionics project called JTIDS.
The commission said there were ``potential conflicts with national
security requirements'' because Siemens isn't a British-owned
company.
   The joint bid for Plessey values each Plessey share at $3.85,
making the total bid worth $2.9 billion.
   GEC and Plessey had no immediate comment on the commission's
findings.
   In February, GEC and Siemens revised their takeover plans for
running Plessey's politically sensitive defense-contracting
business in an effort to appease British defense and antitrust
officials.
   The commission said it would obtain commitments from GEC and
Siemens they won't acquire any interest in or influence or control
over the management of Plessey's radar and military communications
businesses and Plessey's traffic control activities.
   In addition, GEC and Siemens must ensure that access to
technology and licenses for production of JTIDS equipment are made
available to any competitor nominated by the British Ministry of
Defense.
   In order to comply with national security requirements,
arrangements for ownership and management of Plessey's defense,
research and development, and semiconductors businesses will need
approval of Trade Secretary Lord Young.
   Young asked GEC and Siemens for assurances as soon as possible
and said the proposed acquisition shouldn't proceed until they are
received.
</TEXT>
