<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-89 0940EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-TexasInstruments     04-21 0384</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Texas Instruments,0398</SECOND>
<HEAD>Texas Instruments Will Spend Billions on Research, Construction</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tighter Pentagon budgets mean defense contractors
are facing tough times in the short term, Texas Instruments Inc.
executives said in reporting a first-quarter earnings decline.
   ``We are very optimistic about the future of our defense
electronics business in the next decade,'' Chairman Jerry R.
Junkins told shareholders Thursday. ``But we must be realistic
about the near-term environment.
   ``It's going to be a tougher period for defense contractors in
general, and it means lower near-term growth in our business,'' he
said.
   Dallas-based Texas Instruments provides various electronic,
missile and radar systems for the Army, Navy and Air Force and
recently won contracts that could bring the company as much as $11
billion in revenue over the several-year life of the deal.
   But the company on Thursday reported slightly lower earnings for
the first three months of this year, in part because defense
revenues were down 5 percent from the comparable 1988 quarter.
   The company said it had net income of $84.6 million, or 90 cents
a share, on sales of $1.56 billion in the first three months of the
year.
   That compares to $85.5 million, or 95 cents a share, on sales of
$1.47 billion in the same 1988 period. The company said the lower
per-share earnings were due to increased dividends paid on
preferred stock.
   Junkins told analysts not to base their conclusions about the
company's defense business on a quarter-to-quarter comparison
because of the long-term payback of some of the ongoing research
projects.
   Texas Instruments said it will spend more than $1 billion on
research and development and capital expansion during this year.
   Junkins said the company will spend $525 million on research and
development and $760 million in capital expenditures; $127 million
was spent in the first quarter on research and another $150 million
on capital projects.
   Chief Financial Officer William Aylesworth said the research
will focus on improvements in logic devices on the semiconductor
side and in improving radar technology for defense systems.
   Texas Instrument, which had 1988 earnings of $366.3 million on
sales of $6.29 billion, is a major manufacturer of semiconductors.
Besides defense electronic systems, its businesses include computer
systems, various electrical systems and consumer electronics
products.
</TEXT>
