<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-89 1003EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Europe-InterestRates     04-21 0352</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Europe-Interest Rates,0367</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rates Continue To Rise in Europe; Dollar Mixed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The West German central bank today raised rates on short-term
treasury notes a day after its surprise hike in the discount rate,
a move that rattled U.S. financial markets.
   Separately, the central bank in Belgium raised interest on five
key lending rates, mirroring Thursday's moves by West Germany's
Bundesbank as well as rate increases announced by the central banks
of Austria and Denmark.
   The Bundesbank's initial actions jolted financial markets in the
United States, where Wall Street suffered a selloff, bond prices
slipped and the dollar lost substantial ground.
   In early trading today, however, the dollar was mixed and bond
prices were holding firm. Traders continued to look for indications
as to whether Britain and Japan would follow with rate increases of
their own.
   Analysts said they expected the Dow Jones industrial average,
which lost nearly 10 points on Thursday, to bounce back.
   The unsettling of financial markets began when the Bundesbank
raised West Germany's discount rate to 4.5 percent from 4.0 percent
and the Lombard rate _the effective ceiling on overnight loans
between banks _ to 6.5 percent from 6.0 percent.
   Today the central bank set short-term Treasury note rates at 5.0
percent, up from 4.5 percent effective immediately. A Bundesbank
spokesman said the rate on the notes, whose maturity is between 3
and 4 days, usually is set in accordance with the discount rate.
   Domestic overnight rates also rose.
   A dealer at a major West German bank said the market is ``all
confused and nervous'' following the unexpected shift in the rates.
Although market liquidity remains sufficient, he said there were
``too many question marks about the Bundesbank's behavior, which
made short-term rates unstable.''
   Belgium's National Bank said it was raising its discount and
Lombard rates by a half a percentage point each as well as hiking
rates on Treasury bills following ``changes in interest rates
abroad.'' Belgium usually follows changes in interest rates in West
Germany, a key trading partner.
   The new discount rate takes effect Monday. The other rates took
effect today.
</TEXT>
