<FIRST>r f PM-Earns-ConsumerProducts     04-21 0271</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Earns-Consumer Products,0282</SECOND>
<HEAD>Colgate-Palmolive Profit Growth 2.8 Percent In First Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Colgate-Palmolive Co.'s income rose 2.8 percent
in the first quarter, with much of the earnings growth coming from
its European and pet foods divisions, the company said.
   The big household and consumer products company Thursday
reported after-tax profit of $67.2 million, or 98 cents a share, up
from $65.4 million, or 96 cents a share, in 1988's first quarter,
which included $13.8 million from discontinued operations.
   Excluding that gain, earnings from continuing operations went up
30.3 percent in the first quarter from a year earlier.
   Last year's first-quarter included a financial contribution from
Kendall health care, which Colgate sold in 1988 as part of its
strategy to focus on its consumer products businesses.
   Sales totaled $1.20 billion in the three months ended March 31,
compared with $1.14 billion a year earlier.
   Colgate Chairman Reuben Mark said the improvement in
profitability occurred as the net return on sales, considered a key
measurement of financial performance, reached its highest level in
more than 25 years.
   The return on sales, after taxes, was 5.6 percent vs. 4.5
percent in the first quarter of 1988.
   ``I am pleased to see that after we consciously slowed worldwide
volume growth last year by focusing only on more profitable sales,
our first quarter volume growth has accelerated again, but on a
considerably more profitable basis,'' said Mark, who also is
Colgate's president and chief executive officer.
   Colgate sells its products in more than 100 countries and some
of its brands are Palmolive and Irish Spring soaps, Ajax cleanser
and Hill's pet foods.
</TEXT>
