<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-89 1059EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Eastern-Atlanta     04-21 0210</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern-Atlanta,0217</SECOND>
<UNK>Eastern To Add Four Flights From Atlanta</UNK>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Strike-crippled Eastern Airlines has announced
one-way $59 bargain fares on four new flights from Atlanta to New
York, Miami and Washington, D.C., starting May 1.
   The new flights will bring the number of daily Eastern flights
out of Hartsfield Atlanta International Airport to five, compared
to nearly 300 daily before the March 4 walkout by the airline's
Machinists, pilots and flight attendants.
   The flights, announced Thursday, include one daily round-trip
each to Washington and Miami and two daily round-trip flights to
New York's LaGuardia Airport, Eastern spokeswoman Karen M. Ceremsak
said.
   The flights will have one-way unrestricted fares of $59.
   The new flights will begin the same day that Continental
Airlines, which like Eastern is a subsidiary of Texas Air Corp.,
plans to start four daily flights between Atlanta and Newark, N.J.
   Eastern canceled all operations at Hartsfield, once its busiest
hub, after the strike began. A single daily flight between Atlanta
and Miami was added April 2.
   Delta Air Lines has not decided whether it will match Eastern's
bargain fares on the four new Atlanta flights, Delta spokesman Jim
Lundy said. ``Over the next day or two, we'll be taking a look at
it,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
