<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-89 1059EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Japan-Pickens 1stLd-Writethru f0018 04-21 0614</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Pickens, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0018,0631</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pickens Takes On Corporate Japan, Business World Suspicious</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS 2nd graf, `However, the...' to fix typo. PICKS UP 3rd,
`Pickens has...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSAN MOFFAT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Corporate takeover artist T. Boone Pickens has
raided Japan, leaving business leaders suspicious and wondering
whether Americans like him want to buy their companies just as the
Japanese have done in the United States.
   However, the difficulties the Texas oilman has encountered with
the subtleties and intricacies of Japanese business suggest Pickens
himself is far from being a threat to Japan's leading companies.
   Pickens has purchased shares worth about $1 billion in Koito
Manufacturing Co., a major auto parts maker, surpassing Toyota
Motor to become the largest shareholder. But despite owning 20.2
percent of Koito, its management politely turned down Pickens'
request this week for a seat on the board of directors.
   ``It is necessary to build a trusting relationship first. In
Japan, it is not possible to just say, `I'm a major shareholder'
and get a seat on the board right away,'' Koito director Tamotsu
Aoyama told a news conference Thursday.
   Pickens, in his first visit to Tokyo, challenged what analysts
consider two central tenets of Japanese business culture: that a
company belongs to its employees, not its shareholders; and that
the Japanese market is for Japanese, not foreigners, to enjoy.
   Pickens argued in a speech that protecting shareholders' rights
by using corporate buyouts to oust incompetent management helped
resuscitate the U.S. economy over the last nine years.
   ``What happened in the U.S. in the 1980s will find its way to
the Japanese business community in the 1990s,'' he predicted.
   But many Japanese businessmen hope that will not happen. These
businessmen believe the American emphasis on return to shareholders
has caused U.S. companies to lose competitiveness to Japanese
companies.
   ``Japanese companies don't generally have to answer to
shareholders with short-term profits. They can focus on longer-term
growth,'' said Keith Donaldson, an analyst at James Capel Pacific,
Ltd. ``Just look at these two economies to see which approach has
been more successful.''
   But even if Japan doesn't like Pickens' advice, it can't afford
to ignore him because he tied his shareholders' crusade to trade
issues.
   Pickens told reporters that ``people in Washington are watching
carefully'' whether he is able to invest in Japan. He said he was
``concerned that American investors don't have the same access in
Japan as Japanese have in the U.S.''
   While Japanese companies have invested billions of dollars in
the United States, some of it actively wooed by American states
eager for jobs, U.S. companies find it very difficult to invest in
Japan, analysts said.
   However, companies such as Federal Express have broken into
fast-growing Japanese markets by purchasing stakes in Japanese
companies in the same line of business, working hard to establish
themselves by putting down local roots.
   But many Japanese perceive Pickens as making an attempt at
greenmail _ taking a company hostage with the intention of selling
it at a profit rather than managing it for the long run.
   ``This is a bad example of an American acquisition _ a
`corporate activist' with no expertise in the business buying up
shares in a company,'' said Yoshihisa Murasawa, a consultant with
Booz Allen Hamilton (Japan) Inc.
   Mergers and acquisitions have shown signs of picking up. The
number of securities firms have been reduced through such tactics
from 600 a decade ago to 250 today, Murasawa said.
   But he said Japanese lack ``a habit of buying and selling
companies.''
   ``It's even harder for a Japanese company than an American to
acquire another. ... Selling companies is seen as something like
selling family.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890421-0232 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-89 1117EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-OilPrices 1stLd-Writethru   04-21 0664</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Oil Prices, 1st Ld-Writethru,0685</SECOND>
<HEAD>EDS: UPDATES with new 7th and 9th grafs to show Thursday's move was
highest one-day rise on exchange, add today's opening crude price; picks
up 8th graf pvs, ``Because gasoline ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JULIA C. MARTINEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Events in the North Sea and Alaska are diverting
the oil market's attention from factors that normally would be
driving prices down, analysts said as crude leaped another $2 a
barrel.
   Meanwhile, officials of Shell U.K. Ltd., operator of a platform
that exploded in the North Sea this week, said Thursday that
inspection of the damage is continuing but declined to say when
normal operations would resume.
   The gas explosion at the Cormorant Alpha platform Tuesday halted
production of nearly 500,000 barrels of oil _ or one-quarter of
total production _ from the Brent oil fields.
   Crude prices have surged more than $3 a barrel, or almost 15
percent, since the accident.
   ``With Brent being a major crude, it has people scared,'' said
Peter Beutel, an energy analyst with Elders Futures Inc. ``It's
possible there won't be any May deliveries.''
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the May contract for West
Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S. crude, soared $2.04
to finish at $24.65 a barrel, the highest level in more than three
years. The last time the near-month contract was higher was on Jan.
15, 1986.
   The $2.04 rise topped a $1.74 hike on Aug. 4, 1986, to become
the largest one-day increase since trading of crude futures began
on the New York Mercantile Exchange in March 1983.
   Beutel said that buyers anxious to take positions on the May
contract before it expired Thursday also drove prices higher.
   In early trading today, the June contract opened lower then
rebounded slightly after closing at $21.28 on Thursday. The
contract was trading between $20.93 and $21.33 a barrel before
midday EDT.
   Because gasoline prices have already increased in recent weeks
in response to the Alaskan oil spill, the latest jump in crude
prices may have only a minimal impact at the consumer level, unless
the pipeline shutdown is prolonged, analysts said.
   Thursday's frenzied buying was triggered by a comment from
British Energy Minister Cecil Parkinson that the oil field shutdown
could last up to a month.
   The closure affects several major oil companies that pump oil
through the station. Those include Exxon Corp., with about 85,000
barrels a day shut in, Amoco Corp., with 10,000, and Conoco Inc.,
with 24,000.
   Analysts said factors that normally would have driven prices
down during this period _ overproduction by OPEC and a softening in
demand during the second quarter _ had been pushed to the
background.
   But once North Sea operations return to normal and as the
Alaskan spill fades from people's minds, prices could fall back
below $20 a barrel, they said.
   ``The market is so overbought due to the psychological impact of
these events that there's a lot of room for a fall in prices,''
said Ken Miller, an analyst with the petroleum consulting firm of
Purvin &amp; Gertz Inc. ``The fundamentals don't support the prices.''
   Among refined-product trading Thursday on the New York
Mercantile Exchange, the price of unleaded gasoline for May
delivery rose 0.03 cent to 74.64 cents a gallon, while the May
heating oil contract fell 1.04 cents to 52.29 cents a gallon.
   Despite the recent accidents, an actual shortage of oil or
gasoline is more anticipation than reality, market observers said.
   The Department of Energy recently revised its figures to show
that demand is actually lower than thought. And OPEC is believed to
be producing more than 20.5 million barrels of oil a day, 2 million
barrels above its self-imposed quota and about a million barrels
more than needed to meet demand.
   So while the North Sea and Alaska problems have caused temporary
disruptions, there is no evidence of a shortage of oil and gasoline
to meet current world demand, analysts said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
