<FIRST>u f BC-Lorenzo-Iacocca     04-21 0270</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Lorenzo-Iacocca,0278</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lorenzo Gets Pointers From Iacocca</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texas Air Corp. Chairman Frank Lorenzo, whose
Eastern Airlines is in bankruptcy protection, sought the wisdom of
Chrysler Corp. Chairman Lee Iacocca, who years ago helped turn
around the struggling automaker, a Chrysler spokesman said.
   Lorenzo, who put Eastern into bankruptcy reorganization March 9,
asked for advice on a walkout by Eastern's unions that virtually
has shut down the Miami-based carrier, Chrysler spokesman John
Guiniven said Thursday.
   ``Lorenzo's company and its employees are going through rough
times,'' Guiniven said. ``Chrysler and its employees, as everyone
knows, also went through rough times. Chrysler is probably the
country's prime example of bouncing back.''
   Upon his arrival Thursday at Detroit Metropolitan Airport,
Lorenzo was met by striking Eastern employees who had been tipped
to his visit. They chanted and booed as he stepped off the plane.
   Guiniven said he didn't know exactly what Iacocca told Lorenzo
in their meeting at Chrysler headquarters in Highland Park, Mich.
Lorenzo, a friend of Iacocca's for a number of years, didn't seek
financial assistance, nor did the two executives discuss a sale of
the airline, Guiniven said.
   Lorenzo has said he intends to reorganize Eastern, a subsidiary
of Texas Air, as a smaller airline. A deal to sell the carrier to a
group led by former baseball Commissioner Peter V. Ueberroth
recently fell through.
   Tom Barker, leader of 37 striking Detroit machinists, said he
learned Lorenzo was coming about 10 minutes in advance and formed a
reception committee. He said some passengers on Lorenzo's flight
chanted along with the strikers as Lorenzo got off the plane.
</TEXT>
