<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-ConsumerProducts     04-21 0311</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Consumer Products,0321</SECOND>
<HEAD>Borden Reports Results</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Borden Inc. on Friday reported a 12.7 percent
jump in first-quarter profits despite a decline in the food and
consumer products company's dairy division.
   For the quarter ended March 31, Borden said net income totaled
$59.0 million, or 80 cents a share, up from $52.4 million, or 71
cents a share in the year-ago first quarter.
   Net sales during the period rose 12.6 percent to $1.8 billion,
from $1.6 billion a year ago.
   The snacks and international consumer products division posted
the greatest gain, with operating income up 26.5 percent. Operating
income from the worldwide packaging and industrial products
division rose 21.5 percent based on income gains from the sales of
forest products adhesives, industrial resins and specialty coatings.
   Borden's grocery and specialty products division reported a 13
percent rise in operating income during the quarter, boosted by
sales of Creamette and other regional pasta brands, Krylon spray
paint and Elmer's glue.
   Those gains worked to offset a 36 percent decline in operating
income posted by the dairy division, which Borden said was hit by
continued increases in raw milk costs and tougher competition that
that worked to drive down profit margins.
   In remarks to be delivered at the company's annual meeting
Friday in Flemington, N.J., Borden Chairman R.J. Ventres noted that
the company is ``just beginning'' to turn around the troubled dairy
division. Since July the company has eliminated 15 plants and
consolidated production in an effort to cut costs.
   Further, ``we are intensifying our investment in long-term brand
growth through advertising, and in the development of more products
to serve the fast-growing side of the diary business: products
lower in fats and calories.''
   Ventres noted Borden's goal of becoming a $10 billion company by
1991 with 60 brands that are either first or second in their
product categories.
</TEXT>
