<FIRST>u f PM-ExxonSpill 2ndLd-Writethru f0044 04-21 0660</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Exxon Spill, 2nd Ld-Writethru, f0044,0677</SECOND>
<HEAD>Barge Spills Oily Water Waste Near Louisiana Swampland</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with to CORRECT that barge not an Exxon barge;
waste originated at Exxon facility but company not involved in moving it.
Also adds differing estimates of size of spill, nature of waste mixture,
other detail. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BAYOU SORREL, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A tank ruptured and spilled at least
180,000 gallons of oily waste water into Grand River today as a
barge was being unloaded at a waste disposal site in southern
Louisiana, authorities said.
   The tank on the barge was carrying 900,000 gallons of
non-hazardous oily waste from the Exxon-Houston facility for
disposal by GSX Land Treatment of White Castle, state police said.
   ``Environmental officials from Exxon tell us that the material
is about 90 percent water, 7 percent alcohol and 3 percent oil,''
said Lt. Ronnie Jones of the state police.
   No one was injured, Jones said.
   The spill happened at a remote area about 35 miles southwest of
Baton Rouge on the edge of the Atchafalaya Basin, a vast hardwood
swamp and marshland that is a breeding ground for a variety of fish
and wildlife.
   The barge is owned by Palmer Co. of Port Arthur, Texas, and
leased by GSX. Exxon had no responsibility for the barge after it
left the Texas site, said Freddie Pitre, sheriff of Iberville
Parish.
   ``We were unloading the waste when the barge buckled. An unknown
quantity spilled into Grand River. We haven't determined the
cause,'' said Bobby Mayweather, manager of environmental safety for
GSX. ``We had unloaded 260,000 gallons and we believe about 180,000
gallons spilled.''
   State police estimated the spill at between 300,000 and 400,000
gallons.
   Jones said crews quickly surrounded the spill with booms,
adding, ``We believe we've got most of the material contained in
one area.''
   Mayweather said that the remainder of the waste will be emptied
into tanker trucks later today. Paul Dubois, a spokesman for the
Palmer Co., said a water and alcohol mixture, commonly known in the
oil industry as ``slop water,'' is used to wash out tanks and
ships. When it's dirty with oil residue, it becomes waste water, he
said.
   John Reidy, a spokesman for Exxon, said officials at their New
Orleans headquarters had little information about the spill, but
would have a statement as soon as possible.
   Jones said there is little chance of fire or explosion, but
``from an environmental standpoint, this could be a dangerous
spill. Anytime you get 400,000 gallons of anything into a river,
you've got a serious situation.''
   The incident comes four weeks after an Exxon oil tanker hit a
reef and ruptured in the waters off Alaska, spewing 10 million
gallons of crude oil, the worst oil spill in U.S. history.
   After today's spill, Exxon dispatched a cleanup crew from New
Orleans. The Department of Environmental Quality and other state
agencies were also sent to the site, Jones said.
   Stanley Jackson of the Office of Emergency Preparedness for
Iberville Parish, said, ``It doesn't seem that bad, and it's not a
significant spill, but you can't convince the people around here of
that.''
   The tank ruptured about 4 a.m. The barge was carrying three
tanks of the waste, Jones said. Workers removed the tanks from both
ends of the barge, causing the barge to buckle and rupture the
middle tank, Jones said.
   At sunup, the alcohol was evaporating, Jones said, leaving only
the oil to be cleaned up. If the waste is 3 percent oil, 180,000
gallons of waste would contain 5,600 gallons of oil, while 300,000
to 400,000 gallons would include 9,000 to 12,000 gallons of oil.
   Jones said the spill left no visible sheen on the water because
the material was so thoroughly emulsified _ ``more mixed up, that
is, with water and air and bubbles.''
   ``The Grand is a slow-moving river, so there has not been a
tremendous amount of movement of the material,'' Jones said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
