<HEAD>Soybeans Up Sharply On Weather, European Demand</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices surged in early trading
today on the Chicago Board of Trade, reflecting strong European
demand for soybean meal and reduced prospects for rain in the
Midwest next week.
   Corn futures were moderately higher in early trading and wheat
futures were up slightly.
   The firming of European soybean meal markets turned up the heat
on simmering fears of tight U.S. soybean supplies, which are at
relatively low levels as a result of last summer's drought.
   The possibility of a second drought year is keeping the soybean
and corn markets on edge, although planting of those crops in the
Midwest has barely begun.
   Some private meterorologists reduced the chances for rain in the
Corn Belt in their morning forecasts, triggering active buying of
new-crop corn and soybean futures.
   A 12-day-old dock workers' strike at Brazil's Port of Santos is
also having a positive impact on soybean prices. Brazil is the
world's second-largest soybean producer after the United States.
   Forecasts for hot, dry weather in the central Plains continue to
support the wheat futures market.
   In early trading, wheat was } cent to 3\ cents higher with the
contract for delivery in May at $4.10 a bushel; corn was 2{ cents
to 4{ cents higher with May at $2.75{ a bushel; oats were 2\ cents
to 3 cents higher with May at $2.00} a bushel; soybeans were 5
cents to 11 cents higher with May at $7.58{ a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mostly higher on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange ahead of two Agriculture Department reports due
later today, the quarterly cattle-on-feed report and the monthly
cold-storage report.
   Live cattle settled .15 cent lower to .15 cent higher with June
at 71.15 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .05 cent lower to .48
cent higher with May at 76.10 cents a pound; live hogs were .05
cent to .30 cent higher with June at 45.52 cents a pound; frozen
pork bellies were .17 cent lower to .23 cent higher with May at
31.12 cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled mixed on Thursday.
