<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-89 1212EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-TMIFuture 1stLd-Writethru f0522 04-21 0477</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-TMI Future, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0522,0487</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reactor Would Sit Vacant for 30 Years, Then be Dismantled</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Subs thruout to clarify that mothballing would affect damaged
Unit 2, but not operating Unit 1.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Managers of the Three Mile Island nuclear
power plant offered the Nuclear Regulatory Commission a detailed
look at what will happen if the facility's crippled Unit 2 is
mothballed, which the company hopes to do by the end of next year.
   The NRC said during a 90-minute meeting Thursday that it
expected to complete a study on the environmental impact of the
plan and release the assessment in the next few months.
   The plant's Unit 2 reactor was disabled in the nation's worst
commercial nuclear accident on March 31, 1979. The reactor was
allowed to lose the vital cooling water that normally covers it,
causing fuel and other components in the radioactive core to begin
melting.
   The plant's undamaged Unit 1 reactor was not affected by the
1979 accident has been operating since 1985.
   On Thursday, officials of GPU Nuclear, the plant's operator,
provided the NRC with an updated picture of Unit 2's future over
the next 30 years.
   In so-called ``monitored storage,'' the unit 2 reactor building
would be locked up, unneeded systems deactivated, and the reactor
left idle for up to 30 years while radiation decays. The unit would
then be dismantled.
   While insufficient fuel would be present to support a nuclear
chain reaction, relatively high levels of contamination would
remain in the reactor building basement during storage, plant
officials said. Radiation monitoring will be continued, and a
security force will control access.
   The NRC is still studying the environmental impact of the plan,
and Commission Chairman Lando Zech said at the meeting that its
report was due in June. The plan must also pass a separate safety
evaluation, said TMI spokesman Doug Bedell.
   Plant officials originally had hoped to have Unit 2 mothballed
by the end of 1989. But a three-month delay in removing damaged
fuel, combined with changes in the decontamination schedule, has
pushed the beginning of the reactor's storage phase ``toward the
end of 1990, with better than 99 percent of its nuclear fuel
removed,'' GPU Nuclear said.
   GPU Nuclear President Philip Clark told the NRC that the company
had sufficient ``resources, people and money'' to ensure the plant
could safely be placed in storage next year.
   Zech asked the company to formulate as specific a schedule as
possible for ending the cleanup.
   GPU Nuclear said at the meeting the cleanup is expected to be
completed within its $1 billion target. The operator said more than
three-quarters of the 150 tons of damaged fuel and other debris
have been shipped off the site, and the reactor's workforce is to
be trimmed from 960 last year to 250 in 1990.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890421-0239 </DOCNO>
