<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market staged a modest advance today,
resuming the rally that carried it to 18-month highs earlier in the
week.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 8.80 to 2,386.18 by
2 p.m. on Wall Street.
   Gainers outnumbered losers by about 7 to 5 in nationwide trading
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 775 up, 554 down and
557 unchanged.
   The market suffered a temporary setback Thursday when the West
German central bank announced unexpected increases in its official
interest rates.
   That raised fears of downward pressure on the dollar, and of
possible further credit-tightening in this country.
   By today, however, analysts said investors seemed to be taking
the view that the Federal Reserve would wait a while longer to
gauge the effects of the restrictive moves it has already made over
the past year or so.
   Thus, observers noted, the possibility remained open in many
minds that interest rates are close to or at a peak.
   Perkin-Elmer climbed 2\ to 25] in active trading. The company
announced plans to sell some of its operations and pass the
proceeds to shareholders in the form of dividends, stock
repurchases or a combination of the two.
   Syntex rose 1{ to 45~ and Smithkline Beckman | to 63\, on
speculation that either might become a takeover target of F.
Hoffmann-La Roche &amp; Co.
   American Telephone &amp; Telegraph gained { to 34. The company's
report earlier in the week of a 20.7 percent first-quarter earnings
increase was warmly received by investors.
   Navistar dropped [ to 5] on top of a {-point loss Thursday, when
the company said it had lowered its internal earnings projections
for both the current quarter and its full fiscal year.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
.61 to 171.91. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was up .72 at 342.05.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 118.67 million shares with two
hours to go.
