<HEAD>London Shares End Mixed After Rates Hold Steady</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices on London's Stock Exchange closed
narrowly mixed Friday, having recovered from their lowest levels
after a rise in British interest rates failed to materialize.
   A small rise in the value of the pound and early gains on Wall
Street also helped equities rebound from their midday lows.
   However, analysts predicted that interest rate worries in
Britain would persist, following Thursday's increase in interest
rates by West Germany's central bank. As a result, shares would
continue to trade nervously next week, they said.
   ``What the Bundesbank has done has made the market rather
nervous. If sterling comes under pressure, we might have to put up
rates as well,'' said a director at a major British stockbrokerage
firm.
   At the close, the Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index
was down 3.4 points, or 0.2 percent, at 2,061.0.
   The Financial Times 30-share index closed 2.0 points higher at
1,700.5. The Financial Times 500-share index fell 1.19 points to
close at 1,171.74.
   Volume came to 400.7 million shares compared with Thursday's
542.2 million shares.
