<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0276</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soybeans Surge, Grains Advance on Drier Weather Forecasts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices closed sharply higher and
grain futures also advanced Friday on the Chicago Board of Trade as
the weather outlook turned drier for the Midwest and Great Plains.
   Soybean futures also were supported by the slow movement of
Brazilian soybean meal to Europe, a function of a 12-day-old
dockworkers' strike at the Port of Santos, Brazil's largest harbor.
   But weather was the dominant factor and it is certain to remain
the key variable in the markets with corn planting expected to
begin in earnest this weekend in the Midwest.
   Weather forecasts will become even more critical when soybean
planting commences in several more weeks.
   ``Soybeans need more moisture to get started than corn does,''
said Walter Spilka, a grain market analyst with Smith Barney,
Harris Upham &amp; Co. in New York. ``When you see dry forecasts,
you're likely to see a better runup in the soybean market.''
   Predictions for continued dry weather in the Great Plains
bolstered wheat prices. The Kansas wheat crop has already sustained
significant dry-weather damage and without rain, ``there's no doubt
the crop will continue to deteriorate,'' Spilka said.
   At the close, wheat was 4 cents to 5} cents higher with the
contract for delivery in May at $4.15 a bushel; corn was 2\ cents
to 5{ cents higher with May at $2.75 a bushel; oats were 2 cents to
5\ cents higher with May at $2.02 a bushel; soybeans were 4 cents
to 11} cents higher with May at $7.59 a bushel.
</TEXT>
