<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-89 1659EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-McDonnellDouglas     04-21 0335</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-McDonnell Douglas,0347</SECOND>
<HEAD>McDonnell Douglas Experinces Loss in First-Quarter Earnings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   McDonnell Douglas Corp. said Friday that
without $179 million gained because of an accounting change, the
company would have recorded a $10 million loss in first-quarter net
earnings.
   Reduction of the company's deferred tax liability through the
adoption of a new accounting standard had the effect of adding the
$179 million, or $4.68 a share, after taxes, the St. Louis-based
company said.
   Excluding that benefit, the company reported a loss in net
earnings for the quarter of $10 million, or 25 cents a share, on
revenue of $3.4 billion, compared with net earnings of $51 million,
or $1.33 a share, on revenue of $3.31 billion for the same period
last year.
   Earnings were depressed by an operating loss of $66 million in
the company's transport aircraft segment and a special provision
for interest on taxes related to a dispute with the Internal
Revenue Service over the timing of tax obligations, the company
said.
   In addition, the company said there was a 15 percent reduction
in operating earnings from combat aircraft.
   Contributing to the operating loss in transport aircraft was a
major reorganization of the Douglas Aircraft Co. initiated in the
first quarter to provide long-term improvements in operations. The
transition caused some disruption and ineffeciences, the company
said.
   Operating earnings in the combat aircraft segment declined as a
result of decreased performance in the manufacturing process, the
company said.
   Total interest expense in the aerospace and information systems
segments increased from $41 million in the first quarter of last
year to $99 million this year.
   The company said that while that was due partly to higher
interest rates and increased corporate borrowings, a large portion
of it related to a special provision for resolving tax issues.
   The corporation and the IRS have disagreed over the completion
dates of long-term contracts. Settlement with the IRS may result in
interest and previously deferred taxes being paid to the IRS, the
company said.
</TEXT>
