<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-89 1625EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-ChannelOne Bjt   04-21 0702</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Channel One, Bjt,0721</SECOND>
<HEAD>Channel One School News Show Test Ends with Future Undecided</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Whittle Communications LP sent out the last of
its experimental television news shows for teens on Friday but
won't decide until mid-summer if the commercially-sponsored project
passed or failed its test.
   The Channel One news program, a daily 12-minute newscast with
two minutes of product advertising per show, has been beamed by
satellite over the past seven weeks to six middle and high schools.
   The program has proven popular with many of the teachers,
principals and students in the six test schools. But it has drawn
criticism from some national education groups who object to
permitting paid pitches for shampoo, candy bars, sneakers and jeans
in the classroom.
   ``We thought a lot of the program,'' said Stan Jasinskas,
principal at Eisenhower Middle School in Kansas City, Kan., one of
the test schools. ``We think it probably ought to be continued
nationally.''
   Ed Winter, the Whittle partner in charge of the Channel One
project, said it may take two months or more to evaluate results of
the test and if it is feasible to expand the program nationally. He
expects a decision by mid-summer.
   The project's initial goal was to make the program and the
equipment available to as many as 10,000 schools in the fall of
1990. If it does that, Channel One would be Knoxville, Tenn.-based
Whittle Communications' largest single business.
   The speciality magazine and sponsored poster publisher had
revenue of about $150 million last year and estimates Channel One
could produce $100 million in revenue on its own.
   The Channel One test began on March 6 at Eisenhower Middle
School and at high schools in Knoxville, Tenn.; Cincinnati;
Billerica, Mass.; Detroit and Cerritos, Calif.
   In addition to 25 daily shows with advertising, Whittle provided
four-page course guides for teachers, a commercial-free live
broadcast of a space shuttle launch and several Public Broadcasting
System programs.
   In addition to criticism over subjecting students to product
ads, some educators have faulted the way Channel One is presented.
   Scott Thomson, executive director of the National Association of
Secondary School Principals, said research has indicated the best
way to use television as a teaching aid is to use it selectively as
part of a lesson.
   But he said Channel One fails to do that because it is beamed
schoolwide at a regular time of the day without regard to whether
the program fits in with whatever class may follow.
   Thomson said he is not surprised that the administrators at the
test schools speak highly of the program. ``You can't expect them
to say `I've made a poor professional judgment','' he said.
   The test schools get to keep the equipment Whittle installed no
matter what happens with the project. Schools who sign up if it
goes national would keep the equipment only as long as they showed
the program regularly.
   Whittle isn't the only company providing television programming
for schools, and educators expect that competing daily services
will emerge.
   Turner Broadcasting System Inc.'s Cable News Network is already
involved in a venture with the National School Boards Association
that is making a weekly news wrapup show available to schools.
   Under the service called News Access, about 200 schools are
paying fees ranging from $200 to $600 a year for the rights to
replay in class all or parts of CNN's Week in Review program that
airs on Sundays.
   As part of that project, the schools get a 40-page classroom
guide via computer with tips on how the show can be used to
complement lessons in science, social studies, mathematics,
language or the arts.
   One of the differences between the services, however, is that
Whittle is providing about $50,000 in television sets, video
recorders and satellite dishes to each of the participating schools
while the schools subscribing to News Access must provide their own
equipment.
   Another is that Whittle requires that schools air its daily news
program to the entire student body each school day, while teachers
using the weekly News Access program are free to use segments in
class and are not bound to show any of it to their students.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
