<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     04-21 0538</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0556</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Higher In Domestic Dealings; Gold Prices Mixed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede: LONDON</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar recovered from shocks over foreign
interest rate hikes to close higher in domestic dealings Friday
after putting in a mixed performance overseas.
   Gold prices slipped after rising overseas. Republic National
Bank of New York said gold was bid at $384.25 an ounce as of 4 p.m.
EDT, down $1 from late Thursday's bid.
   Although currency markets calmed down somewhat after the West
German central bank's surprise 0.5 percent hike in the discount
rate on Thursday, the dollar seesawed because of the uncertain fate
of an investment tax overseas.
   Traders said the market was battered by unconfirmed reports that
West Germany was about to eliminate its controversial withholding
tax on interest income.
   West Germany's finance minister, Theo Waigel, is trying to gain
enough political support to repeal or suspend the measure. Without
the tax, West German mark-denominated investments would become
increasingly attractive.
   Unconfirmed reports that the tax was to be eliminated ``took the
dollar down,'' said Bob Morrissey, a senior trader at the Bank of
Boston. Then, however, the reports were reversed.
   ``Had the statement not been rescinded, the dollar would have
traded much lower,'' Morrissey said.
   Traders also were concerned ``by what the market perceives as
the eventual rise in Japanese and British interest rates,'' said
Stephen Flanagan, a vice president at Manufacturers Hanover Trust
Co.
   Traders are looking to a batch of fresh economic statistics
scheduled to be released next week for an indication as to whether
the Federal Reserve will be prompted to raise interest rates, thus
offsetting the week's rate increases in Europe.
   Earlier in Tokyo, the dollar closed at 131.45 Japanese yen, down
from 132.28. In London late Friday the dollar traded lower at
131.35 yen. In New York, the dollar rose to 131.48 yen, from 131.15
yen on Thursday.
   In London, one British pound cost $1.7160 late Friday, more
expensive for buyers than late Thursday's $1.7115. In New York, one
pound cost $1.7135, cheaper than $1.7167 on Thursday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late
Thursday, included: 1.8485 West German marks, up from 1.8478;
1.6305 Swiss francs, up from 1.6295; 6.2720 French francs, up from
6.2675; 1,357.50 Italian lire, down from 1,359.00, and 1.1869
Canadian dollars, up from 1.1839.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with Thursday
included: 1.8460 West German marks, up from 1.8450; 1.6320 Swiss
francs, up from 1.6275; 6.2625 French francs, down from 6.2925;
2.0830 Dutch guilders, down from 2.0990; 1,357.50 Italian lire,
down from 1,361.50; and, 1.1850 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1840.
   Gold bullion prices were mixed. The late bid price of gold in
London, the major European metals market, was $384.40 a troy ounce,
up from $383.25. The late bid price in Zurich was $384.15, up from
$382.70. Earlier in Hong Kong, gold closed at $385.45 bid, up from
$383.95.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for current
delivery slipped to $384.90 a troy ounce, from Thursday's $385.60.
   Silver bullion traded late in London at a bid $5.78 a troy
ounce, up from $5.76. On New York's Comex, silver bullion for
current delivery fell to $5.756 an ounce, from $5.776 on Thursday.
</TEXT>
