<FIRST>r f AM-C&amp;S-Chapman     04-21 0405</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-C&amp;S-Chapman,0422</SECOND>
<HEAD>C&amp;S Executive Promoted After Offer Of New Post In Takeover Bid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Citizens &amp; Southern Corp. President Hugh Chapman,
who has been offered a high level position as part of NCNB Inc.'s
unsolicited bid to acquire the bank, was named Friday as chief
operating officer of C&amp;S.
   However, a C&amp;S spokesman said the move had no connection to
NCNB's offer.
   ``This has been in the works a long time. We just announced it
at this time,'' said C&amp;S spokesman Scott Scredon.
   Chapman will retain his position of president in the newly
created job, and will head the Atlanta-based bank's policy
committee, a group of senior managers who guide the company.
   ``Hugh will be responsible for the day-to-day operation of C&amp;S
when I am not available,'' said C&amp;S Chairman Bennett A. Brown.
``All who know Hugh share my respect for his judgment and my
confidence in his leadership abilities.''
   C&amp;S has been targeted by Charlotte, N.C.-based NCNB in a $2.4
billion takeover bid. NCNB's stock transfer offer has been rejected
by the C&amp;S board, which said it was inadequate and would face stiff
regulatory hurdles.
   NCNB Chairman Hugh L. McColl Jr., in a letter to Brown April 12,
addressed those objections and outlined what he considered the
benefits of the proposal. McColl offered Brown the chairmanship of
the combined company and said Chapman would have a key role.
   ``Hugh Chapman will become one of the most senior executives and
an important member of the combined management team,'' McColl wrote.
   C&amp;S officials have refused to meet with NCNB to discuss the bid.
NCNB, which has maintained its offer remains on the table, is
scheduled to hold its annual meeting Wednesday in Charlotte.
   Scredon said Chapman's promotion was prompted by Brown's recent
election as president of the Association of Reserve City Bankers,
an industry organization. That position will require Brown to make
frequent trips to Washington, he said.
   ``We don't want the machine to get bogged down. When he is gone,
we don't want things to grind to a halt,'' Scredon said.
   ``Bennett is still clearly the head man,'' Scredon added.
   Chapman joined C&amp;S Corp. as president in 1986. He previously was
chairman and chief executive officer of C&amp;S South Carolina, a
company he joined in 1958.
   As president, Chapman's duties have included all of C&amp;S'
financial areas, as well as strategic planning, marketing and
government relations.
</TEXT>
