<FIRST>u f AM-Eastern-Fares     04-21 0298</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern-Fares,0308</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eastern Says New Bargain Fares Attracting Customers; Agents Skeptical</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Eastern</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new round of bargain fares between some of the
few cities still served by strike-crippled Eastern Airlines has
drawn a tremendous response, the company said Friday.
   But some Miami area travel agents didn't share the carrier's
enthusiasm.
   The fares announced Wednesday range from $29 to $99 for one-way
flights from Miami to New York, Atlanta, Puerto Rico, Haiti and the
Bahamas. A flight from Miami to New York, for example, would cost
$79 one way and $158 round trip.
   Eastern said Thursday it would restore other pre-strike routes
May 1 and offer cheap one-way fares along with them: Miami-Orlando
for $29, Atlanta-New York and Atlanta-Washington for $59, and
Atlanta-San Juan, Puerto Rico, for $119.
   ``The response to these new fares has been tremendous,'' George
Brennan, Eastern's vice president for marketing, said Friday. He
said Thursday's ticket sales of 23,000 ``tripled those sold on the
previous high booking day since the strike began March 4.''
   But Joyce Curtis, who said the Up Up and Away travel agency she
manages in Fort Lauderdale, Fla., once handled nearly $800,000 a
year in Eastern ticket sales, said the bargain rates had attracted
only two customers by Friday afternoon.
   ``And Eastern was once our preferred carrier,'' she said.
   Some travel agents, who had customers stuck with worthless
tickets after pilots and flight attendants joined striking
Machinists on March 4 to virtually shut down the Miami-based
airline, remain so disgruntled that they won't sell Eastern tickets
at any price.
   ``We're not booking Eastern right now,'' said Jan Lobota,
assistant manager of Hollywood Travel's office in West Palm Beach,
Fla. ``It's not to our benefit to sell Eastern tickets now. We
don't want the same mistake twice.''
</TEXT>
