<FIRST>u f AM-InterestRates Bjt   04-21 0506</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Interest Rates, Bjt,0524</SECOND>
<HEAD>Markets Recover After Scare Over High Interest Rates</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Financial markets staged a powerful comeback
Friday from a brief scare that an interest rate increase in West
Germany would trigger a spiral of rising rates around the world.
   Stock prices leaped in late trading and bonds rose after
Thursday's modest sell-off, which came after West Germany announced
it would raise key interest rates to stave off inflation.
   The fear Thursday was that West Germany's action could prompt
other nations to raise their own rates in order to keep global
money from flowing out of their currencies.
   That concern eased Friday as investors concluded that the
Federal Reserve would not necessarily push U.S. interest rates
higher.
   ``I think what the markets are telling us is that this was a
temporary scare and the underlying tone of the markets is
constructive,'' said Michael Metz, a managing director and
investment strategist at Oppenheimer &amp; Co.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials jumped 32.08 to 2,409.46
after having fallen 9.53 points on Thursday.
   The rise, accelerated by program trading, brought the average to
its highest point since the October 1987 crash.
   In the credit market, the yield on the Treasury's benchmark
30-year bond dipped back below 9 percent, which it had exceeded
Thursday.
   West Germany is historically fearful of inflation, and its moves
to dampen price increases by tightening the screws on its own
economy have often sent ripples through the world economy.
   Indeed, the Netherlands, Austria and Denmark followed the
Germans Thursday in raising rates, keeping their nations'
securities attractive to investors.
   But the Federal Reserve has apparently concluded that it does
not need to raise U.S. rates, even if the failure to do so causes
money to flow abroad and the dollar to fall, Metz said.
   The Fed places more importance on the state of the U.S. economy
than on the dollar's level and has apparently concluded that the
level of U.S. inflation does not justify higher rates, he said.
   Some investment analysts say the West Germans are right to be
vigilant and that the United States could be in for a crisis if it
does not squelch inflation now.
   ``We're riding along on a wave of liquidity-inspired euphoria,''
said Samuel Thorne Jr., managing director for fixed-income
portfolio management at Scudder, Stevens &amp; Clark Inc. in Boston.
   ``We're going to get a squall,'' he said.
   Although West Germany's inflation rate remains low by world
standards _ 3 percent year-over-year at the consumer level in the
latest tally _ the nation's factory usage rate is at a 16-year high
and economic growth is running above normal.
   Those factors prompted Thursday's announcement of increases in
the German central bank lending rates, said Nicholas Sargen, an
international economist at Salomon Brothers Inc. in New York.
   Still, the increases surprised the financial markets because
Karl Otto Poehl, president of the West German central bank, had
said recently that interest rates were high enough to discourage
inflation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
