<FIRST>u f AM-ChannelOne-Eisenhower     04-21 0428</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Channel One-Eisenhower,0445</SECOND>
<HEAD>Experimental TV Program In KC School Called Successful</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Channel One, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By AMANDA DAVIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An experimental news program for
children was hailed as a success Friday by students and the
principal at one of six schools nationwide that tested the show.
   ``We have been tremendously pleased with our participation in
the program,'' said Stan Jasinskas, principal at Eisenhower Middle
School. ``We have seen many positive results.''
   Eisenhower was one of the schools that watched Channel One, a
12-minute news program complete with commercials. The $5 million
program debuted in the six schools in March.
   The show resembled a network news program but with young
anchors, flashy graphics and a teenage perspective on the news.
   The commercials raised the ire of some children's advocates, who
feared advertisers would take advantage of children.
   But Ottice Hall, a seventh-grade student at Eisenhower, said he
enjoyed watching the programs at school.
   ``I liked it because they had all these fun things to watch,''
he said. ``And I liked the commercials. They had some new ones.''
   Ottice said he would like to keep ``Channel One.''
   ``It's fun to watch tv at school. I don't watch the news at
home,'' he said.
   Jasinskas said the program provided students with a valuable
educational lesson.
   Channel One featured the environment in a five-part series one
week, for instance, and some students wrote to fast-food
restaurants, soft drink producers and city councilmen to express
their concern about chemicals and recycling.
   ``Some kids got written responses from the mayor and from these
corporations,'' Jasinskas said. ``What happened goes beyond content
knowledge. The kids have picked up an appreciation for how the
system works. Whether just writing that letter is enough to bring
about a change, I can't say. But I know that the experience has
brought about a change in the kids.''
   The experiment exposed the children to news they otherwise would
not have seen, the principal said.
   ``With the lifestyles that kids have with school and homework
and church and some with jobs, they are not going to be regular
consumers of the news,'' he said. ```Channel One' has brought to
those kids consistent access not only to events but to issues.''
   If Jasinskas was making decisions for only one school instead of
a multi-building district, he said he would keep the program.
   ``I might find that I would want to tailor it a bit more to our
needs, but overall, I am very pleased. It has been a tremendously
valuable program,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
