<FIRST>r f AM-Ford-Smoking     04-21 0154</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ford-Smoking,0161</SECOND>
<HEAD>Automaker Announces New Smoking Restrictions In U.S. Facilities</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DEARBORN, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford Motor Co. on Friday announced new
restrictions on smoking in its U.S. facilities.
   Effective June 1, smoking will be prohibited in conference
rooms, training rooms, classrooms and auditoriums. The ban will be
expanded Jan. 1, 1990 to include all enclosed offices and open
office areas, the No.2 automaker said in a statement.
   The restrictions will not apply to smoking in open factory and
garage areas within certain guidelines, the statement said.
   Ford also said it would expand stop-smoking services and
programs for both salary and hourly employees interested in
quitting smoking.
   Ford previously had designated smoking and non-smoking areas in
cafeterias while smoking was prohibited in some work areas because
of safety, Ford spokesman Dick Routh said.
   ``It's a bold step forward but reflects a growing feeling among
employees that they want a healthier work environment,'' Routh said.
</TEXT>
