<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-89 1750EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     04-21 0682</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0704</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Surge As Weather Forecasts Turn Drier</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices rose strongly Friday on the
Chicago Board of Trade after some private meteorologists reduced
the amount of rain in their forecasts for early next week in the
Midwest and Great Plains.
   On other markets, gold and silver futures retreated; livestock
and meat were higher and energy futures were mixed.
   In Chicago, wheat settled 4 cents to 5\ cents higher with the
contract for delivery in May at $4.14{ a bushel; corn was 2{ cents
to 5{ cents higher with May at $2.75\ a bushel; oats were 4 cents
to 5} cents higher with May at $2.02{ a bushel; soybeans were 4
cents to 12} cents higher with May at $7.60 a bushel.
   The sharp gains in the soybean and corn markets reflected
concerns about low soil moisture in Iowa, northwestern Illinois and
other areas of the Corn Belt still struggling to recover from last
year's drought.
   ``There's just a lot of nervousness that we're going to have a
repeat of last year,'' said James Candor, a meteorologist with
Accu-Weather Inc., a private forecasting firm in State College, Pa.
   Candor said Accu-Weather revised its forecast Friday toward the
dry end of the scale, predicting that a third of the Midwestern
croplands would receive about a half-inch of rain on Sunday or
Monday. On Thursday, Accu-Weather had predicted coverage of 40
percent to 50 percent.
   Weekend rain could hamper corn planting, though, and it would
not necessarily be beneficial for corn seedlings, which prefer
warm, dry conditions early in their growth cycle.
   ``Soybeans need more moisture to get started than corn does,''
said Walter Spilka, a grain market analyst with Smith Barney,
Harris Upham &amp; Co. in New York. ``When you see dry forecasts,
you're likely to see a better runup in the soybean market.''
   Predictions for continued dry weather in the Great Plains
bolstered wheat prices.
   Gold and silver futures prices fell slightly on New York's
Commodity Exchange in response to the dollar's gains against other
major currencies.
   Gold settled 70 cents to $1.20 lower with June at $388.20 a troy
ounce; silver was 2 cents to 2.2 cents lower with May at $5.765 a
troy ounce.
   Livestock and meat futures ended mostly higher on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange in light, cautious trading ahead of two
Agriculture Department reports, the quarterly cattle-on-feed report
and the monthly cold-storage report, which were released after the
close of trading.
   In the cattle-on-feed report, the USDA counted 9.68 million head
of cattle on feedlots on April 1 in the 13 largest cattle-producing
states. The tally was 3 percent larger than last year's
first-quarter count and slightly above market expectations, but
probably not by enough to have much impact on Monday's trading,
analysts said.
   In the cold-storage report, the USDA found 133.8 million pounds
of frozen pork bellies on hand at the end of March, the fifth
consecutive month of record supplies. The USDA pegged total pork
supplies at 397.2 million pounds, the largest monthly supply figure
in the past 10 years.
   The numbers were close to market estimates and were not expected
to cause any sharp price movement on Monday.
   Live cattle futures settled .20 cent lower to .45 cent higher
with June at 71.42 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .20 cent to
.50 cent higher with May at 76.17 cents a pound; hogs were .12 cent
to .65 cent higher with June at 45.60 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .30 cent lower to .40 cent higher with May at 31.30
cents a pound.
   Heating-oil futures prices rose sharply on the New York
Mercantile Exchange, leading crude-oil prices higher in quiet,
technically inspired trading. Unleaded gasoline futures finished
narrowly mixed.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 4 cents to 32 cents
higher with June at $21.32 a barrel; heating oil was .95 cent to
1.34 cents higher with May at 53.63 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .49 cent lower to .46 cent higher with May at 74.16
cents a gallon.
</TEXT>
