<FIRST>u f BC-Earns-Computers     04-21 0158</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Computers,0164</SECOND>
<HEAD>Unisys Posts Loss In First Quarter</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Unisys Corp. said Friday it lost money in the first quarter
because of ``transitory factors,'' but the computer maker predicted
a return to profitability in the current quarter and a strong
second half of 1989.
   Unisys said its loss, which it had publicly predicted, was the
result of a transition to a new mainframe computer line and the
resulting start-up costs, interruption in sales and inventory
reduction costs.
   The computer giant, which has headquarters in Blue Bell, Pa.,
and Detroit, said it lost $78.7 million. That is in contrast to a
profit a year earlier of $149.3 million, or 72 cents a share.
Revenue fell about 8 percent to $2.20 billion from $2.37 billion.
   ``Overall, we expect very strong year-over-year gains in revenue
and operating earnings in the second half of 1989,'' W. Michael
Blumenthal, the chairman and chief executive, said in a news
release.
</TEXT>
