<DOCNO> AP890421-0276 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-89 1756EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     04-21 0615</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0635</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Pause After Rapid Runup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JULIA C. MARTINEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Petroleum prices finished mixed Friday, capping
a frantic week in which a North Sea oil platform explosion sent
crude oil to the highest level in more than three years.
   The explosion resulted in a supply shutdown that stopped the
shipment of more than 500,000 barrels a day of Brent crude, or
about 30 percent of total North Sea Brent oil production, Britain
Energy Minister Cecil Parkinson said.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the June contract for West
Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S. crude oil, finished
4 cents higher at $21.32 a barrel. Contracts for delivery after
June rose as much as 41 cents.
   The $2.04 surge in the May contract on Thursday set a record for
the highest one-day rise since the exchange started trading crude
oil futures in March 1983, said John Santana, NYME statistical
analyst. The contract closed at $24.65, the highest level since
Jan. 15, 1986, when it reached $25.15.
   In the four days before the contract expired on Thursday the
contract rose more than $3, or about 16 percent.
   Among refined products traded on the exchange Friday, unleaded
gasoline for May delivery fell 0.41 cent to 74.16 cents a gallon,
while the June contract was down 0.18 cent to 71.18 cents. Other
contract months finished higher.
   May heating oil, meanwhile, rose 1.34 cent to 53.63 cents a
gallon, with other contract months also registering gains.
   There was no word late Friday on when the Brent pipeline system
would return to normal. Officials of Shell U.K., the unit of the
Royal Dutch-Shell Group that operates the platform and the pipeline
system, indicated there might be a partial resumption of about
100,000 barrels a day starting Monday.
   British officials had indicated earlier in the week that the
closure could last up to four weeks.
   Analysts said the timing of the North Sea accident on Tuesday
was the biggest reason for rising prices, coming less than four
weeks after the Alaskan oil tanker spill that temporarily cut the
flow of oil to refineries and adding to concerns about tight
supplies of gasoline for the summer.
   ``We're heading into the driving season, only a month from
Memorial Day,'' said Andrew Lebow, senior broker with E.D.&amp; F. Man
International Futures Inc. ``This is when refiners want to start
increasing production of gasoline. They want to make sure they have
enough crude to run their refineries at full capacity.''
   Light North Sea Brent crude is in high demand because it is more
easily refined into gasoline. Analysts said there is plenty of
crude in storage to compensate for the shortfall if the North Sea
shutdown is not prolonged.
   ``The stoppage in the North Sea could be serious and for a long
time, but there is enough OPEC and non-OPEC crude to make up the
difference in the short-term,'' said James Steel, energy analyst
with Refco Inc.
   Steel said the North Sea accident is not likely to boost
consumer prices, barring a prolonged shutdown.
   ``Not because of this, but I think gasoline prices will go up
for other reasons,'' Steel said.
   Those include the change to higher octane gasoline required by
the Environmental Protection Agency and the reduction in refinery
capacity. The same amount of crude oil makes a smaller amount of
gasoline. Also, demand for gasoline has risen dramatically over the
last year while the refinery capacity has declined as many
antiquated refineries closed down.
   U.S. retail gasoline prices have risen more than 10 cents a
gallon since the Alaskan spill, based on a combination of factors,
including expectations of possible short supplies.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890421-0277 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-89 1759EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Bonds     04-21 0454</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bonds,0474</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bond Prices Recover</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Interest Rates, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bond prices climbed back Friday after investors
concluded that other major central banks were not on the verge of
raising interest rates to match Thursday's increases by West
Germany.
   The Treasury's benchmark 30-year bond rose 11-32 point, or $3.44
per $1,000 face amount. Its yield, which moves in the opposite
direction from its price, slipped to 8.98 percent from 9.01 percent
late Thursday.
   Bond prices fell Thursday in the United States after the West
German central bank unexpectedly raised two of its key lending
rates.
   Traders worried that other nations would match the German
increases to keep global investors from pulling money out of their
currencies in search of higher yields. Higher rates depress prices
of existing fixed-income securities.
   The bond market recovered when there was no indication of
imminent credit-tightening by the Japanese, U.S. or British central
banks.
   ``The feeling now is maybe the Fed doesn't have to tag along,''
said Michael Metz, a managing director and investment strategist at
Oppenheimer &amp; Co.
   In the secondary market for Treasury securities, prices of
short-term governments were unchanged to 3-16 point higher,
intermediate maturities rose \ point and long-term issues were up
as much as 11-32 point, according to Telerate Inc., the financial
information service.
   The movement of a point is equivalent to a change of $10 in the
price of a bond with a $1,000 face value.
   The Shearson Lehman Hutton Daily Treasury Bond Index, which
measures price movements on all outstanding Treasury issues with
maturities of a year or longer, rose 2.34 to 1,128.79.
   In corporate trading, industrials edged up. Moody's Investment
Grade Corporate Bond Index, which measures total return on a
portfolio of 80 corporate bonds with maturities of five years or
longer, rose 0.92 to 302.32.
   In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively
traded municipal bonds rose 1-16 point. The average yield to
maturity fell to 7.64 percent from 7.65 percent late Thursday.
   Yields on three-month Treasury bills remained at 8.93 percent as
the discount stood unchanged at 8.63 percent. Yields on six-month
bills rose to 9.09 percent as the discount jumped 10 basis points
to 8.59 percent. Yields on one-year bills fell to 9.32 percent as
the discount lost 1 basis point to 8.61 percent.
   A basis point is one-hundredth of a percentage point. The yield
is the annualized return on an investment in a Treasury bill. The
discount is the percentage that bills are selling below the face
value, which is paid at maturity.
   The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between
banks, traded at 913-16 percent, down from 9~ percent late Thursday.
</TEXT>
