<FIRST>r f AM-Earns-Media     04-21 0248</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earns-Media,0258</SECOND>
<HEAD>Media General Profit Edges Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Media General Inc. said Friday its
first-quarter profit edged up 2.6 percent mainly because of a
one-time gain resulting from the sale of a newsprint mill.
   Net income rose to $11.9 million, or 46 cents per share, in the
three months ended March 31 compared with $11.5 million, or 40
cents per share, in the same period in 1988.
   The latest results include an after-tax gain of $5.7 million, or
22 cents per share, which Media General said resulted from the
federal income tax accounting treatment of the sale of its Pomona,
Calif., newsprint mill.
   First-quarter revenues fell 19.9 percent to $149.3 million from
$186 million last year.
   James S. Evans, president and chief executive officer of Media
General, said he expected financial results for the next two years
won't likely reach the highs set in 1987.
   In the latest quarter, newspaper profits fell 31.6 percent due
to a continuing slide in national and retail advertising and
ongoing competitive pressure in the Tampa-St. Petersburg, Fla.
market, where Media General's Tampa Tribune is competing with the
St. Petersburg Times.
   Newsprint profits fell nearly 41 percent because of heavy price
discounting and the loss of income from the Pomona mill.
   But broadcast and cable profits nearly doubled from a year ago,
the company said, aided by growth at its Fairfax, Va., cable
operation and the absence of the company's broadcast services unit
that was sold late last year.
</TEXT>
