<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-89 0122EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-TankerSpill 1stLd-Writethru f0262 04-21 0876</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tanker Spill, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0262,0897</SECOND>
<HEAD>Interior Secretary Visits Oil Spill</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 11 grafs to UPDATE with Lujan visit, quotes, other
comment; UPDATES deployment of Soviet skimmer; picks up 7th graf pvs: `A
poll ...; DELETES outdated grafs 10-11 pvs, `Lujan planned ...'. Also moved
on general news wires.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto VDX3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL JENKINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VALDEZ, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interior Secretary Manuel Lujan toured an
oily Alaska beach Thursday but said it was ``too early'' to draw
conclusions, but a congressman with him said it was clear Exxon and
the Coast Guard both were ``covering their rear ends.''
   The visitors from Washington, D.C., accompanied by U.S. Rep. Don
Young, R-Alaska, traveled to Naked Island where workers turned
firehoses on oil-covered rocks to wash the sludge back into Prince
William Sound where it was sucked up by a waiting skimmer.
   ``It looks like it will be a big job to clean it up,'' Lujan
told reporters who caught up with him after he eluded the news
media in Valdez.
   ``I was expecting something like this. I'd read about it and
seen it on TV, and this doesn't surprise me. It's too early for me
to say what I'll tell the president,'' Lujan said.
   U.S. Rep. Curt Weldon, R-Pa., a member of the Merchant Marine &amp;
Fisheries committee, said he had no trouble drawing conclusions
after separate briefings in Valdez by the Coast Guard and Exxon
officials.
   ``There were a lot of people covering their rear ends,'' Weldon
said. ``We got briefings by the Coast Guard and Exxon. They were
completely, diametrically opposite.''
   Lujan and his entourage divided their day between Valdez and
Naked Island, where the Exxon Valdez was towed for repairs after
running aground March 24, rupturing its tanks and spilling 10.1
million gallons of oil into Prince William Sound.
   On Friday, he will visit the rich fishing ports of Homer and
Kodiak, both threatened by runaway oil slicks.
   The U.S. Fish &amp; Wildlife Service already has tallied more than
2,000 dead birds and several hundred dead sea otters. Biologists
say the death toll certainly is many times higher, but the
remoteness and inaccessibility of Prince William Sound make an
accurate count impossible.
   A giant Soviet oil skimmer went to work Thursday along the Kenai
Peninsula, raising the hopes of Coast Guard officials who had no
skimmers capable of gathering floating oil on the high seas.
   Coast Guard Lt. Gary Stock in Anchorage said the 425-foot
skimmer Vaidogubsky spent most of the day getting in place and
testing its booms at the mouth of Resurrection Bay, where streamers
of oil that escaped into the Gulf of Alaska were being scattered by
strong wind and currents.
   From there, the skimmer was expected to move along the hard-hit
southern edge of the Kenai Peninsula, including the Kenai Fjords
National Park. State officials said oil up to six inches deep has
been reported on beaches around Gore Point, about 90 miles
southwest of Seward.
   A poll released Thursday showed a 21 percentage point drop in
the number of people who believe Bush is doing a good job in
handling environmental matters. And the administration's response
to the spill was lambasted at a Senate subcommittee hearing this
week.
   Transportation Secretary Samuel Skinner came to Alaska on Bush's
behalf a week after the spill and said he was generally satisfied
with Exxon's response. But Skinner took a much tougher stance when
he testified before the Senate this week.
   Describing the oil industry's contingency spill response plan,
Skinner said: ``On the scale of one to 10, it was a zero.''
   The big Soviet skimmer ship was called in because the small
boats available in Alaska can handle seas only to about 5 feet.
Seas in the Gulf of Alaska recently have run as high as 12 feet.
   Bigger skimmers weren't built because cleanup contingency
planners didn't expect oil to get outside Prince William Sound,
which is largely protected from rough waves by a series of islands.
   The Vaidogubsky is the world's largest oil-skimming vessel. It
is owned by the Far Eastern Sea Oil and Gas Deep-drilling
Organization, a government-owned enterprise. The ship can pick up
800 cubic meters of sludge per hour with booms and two pumps.
   The Soviet ship was working in conjunction with the U.S. Coast
Guard, but state officials relinquished command to Exxon of a fleet
of more than 300 other vessels engaged in the cleanup. They said
the move was to improve coordination.
   Jim Hayden of the state Department of Environmental Conservation
said monitors will be placed on larger vessels to make sure Exxon's
claims of oil recovered aren't exaggerated and the number of dead
animals isn't undercounted.
   State Environmental Conservation Commissioner Dennis Kelso said
Exxon claims to have recovered 13 percent of the 10.1 million
gallons spilled. But he said the figure probably includes seawater
sucked up with the oil.
   The oil has gotten progressively more difficult to clean up as
it congeals from the effects on wind and water. Two Coast Guard
skimmers were knocked out of action when the sludge fouled their
pumps.
   Exxon says the recovered oil will be mixed with fresh North
Slope crude and taken to West Coast refineries to be turned into
heating oil and asphalt.
</TEXT>
