<FIRST>u f AM-Japan-Markets 1stLd-Writethru f0304 04-21 0421</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0304,0433</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar, Share Prices Lower</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with morning Nikkei, comments</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar was lower against the Japanese yen
at midday Friday, while share prices fell on the Tokyo Stock
Exchange in morning trading.
   The dollar, which started trading at 131.35 yen, down 0.93 yen
from Thursday's 132.28-yen finish, was quoted at 131.65 yen by late
morning. It moved in a range of 131.30-131.75 yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which lost
178.68 points the previous day, shed another 79.53 points, or 0.24
percent, to finish morning trading at 33,105.62.
   The index lost 354.51 points earlier mainly due to interest rate
hikes in West Germany and European nations and higher oil prices,
but it made up some losses toward the end of the morning session
when Salomon Brothers (Ltd.) bought 15,000 shares of each of the
225 key issues, said Satoru Nagayoshi of New Japan Securities in
Tokyo.
   West Germany's central bank raised interest rates, including its
official discount rate, by half a percentage point to 4.5 percent,
effective Friday, to stem inflation, while similar moves were taken
by other central banks in the Netherlands, Austria and Denmark.
   The securities company bought issues soon after the index's
early morning plunge to pick up cheaper issues, Nagayoshi said.
   But a majority of market participants were reluctant to buy
ahead of the weekend, he added.
   On the currency exchange, traders said the dollar's low opening
followed its slide on overseas markets after a round of interest
rate hikes by the European countries. In New York, the currency
closed at 131.13 yen overnight.
   After opening lower, the dollar edged up as speculative
investors and export companies bought dollars for their payments,
said a trader with a Japanese commercial bank, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
   Japanese Finance Minister Tatsuo Murayama said early Friday that
he saw no need to raise the country's discount rate.
   Murayama, speaking at a press conference following a regular
Cabinet meeting, said: ``I don't see any need (right now) for a
change in credit conditions.''
   ``We don't want to go against business trends,'' Murayama said,
adding that prices and other business conditions are ``stable,''
although he admitted concerns over inflation have grown recently.
   The minister also noted that the current yen-dollar exchange
rate ``isn't that much to worry about,'' but that its impact on
prices is important or bears ``caution.'' He was referring to the
effects of a relatively weak yen in undermining domestic price
stability.
</TEXT>
