<FIRST>u f AM-Mexico-Debt     04-21 0218</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico-Debt,0228</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mexico Asks Extension on $1.175 Billion in Principal Payments</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government of Mexico asked Friday for an
extension on $1.175 billion in principal payments due over the next
year on commercial bank loans while it tries to negotiate a
broadly-based financial package.
   The announcement came as officials from Mexico continued talks
begun Wednesday with a bank group in an effort to develop a new
debt repayment plan.
   Mexico owes both commercial banks and government lenders about
$107 billion, making it the developing world's second-largest
debtor behind Brazil, which owes $121 billion.
   President Carlos Salinas de Gortari wants to reduce the burden
of Mexico's foreign debt and keep more money inside the country for
economic investment.
   The current talks involve only the portion of Mexico's total
debt owed to commercial banks.
   Angel Gurria, deputy secretary of Mexico's ministry of finance,
and William R. Rhodes, co-chairman of the Bank Advisory Committee,
said the interim extension request was made in a telex being sent
Friday to Mexico's commercial bank creditors.
   The Bank Advisory Committee endorsed the request.
   The government is asking for an extension until the second
quarter of 1990 principal payments totalling $1.175 billion that
are due starting July 1 through March 31, 1990. The payments
involve agreements reached in 1983 and 1984.
</TEXT>
