<FIRST>u f AM-Perkin-Elmer 1stLd-Writethru   04-21 0258</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Perkin-Elmer, 1st Ld-Writethru,0267</SECOND>
<HEAD>Perkin-Elmer to Sell its Semiconductor Equipment Business</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES with figures on profitability in fiscal 1988.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORWALK, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Perkin-Elmer Corp. announced Friday it
intended to sell off its business of making equipment for
semiconductor manufacturers, which has been marginally profitable
and has lost world market share.
   Reflecting the slippage of the U.S. chip industry overall,
Perkin-Elmer ranked as the world's eighth-largest equipment
supplier last year, down from second in 1979.
   The company said the business had operating income of $3.2
million on revenue of $199.6 million in the fiscal year ended July
31, 1988.
   Perkin-Elmer said it also would sell its West German aerospace
unit and its government systems unit and distribute the proceeds
among shareholders through increased dividends or stock repurchase
plans.
   The West German unit had operating income of $32.2 million on
revenue of $162.7 million last fiscal year, while the government
systems business had operating income of $13.6 million on revenue
of $145 million.
   The sales will allow the company to focus more attention on its
scientific instrument and materials technology businesses, it said.
   No buyers have yet been identified for the three units to be
sold off. Goldman, Sachs &amp; Co., the New York investment-banking
house, is advising Perkin-Elmer on the restructuring.
   Horace G. McDonell, chairman and chief executive officer of
Perkin-Elmer, said the restructuring will direct ``management
attention and financial resources to its core businesses.''
   McDonnell said the move will make Perkin-Elmer a ``streamlined
competitor'' in the manufacture of sophisticated scientific
instruments and related materials technology.
</TEXT>
